after receiving a flood of angry phone calls, the israeli embassy said friday that four israeli soldiers shown on television broadcasts beating two bound palestinan youths will face court-martial
a cbs-tv segment broadcast earlier friday on british television showed the soldiers in the occupied west bank kicking the youths in the head and chest before picking up rocks and smashing them down on arms and legs in an effort to break limbs
the embassy said the soldiers involved were detained by military police, who were investigating the thursday incident in nablus
the soldiers would be subject to court-martial and if found guilty would be sent to a military jail, said the embassy
it is being treated very seriously. but we are satisfied that this sort of thing is not going on all over the place every day,'' said an embassy spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity
there has been much reaction from the british public. we have had many calls. but people can be assured that at least the wheels of justice will run their course.''
earlier, the israeli ambassador in london, yehuda avner, promised a full investigation
interviewed on itn-tv news, he said: ``my reaction is one of shock.''
the beating also was shown on television in denmark and the israeli embassy there was deluged with telephone calls from outraged viewers
the film was shot by bob simon of the american cbs-tv network. at the invitation of the israelis, simon later flew by helicopter to a military camp where he was able to identify the soldiers involved, according to press association, the british domestic news agency.
according to tv news reports, the beating kept up for a full 40 minutes and was in direct contravention of orders issued this week by the army high command that prisoners are not to be beaten if detained after rioting or violence is over
in israel, maj. gen. amram mitzna, the army's west bank commander, said, ``we were shocked and couldn't say a word after we saw this film.''
mitzna said he suspended the unit's deputy commander, a captain, and ordered the two arabs released
rioting broke out in the occupied west bank and gaza strip 11 weeks ago, and scores of arabs have been killed
a foreign office spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity under british procedure, said, ``we have watched the scenes on tv with shock and horror. ..
the action of the ... soldiers is incompatible with the professional standards of the israeli defense forces and shows how far the israeli soldiers have been brutalized by their experience.''
israel's ambassador to the netherlands, zev sufott, made an unusual appearance on nationwide television there friday shortly after the beating scene was shown on dutch television
these are aberrations which, as soon as we hear of them, we go out and pick them (the perpetrators) up,'' sufott said in an interview with the nos-journaal news broadcast
anchorwoman noraly beyer said that by that time, 150 protest calls already had been made to the studio
passengers on a cruise to central america abandoned ship in panama after the crew mutinied, the air conditioning failed and a travel agency's promise of a dream vacation turned into a floating nightmare
the last 90 passengers aboard the cruise ship galaxy disembarked in panama city, panama, on friday without completing the last leg of the trip between acapulco and cancun, mexico, said ron dusek, spokesman for the state attorney general's office
texas attorney general jim mattox filed suit wednesday against golden cruisetours inc. of san antonio, which booked the cruise, two of its subsidiaries and the companies' owners. mattox alleged that customers were bilked of hundreds of thousands of dollars when their trips were canceled and their money was not refunded
the cruise was advertised in 52 newspapers across the country, officials said. a brochure promised passengers a ``friendly, attentive crew'' and the chance to meet new friends
the cruise that began feb. 11 in acapulco fell short of the promises, passengers said
eighty-seven of the 250 passengers refused to go aboard because food was cold and the air conditioning was broken, officials said
the next day, the crew mutinied, according to the state department. more passengers left the ship feb. 18 before the galaxy departed punta renas, costa rica
about 50 mutineers were removed from the ship in costa rica, leading to a dock rally sponsored by a local union which refused to supply replacement labor
passenger sarita anderson described a fight in the ship's lounge during a stop in guatelmala
as we started into the lounge, there was a fight going on,'' mrs. anderson said. ``it was something to do with work schedules.''
the english-speaking honduran crew supervisor was arguing with the ship's staff chief, yelling that the mexican crew members, kitchen help and cabin boys, who had been hired only days earlier in acapulco, were being worked too hard, mrs. anderson said
the two men then began a bloody fight, she said
telephone calls friday to golden cruisetours' office in san antonio went unanswered
the air force dispatched investigators to begin processing damage claims after a fighter jet buzzed a residential area, causing broken windows, fallen roof tiles and minor injuries
a pilot from edwards air force base was participating in a week-long military exercise at george air force base, and was simulating an attack in an f-4 phantom fighter when the damage occurred thursday afternoon, george spokesmen said
he probably didn't know the area and didn't know how close we are to adelanto,'' tech. sgt. jorge caballero. the two bases are more than 50 miles apart in the desert north of los angeles
there were no major injuries, but there were some complaints of roof tiles falling on people and some minor cuts and scrapes,'' caballero said
the pilot's name was not released
a hospital and a nursing firm will split the cost of a $925,000 settlement to a woman who sued, charging malpractice after her stomach blew up like a balloon and her intestine ruptured, her lawyers said
juanita johns, 53, reached the settlement this week with university medical center and medical personnel pool of northeast florida inc., which supplied a private duty nurse for her last year, attorney wayne alford said friday
the suit charged that the nurse, ordered by a doctor to place a tube down mrs. johns' throat to remove intestinal gas, incorrectly hooked up a pump, causing air pressure that blew a hole in the patient's intestine
mrs. johns, who continues to suffer infections and has a disfiguring scar on her abdomen, will receive $150,000 from the hospital and $775,000 from the nursing pool, said alford and fellow attorney john kalil
like olympiads and presidential elections, leap day comes but once in four years. monday's calendar adjustment, like setting a watch back in the fall to get an extra hour, adds a day in the year to keep things in tune with nature
except for owners of some day-date watches, of course, most people don't have to make any actual calendar adjustments. the printers have done that for them by adding a 29th day to february
for folks born on prior february 29ths, it's an eagerly awaited chance to to celebrate that doesn't occur every year. for some aged 80, perhaps having to list only 20 birthdays is a joy
others anxious for adulthood struggle to prove that five birthdays makes them old enough to vote and drive a car. indeed, the problem was crucial for frederick, the hero of gilbert and sullivan's ``pirates of penzance,'' a young man born feb. 29 and indentured until his 21st birthday
for both the fun and frustration of this added day, render unto julius caesar the blame that is his
caesar wanted to make the calendar accurate, and it almost worked
the day is designed to compensate for the fact that calendars count in whole days, 365 or 366 depending on the year, while it takes the earth 365 days, 5 hours, 48 minutes and 46 seconds to get around the sun
adding an extra day every fourth year helped compensate for that difference of about a quarter day, but problems became obvious as the romans' inaccurate calendar got three months out of line with the seasons
so, in 46 b.c., known ever since as the ``year of confusion,'' caesar added 67 days to the calendar to set it right again. and to keep the calendar accurate, he instituted the system of slipping in one more day on feb. 29
that reform, suggested by the roman astronomer sosigenes, became part of what is known as the julian calendar and remained in use for centuries
there was one small problem: sosigenes had done a little too much rounding off,'' explained gail s. cleere of the u.s. naval observatory
sosigenes had estimated the year at 365.25 days, while it really was 365.2422 days. that means sosigenes was about 11 minutes off over the course of a year
although caesar and his astronomer were long gone before anyone noticed it, some 1,500 years later, 11 minutes per year had added up to a whopping 10 days,'' cleere said. ``and so, the seasons were slipping backwards again _ spring into winter, winter into fall, and so on.''
that prompted the current calendar, instituted by pope gregory in 1582, who dropped the offending 10 days _ a change that took a while to be accepted in non-catholic countries. indeed, england and her colonies didn't join in until 1752, by which time the error had grown to 11 days. japan came over in 1873, china in 1911 and russia held out until its bolshevik revolution in 1917
that's why many history books refer to dates during the transition period as either ``old style'' or ``new style'' depending on whether a country was following the julian or gregorian calendar at the time
in addition to dropping the added days, pope gregory ruled that not every fourth year would be a leap year
in the gregorian calendar, centennial years are leap years only if they can be divided evenly by 400
thus, the year 2000 will be somewhat unusual in being a leap year. the last centennial leap year was 1600, the next will be 2400
the calendar's still not perfect, cleere admits, with the gregorian year still 26 seconds too long. but that only amounts to a bit over a half-hour per century, so it will be a long time before any further adjustments need to be made
the reagan administration, in a new rebuff to panamanian military strong man manuel antonio noriega, is lending diplomatic support to president eric arturo delvalle in his bid to resist a noriega-led effort to oust him
delvalle was the target of a series of maneuvers that had the earmarks of a military coup after noriega successfully fought off the president's effort to depose him as defense chief
we still regard him as president,'' state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley said friday, hours after noriega's allies in the national assembly voted to remove delvalle from office and to appoint the education minister as president. delvalle called the move ``legally despicable'' and urged a national strike to repudiate noriega's leadership
mrs. oakley said the u.s. decision was based on its support for ``civilian constitutional rule.''
high-level meetings were held throughout the day friday as officials assessed the startling array of developments in a country regarded as one of latin america's most strategically important
the administration has demonstrated increasing hostility toward noriega, particularly since two federal grand juries returned indictments feb. 5 depicting him as a key figure in an international drug trafficking conspiracy
delvalle had been viewed by the administration as little more than a front man for noriega, but that all changed thursday evening when he broke with the military chieftain
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said, ``we condemn all efforts to perpetuate military rule in panama, including efforts to remove president delvalle from office.''
panama's political turmoil, marked by shifting allegiances and high-stakes intrigue, gave rise to questions about whether the united states would intervene militarily. but president reagan said, ``i don't think that's an answer.''
vice president george bush, speaking to the south carolina press association, was less categorical than reagan
bush said he would ``reserve the right to do whatever is necessary, including military force, to protect america's sacred interest in that region of the world.'' on the other hand, bush said he didn't ``want to rattle any sabers.''
according to a panamanian dissident, delvalle knew in advance that his effort to replace noriega would fail, but the maneuver was only the first step in an elaborate plan designed to force noriega's departure over the next three weeks
jose i. blandon, a former close associate of noriega who has joined forces with delvalle, said in an interview here friday that he expects democratic countries in latin america will rally behind delvalle, further weakening noriega's position. the united states has been consulting with latin american countries on that subject
blandon said that he, delvalle and an array of panamanian opposition leaders have been working secretly for weeks on the plan to remove noriega
noriega's downfall will be hastened, blandon said, if there is broad support for a general strike in panama and if the united states decides to impose a trade embargo against that country
sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., called friday for a trade embargo, but white house spokesman marlin fitzwater indicated the administration had no interest in such a proposal. other administration officials said they knew of no firm decision to rule out that option
blandon said a u.s. trade embargo would cripple panama, pointing out that the country is heavily dependent financially on a trans-isthmus pipeline that transfers alaskan oil to tankers serving u.s. east coast ports
blandon said noriega already has been approached about the possibility of seeking exile in the dominican republic. he said dominican authorities have indicated they would be willing to receive him
but because of the federal indictments against him, noriega could be subject to extradition procedures because of a u.s. treaty with the dominican republic
an agriculture department study of 1984 yields and expenses shows that sugarbeets can be produced at lower costs in the midwest than in some areas of the west, as a rule
the study involved seven regions that produce nearly all the u.s. sugarbeets on about 8,700 farms. overall, the department's economic research service reported friday that it cost an average of $30.30 per net ton to produce beets. the range, however, was between $24 and $35 per ton
about 60 percent of the 1984 u.s. sugarbeet crop was produced at a cost below the u.s. average price support of $31.63 per ton,'' the report said. ``the producers received a weighted average price of $33.90 a net ton, ranging from $23.30 in region 3 (colorado, nebraska and southeastern wyoming) to $37.10 in region 6 (eastern idaho).''
most beet producers in region 3 operated at a loss because of the closing of several processing plants by the great western sugar co., the report said
sugarbeets are a high-value crop, but incomes vary widely among producers because of differences in input costs, yields, risks and non-farm income,'' the report said. ``climatic extremes in the widely disparate sugarbeet production regions may create highly variable incomes from region to region or from year to year.''
the study of 1984 costs, by region, showed:
_region 1, michigan and ohio, 10.8 percent of the u.s. sugarbeet acreage; government support of $27.79 per net ton; actual price received by growers, $32.95 per ton; average cost of production, $24.02 per ton
_region 2, minnesota and eastern north dakota, 35.2 percent of the u.s. acreage; support of $32.24 per ton; actual price received by growers, $36 per ton; average cost of production, $25.66 per ton
_region 3, colorado, nebraska and southeastern wyoming, 12.8 percent of the acreage; support of $31.23 per ton; actual price received by growers, $23.30 per ton; average cost of production, $28.06 per ton
_region 4, new mexico and texas, was not included in the study
_region 5, montana, northwestern wyoming and northwestern north dakota, 5 percent of the acreage; support of $31.37 per ton; actual price received by growers, $35.40 per ton; average cost of production, $34.26 per ton
_region 6, eastern idaho, 7.4 percent of the acreage; support of $31.05 per ton; actual price received by growers, $37.10 per ton; average cost of production, $34.87 per ton
_region 7, western idaho and oregon, 6.5 percent of the acreage; support of $31.05 per ton; actual price received by growers, $36.90 per ton; average cost of production, $34.68 per ton
_region 8, california, 18.8 percent of the acreage; support of $32.98 per ton; actual price received by growers, $35.10 per ton; average cost of production, $34.57 per ton.   
the use of cotton by domestic textile manufacturers is at the highest level since the early 1970s, but an agriculture department analysis says the price outlook for producers is uncertain
in the 1987 marketing year that ended last july 31, nearly 7.5 million bales of cotton were used by mills, up from 6.4 million in 1986. as it looks now, 1988 mill use is headed for another gain to around 7.8 million bales
but imports of cotton textiles also are up, totaling an equivalent of 4.9 million bales in 1987, a 22 percent increase from 1986, the department's economic research service said friday
meanwhile, u.s. exports of raw cotton are expected to be around 7 million bales in the 1988 marketing year, an increase of 300,000 bales from 1987, the agency said in its new outlook report
based on jan. 1 indications, the 1987 cotton harvest _ which goes into the overall supply for the 1988 marketing year _ is expected to yield 14.7 million bales, up from 9.7 million bales in 1986
cotton prices moved up last year because of the tighter supply and rising demand. the u.s. spot price, for example, rose above 77 cents per pound, the report said. but since last august, prices have dropped 17 to 20 cents
the larger-than-expected 1987 u.s. crop, the potential for increased acreage and production in 1988, and concern about the economy's performance have pressured prices lower this season,'' the report said
milk production last year declined 1 percent to less than 142.5 billion pounds from a revised 1986 record of 143.8 billion pounds, the agriculture department says
previously, usda had estimated 1987 milk output at about 142.9 billion pounds and the 1986 record at 144.1 billion
the new estimates were in a monthly report friday on milk production, which showed january output running about 3 percent above a year ago in the major dairy states
department economists say 1988 milk production is expected to rise by 1 percent to 3 percent, which could push output for the year to another record level
the romanian government has decided to renounce special trade benefits from the united states rather than comply with american human rights demands, the state department says
as a result of abandoning the 13-year policy, romania could lose up to $250 million in commerce with the united states this year
at the same time, the united states will lose an economic weapon the reagan administration has claimed to be effective in pressuring romania to improve the plight of its people
state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley announced friday that romania informed the united states through diplomatic channels that it had decided to renounce its receipt of most-favored-nation trading status. that status has kept tariffs on romanian goods at levels lower than those for products from most other soviet-allied countries
the benefits will end july 2 and romania also will lose eligibility for u.s. government-supported export credits through the commodity credit corp. or the export-import bank, mrs. oakley said
she said romania estimates the action will cause a $250 million annual reduction in romanian sales to the united states, which totaled $775 million in 1987
u.s. exports to romania are worth $200 million annually, of which half are agriculture products, and mrs. oakley said the competitiveness of these exports also will suffer
rep. christopher smith, r-n.j., a house foreign affairs committee member who visited bucharest last year, said in an interview that the decision by romanian president nicolae ceausescu to renounce the benefit was ``to pre-empt the annual scrutiny of romania's human rights record, which is deplorable.''
he's cutting off his nose to spite his face,'' smith said of ceausescu. ```we don't want to end the relationship. we just want them to stop the trashing of human rights.''
in recent years, u.s. diplomats have conferred with the ceausescu government on steps romania was expected to take to get most-favored-nation status. the message was simple: improve rights or lose income
under the 1975 jackson-vanik amendment, communist countries otherwise ineligible for most-favored-nation status can win the benefit from congress if the president certifies the country has fair emigration policies
since enactment of the amendment, which was designed to spur emigration of jews and other ethnic groups from the soviet bloc, only hungary, poland and romania have received the benefits
while the statute links the benefits only to emigration policies, a growing dissatisfaction on capitol hill with romania's overall human rights record in recent months has prompted bills cutting off the privileges this year
besides romania's longstanding suppression of free speech, assembly, political opposition and other rights, senators and congressmen said, there had been little movement on u.s. demands for a loosening of control over religious minorities
deputy secretary of state john c. whitehead, who met ceausescu in bucharest three weeks ago, informed the romanian leader of u.s. dissatisfaction with human rights policies
ceausescu's reply appeared to presage the decision announced friday. whitehead told reporters after the meeting that in response to his comments about romanian rights, ceausescu said, in essence: stop meddling in romania's internal affairs
mrs. oakley said that despite the halting of the most-favored-nation process, romania ``has authoritatively stated to us that it will continue to allow emigration for family reunification purposes, without relation to economic ties with the united states. we welcome this.''
this staid old spa town was a bit taken aback last week to discover that the winter olympics' best-loved loser is a native son _ ski-jumper eddie ``the eagle'' edwards
most of cheltenham, like the rest of the world, hadn't heard of the 24-year-old edwards until he leaped into the olympic limelight with flailing arms and an unflappable smile
edwards finished last in two events but came first as a crowd-pleaser, and on friday, british television viewers saw him rubbing shoulders with actor burt reynolds on the johnny carson show
mayor gil wakeley said cheltenhamites are preparing a homecoming parade, cakes and receptions for the part-time plasterer, although wakeley confessed he wasn't sure where or in what order
there were quite a number of people that had never heard of his name,'' said wakeley, sitting at the desk in his office, nicknamed ``the parlor,'' where silver tea sets bedecked a chest and a little dog wandered in and out
but i think most of cheltenham stayed up to watch his final jumps,'' he said
there was no sign of excitement on the promenade of chic shops and fine regency buildings, no eddie-the-eagle t-shirts and no banners in the city of 95,000 people 90 miles west of london
cheltenham, a tourist town built around mineral waters tapped 200 years ago, isn't the type of place to blow its horn about the eagle, but it seems quietly proud
without sponsors, coaches or a single jumping slope in his native land, with no one but his parents and sister with him in calgary, edwards had dared to ``have a go at it,'' as the townspeople put it
the eagle, whose thick glasses enhance his gangly, birdlike look, came last in both his events, the 70- and 90-meter jumps. his longest jump fell 46.5 meters short of the winner of both events, matti nykanen of finland
but when he added three meters to the british record of 68 meters, london newspapers ran headlines such as, ``eddie survives ... and breaks british record.''
edwards, who doesn't mind coming across as a bit of a klutz, always had a smile and wave for the crowd after his jumps
the crowds roared, but so did the critics. norway tried to have edwards barred, and an olympic official said 11-year-olds could jump farther, although nykanen reportedly supported edwards' right to compete
back home there were doubters too, like the times of london, whose sportswriter commented: ``the question remains whether the likes of eddie, the wingless eagle, ... deserved to compete in the games,'' since ``the emphasis should be on excellence.''
cecil baylis, a retired cheltenham businessman, agreed. ``it's a bit of a joke isn't it? i think people are laughing at him and with him too.''
the mayor dismissed the critics
the idea of the olympics is for people to try _ for each and everyone to have an opportunity to try,'' said wakeley. ``it's for the amateur.''
edwards seems to have struck a peculiarly british chord _ a weakness for the gallant loser
the british always tend to like the underdog,'' said david watson, edwards's first coach on the artificial slopes of the gloucester hotel and ski center near cheltenham, where edwards took up skiing in his teens on turf that doubled for snow
and in ski jumping, he's certainly the underdog,'' added watson, who manages the resort
watson recalls the novice eagle as ``keen but not as good as a lot of people who were skiing then .... he was very ambitious but he didn't want to listen.''
edwards yearned to slalom, but became fond of jumping during a visit to italy. also, said his aunt, jean byrne, jumping was ``a wee bit cheaper.''
we were really surprised'' by the publicity, she said. ``he only went to jump. people really took to him.''
