here are some comments friday from candidates for the presidency:

george bush, on panama's military strong man manuel antonio noriega: ``noriega's gone bad, and he's proven he's trafficked in narcotics. ... noriega should go and in my view he will go.''

jack kemp, saying he thinks noriega should be ousted because a friendly government in panama is essential: ``noriega ... represents a threat to the panama canal.''

richard gephardt, saying eastern airlines cares more about profits than its employees: ``we will stop the attitude that the way to make profits is to take them out of the hides of employees.''
eastern airlines spokesman robin matell called gephardt's remarks ``a cheap attempt to get votes in the upcoming presidential primaries.''

michael dukakis, stressing education and urging good jobs and opportunity for all: ``it's going to take hard workers, not high rollers, to get america moving again.''

pat robertson, speaking to students at a christian academy: ``(i want) to see america once again return to the fundamental faith that she had, the faith of our fathers, to go back to our faith in god and go back to individual self-reliance, to go back to a feeling of community, to go back to strong family values.''

jesse jackson, reminding the georgia legislature of his southern roots: ``i am one of you. i worked hard to make the new south new _ now, let's make the new south better. i am my party's conscience. by july, with your help, i want to be its candidate.''

bob dole, picking up an endorsement from former texas gov. john connally: ``i think today our campaign goes up another notch.''
president reagan and southern republican state chairmen did some talking about prospects of attracting conservative democrats to vote gop in the super tuesday presidential primary balloting
the participants in the discussions friday also talked about how republican ranks will already be swollen with new members drawn to the primary by the candidacy of former television evangelist pat robertson
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the president invited the southerners to talk about ``what they expect in terms of voter turnout, the new strength of the republican party in the south, and how they see the campaign going at this point.''
according to arkansas gop chairman ed bethune, voters in his state will ``see very clearly there are two primaries, the liberal primary and the conservative primary.''
jeannie austin of orlando, fla., head of the southern republican chairmen's association, said ``we talked about super tuesday and how we could get conservative democrats to vote with us.''
ms. austin and oklahoma state chairman tom cole agreed that the candidacy of pat robertson, by encouraging his fundamentalist christian admirers to participate, is swelling the ranks of republican primary voters
he gets part of the credit without a doubt,'' cole said. he added, however, that he believes reagan has done more than anyone else to increase republican strength in the south
ms. austin said robertson ``certainly has an organization and we welcome these new people to our party because it certainly beefs up our numbers.''
republican state chairman van hipp of south carolina, which will hold its gop primary march 5, predicted a ``very tight race'' in his state, saying robertson has a good organization, sen. bob dole of kansas has the support of the popular sen. strom thurmond, r-s.c., and new york rep. jack kemp ``is coming on strong in rural areas.''
hipp said reagan ``views this as a golden opportunity to attract independent and conservative-leaning democrats.''
others attending were george strake of texas, jack hawke of north carolina, evelyn mcphail of mississippi, john stuckey of georgia, jim henry of tennessee, donald hoffman of virginia, and bob gable of kentucky. chairmen from louisiana and alabama missed the meeting
reagan, who has remained publicly neutral in the gop race, was asked by a reporter during a photo-taking session before the meeting whether he expects vice president george bush to win in the south
gesturing around the table with his hands, the president said: ``ask them.''
a federal appeals court has given two of the nation's largest manufacturers of glass containers the green light to operate as a single company
on friday, the u.s. court of appeals for the district of columbia rejected a request by the federal government to block the proposed merger between owens-illinois inc. and brockway inc
owens-illinois spokesman john hoff said the court denied a motion by the federal trade commission for an injunction and dissolved a temporary stay of the proposed merger
hoff said the court ruled that the ftc had failed to demonstrate the need for an injunction
he said the company has extended its $60-per-share tender offer for brockway until 5 p.m. monday, after which time it will be free to proceed with the merger
last week, u.s. district court judge joyce hens green refused the ftc's request for a preliminary injunction, ruling that the ftc had not proven the deal would harm competition
the ftc then asked the appeals court to block the merger until the agency could conduct an administrative review of potential anti-competitive effects of the deal
last september, the toledo, ohio-based owens-illinois proposed to buy brockway, of jacksonville, fla., for $750 million
the merger would make the combined company the largest manufacturer of glass containers in the industry. the nation's top manufacturer is anchor glass container corp., which controls 23.7 percent of the market
the ftc has said the merger might violate federal antitrust laws by substantially reducing competition in the glass container industry and creating conditions for price discrimination
but judge green accepted the argument by the two manufacturers that competition from the plastics and metal-packaging industry will keep down prices
attorneys for owens-illinois say the purpose of the merger is to achieve cost savings and efficiencies that will enable the combined companies to vigorously compete against the producers of plastics, metal and other types of packaging materials
the customs service was unable to produce immediate documentation that 6.4 million barrels of oil imported from iran late last year had been shipped or under contract before a trade ban was imposed
buyers up, a consumer oil-buying cooperative affiliated with consumer advocate ralph nader, said friday the oil was imported in november and december after president reagan banned trade with that country
the customs service said it believed the oil was legal, but couldn't immediately lay its hands on the documents that would prove itt
the oil accounted for 7.3 percent of u.s. crude imports for those two months. the trade embargo took effect nov. 29
buyers up director jason adkins said officials at the foreign assets control division of the treasury and the strategic branch of the customs service ``were completely unaware of the november and december shipments of iranian oil to this country until we brought it to their attention.''
he agreed the oil could be legal, but said he had not been able to find anyone in the government who could say it was
customs service spokesman david hoover said, ``we're reasonably sure _ we don't have the printout _ the oil was legal.'' he said it might take two days to find the computer printout that would show the certifications that the oil was exempt from the president's action
since the exemptions expired dec. 31, hoover said he would be surprised if january statistics showed any shipments from iran
iran was a major supplier to the united states in the 1970s before the revolution in that country, but shipments fell after the 1981 release of the american hostages seized in the u.s. embassy in tehran
iran generally accounted for from 1 percent to 3 percent of u.s. crude imports in following years
shipments rose sharply in the early months of 1987, however, and in july iran was the second largest supplier of crude to the united states. reagan said he imposed the ban to ensure that u.s. purchases did not contribute to terrorism, which the u.s. government says iran supports
for all of 1987, iran's crude shipments amounted to 5.1 percent of u.s. crude imports, more than 88 million barrels worth $1.5 billion. that was more than triple the $468 million paid for 34 million barrels in 1986. far, including 137 selected earlier, actions at portland caucus, quotes from party chairwoman; picks up 13th graf pvs bgng, `gov. john'</note>
part-time resident george bush was way out in front friday night as maine republicans launched a weekend of gop presidential caucuses, his campaign said
statewide, the vice president's campaign claimed to have won 166 of the 234 state delegates selected so far for the april convention in bangor, at which 22 national delegates will be chosen
the bush campaign said pat robertson so far has received 28 state delegates, sen. bob dole of kansas has collected 20 and rep. jack kemp of new york has garnered five while 15 delegates were uncommitted
the results of the republican caucuses do not bind state convention delegates and party leaders were not bothering to compile the tallies right away
the delegates totaled by the bush campaign included the 137 selected in caucuses in 43 towns since late january
the republicans will select the rest of the 1,506 state delegates during caucuses saturday and sunday
bush and dole forces had forged an uneasy alliance before the caucuses to frustrate robertson forays in delegate-rich areas as they faced an influx of first-time voters from fundamentalist churches
robertson supporters warred with bush backers over voting rules friday night at the republican caucus in portland, maine's largest city, but tempers cooled when most of the 33 delegate slots at stake were evenly divided between the two
each camp came away with 15, while dole received the rest after three hours of heated procedural voting and brokering
the local republican organization in portland became the first to drop its winner-take-all standard in favor of proportional representation
bush and dole factions conferred continuously during the portland caucusing but, in the end, the dole supporters sided with robertson's campaign in scrapping the all-or-nothing allocation of delegates
state party chairwoman karen stram, watching the portland voting, acknowledged that feelings were running high in the various camps. stram said her job was ``to be sure that everyone comes out of it feeling they got a fair shake.''
she also said statewide turnout could reach 15,000 or more by the end of the weekend
no question, we're up three times at least'' over previous years, she said
organizers say their primary goal is to win as many as possible of 1,506 state convention delegate slots for their partisans. but party regulars also say the bush-dole coalition reflects fears that the state republican organization could be taken over by robertson's supporters, a repeat of what happened in michigan
john solberg, robertson's state coordinator, this week charged that ``the bush and dole campaigns are attempting to keep the majority silent in the democratic process.''
solberg made his comments after the gop caucus in waterville, at which robertson won a straw poll but came away with no delegates
participants in the straw poll split four ways, with robertson leading with 57 votes, bush 40, dole 20, and kemp eight, solberg said. but bush and dole backers joined together in the caucusing to block robertson from maintaining a winner-take-all plurality. the caucus's 12 delegate slots for the state convention were awarded to the stop-robertson combine
solberg said a similar deal was struck at the gop caucus in kittery last week
gov. john r. mckernan jr., who has been campaigning for bush, who has a summer home in kennebunkport, said thursday the vice president's campaign was acting in self-interest to ``maximize the number of delegates'' it could lock up. he called solberg's complaint ``amusing,'' saying that robertson organizers had themselves sought to build anti-bush coalitions around the state
this is not fun and games,'' said mckernan, maine's first republican governor in two decades. ``we're talking about the next president of the united states.''
state sen. pamela cahill, a dole organizer, also dismissed the robertson campaign charge. ``we operated within the caucus structure and got those dole delegates,'' she said friday
acknowledging that a bush-dole alliance here represented a far different attitude than seen nationally between the competing campaigns, cahill said she was motivated by concern for ``the well-being of the republican party.''
i guess i'm too damn parochial,'' cahill said. ``i'm concerned because i don't want to see robertson people getting all the positions ... blocking out the rank-and-file republicans who support our party in good times and bad ... and then leaving the party in disarray,'' she said
at the few republican caucuses held already, turnout appears to be much higher than in the past, a factor attributed to robertson's grass-roots drive
but a hostile reception for the insurgents could undercut the potential for long-range party growth, warned an organizer for the flagging maine campaign of kemp
we're sending the people home and telling them `you're not welcome,''' said george smith, who predicted the establishment alliance would make bush ``the big winner.''
in michigan, robertson supporters won control of the state gop committee, working in cooperation with kemp backers. the coalition fell apart, however, in january when kemp's camp defected to join forces with bush and split the state's 77 gop delegates
democrats caucus statewide on sunday, and first place is conceded to gov. michael dukakis of neighboring massachusetts
an off-duty policeman was slain friday during a robbery attempt outside the grocery where he moonlighted as a security guard, police said
a witness said the officer, gary d. mccarthy, 32, was shot after refusing to hand over a money bag. mccarthy, who was in street clothes, died at parkland memorial hospital four hours later, said police chief billy prince
the 14-month member of the force was escorting the store manager from a bank visit when a man jumped out of a car and attempted to rob the manager, said sgt. s.g. shaw
`the officer went for his weapon and they got into a shootout,'' shaw said
mccarthy was shot three times, and one of the bullets lodged in his heart, hospital spokeswoman paula sears said. after the officer fell to the ground, he fired twice at the fleeing vehicle and shattered its rear window, police said
officers found a car believed to be used in the robbery attempt a few blocks away in a housing project, where witnesses said they saw three men flee, police said. helicopters searched for the men
derick johnson, 21, who was standing outside the store when the shooting occurred, said the officer was carrying a money bag when approached by the gunman
the guy tried to snatch the money, but the police officer wouldn't give it to him,'' johnson said. ``the guy was waving a gun, and when the officer wouldn't give him the money, he just shot him.''
two officers were slain last month in cases that sparked both support for police and criticism from minorities who said officers had been too trigger-happy when arresting blacks and hispanics
a white officer was slain jan. 23 by a deranged black vagrant who had wrested the policeman's gun away on a downtown street. a black officer was killed a week earlier during a suspected burglary at an apartment complex where he worked off-duty
prince, who earlier had charged that city council criticism of the police department had created so much public hostility that police deaths were inevitable, said of friday's shooting, ``i don't see how you can make anything racial out of this.''
the gunman was black; the officer white
the problem is we have too many people on the streets who should be in the penitentiary,'' the chief said. ``there are too many people on the streets who are mean.''
here, at a glance, are the methods for picking delegates from maine to attend the 1988 democratic and republican national conventions this summer
method: caucus
date: sunday, february 28
presidential filing deadline: none
pledged delegates: 23
super delegates: 4
total: 27
delegates allocated: sunday, february 28
selection of delegates: saturday, may 14 and sunday, may 15

maine uses a two-step caucus-convention system for picking its delegates to the democratic national convention. maine, which is one of four states specifically allowed by democratic party rules to begin the process of picking delegates before march 8, holds local municipal caucuses on feb. 28. the results of these caucuses will govern the allocation of the state's 15 pledged national convention delegates from congressional districts. maine's remaining eight pledged national convention delegates will be chosen at the democratic state convention on may 13-15
method: caucus
date: sunday, february 28
presidential filing deadline: none
delegates: 22
delegates allocated: saturday, april 16
selection of delegates: saturday, april 16
maine republicans choose their national convention delegates with town caucuses held between feb. 26 and feb. 28 to elect delegates to the state convention and congressional district conventions. delegates are not required to pledge their support to a presidential candidate. the state's two congressional district conventions meet in conjunction with the state convention april 15-17. six national convention delegates are chosen by the congressional district conventions, and the remaining 16 delegates are elected at-large by the state convention
an eastern airlines spokesman says democratic presidential candidate richard gephardt was playing ``cheap political games'' when he criticized the attitude of company management
eastern spokesman robin matell described gephardt's comments as ``a cheap attempt to get votes in the upcoming presidential primaries.''
gephardt said controversy surrounding the miami-based airline is a national issue as well as a local one
what it signifies is an attitude in corporate america that the way of the future is to cut jobs, is to engage in mergers, is to engage in taking the important parts of the corporation out and splitting them out into entities so that there can be quick paper profits,'' gephardt said
reps. larry smith and claude pepper said they'll ask congress to hold hearings to investigate eastern. the two florida democrats support gephardt's candidacy and appeared with him at a news conference friday
gephardt, whose campaign has stressed a need to improve corporate productivity, stopped short of calling for re-regulation of the airline industry by the federal government. but the missouri congressman said if he's elected president, his administration will enforce the industry's safety standards and change the way management thinks
we will stop the attitude that the way to make profits is to take them out of the hides of employees,'' said gephardt, who met with eastern employees before the news conference
eastern, which reported a net loss of $181.1 million in 1987, is demanding contract concessions totaling $450 million from unions representing its machinists, pilots and flight attendants
eastern is trying to negotiate a sensible solution with the (international association of machinists) to what has been a long-term cost problem,'' matell said. ``no company can pay baggage handlers an average of $43,000 a year. we are doing everything possible to negotiate a sensible solution with the iam to solve the cost problem
the irresponsible charges made today are not in the best interest of any of the parties, least of all eastern or its very fine group of employees
it's extremely unfortunate that a collective bargaining situation is being used for cheap political games.''
rep. smith said many in congress want to investigate eastern ``to prevent further deterioration'' of the company. pepper said ``there ought to be some way'' the breakup of eastern can be stopped
gephardt supported the call for an investigation of eastern
congress should be concerned about the safety in this airline and should be concerned about some of the actions that have been taken,'' gephardt said. he said recent management decisions at eastern reflect ``the dismantling of a great corporation.''
two soldiers charged with mishandling classified documents were arrested after a teen-ager who claimed to be running drugs for one of them brought a briefcase of papers to a tv station, officials said
the fbi arrested the two soldiers based at the army's fort irwin on wednesday
james weller, agent in charge of the fbi's las vegas office, declined to say what the secret papers contained. he said investigators were trying to determine whether the documents were to be sold, and if so, to whom
a tip to a las vegas tv station from a former mental patient prompted the arrests, weller said
a young man came to our studios ... with a briefcase full of secret documents,'' said lynn mathis, a reporter for station ktnv. ``he told us that he was employed by an army sergeant as a drug runner.''
station news director steve minium said the claimed he was tired of dealing drugs and ``flipped out'' when he found the documents. minium declined to identify the 19-year-old
staff sgt. edmund washington tuck, 24, and specialist 4th class kelly joe schmidt, 23, were arrested and held in the stockade at fort irwin on charges of improper handling of classified documents, weller said
the informant told minium he met tuck in the mental ward of a victorville hospital and later moved in with him in barstow. there he said his job was to run a methamphetamine and lsd trafficking operation for tuck, minium said
agents are investigating the drug-trafficking allegations
fort irwin is in the mojave desert, about 140 miles northeast of downtown los angeles. the army trains soldiers in desert warfare tactics at the base. un vote</head>
the united states is willing to talk about delaying the effective date of an arms embargo against iran in exchange for soviet agreement to have the united nations vote on the issue as soon as possible, a state department official says
the state department official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said friday the proposal is designed to get a speedy vote on the resolution while meeting the kremlin's stated desire for another round of diplomacy aimed at winning a cease-fire in the iran-iraq war
the official said u.s. officials proposed thursday to soviet representatives at the united nations that the united states would be willing to discuss delaying implementation of an embargo from 30 to 60 days
the united states has been pushing the soviets to agree to the embargo but the soviets have been reluctant to implement one without another diplomatic attempt by u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar to get iran to agree to a cease-fire in its seven-year war with iraq
the soviet position has been that any embargo should immediately follow passage of an embargo resolution by the u.n. security council, and therefore such a vote should be delayed to allow time for more diplomatic efforts
meanwhile, the minneapolis star &amp; tribune in today's editions quoted administration officials who said the united states also is willing to discuss with the soviets the creation of a u.n. fleet to stop and search ships suspected of carrying arms to iran
the officials, who were not identified by the newspaper, said the u.n. fleet would not be similar to a soviet proposal that u.s., french, british and other western naval forces in the persian gulf be put under the u.n. flag and command
rather, the arms-monitoring fleet under the u.s. proposal would be made up of ships from neutral countries and would intercept freighters at the mouth of the gulf as they headed for the iranian port of bandar abbas, the newspaper said
the state department official told the associated press that the u.s. position all along has been to discuss proposals that might be used to implement the embargo after passage of the u.n. resolution
the united states has not yet made a specific proposal to the soviets about how the embargo would be enforced, the official said
the security council adopted a resolution july 20 demanding an immediate cease-fire in the iran-iraq war, troop withdrawal, prisoner exchange and enforcement steps if either party did not comply
only iraq has agreed to the cease-fire. an attempt by the secretary-general to bring both sides to agreement foundered in september
any of the five permanent members of the security council _ the united states, the soviet union, great britain, france and china _ could veto an embargo resolution
the soviet union and other nations seeking better relations with iran have been reluctant to push for punitive enforcement
earlier this month, u.s. officials said that china, which they said sold $1 billion worth of arms to iran last year, is not expected to block an embargo
singer michael jackson ordered more flowers than other celebrities who've stayed at the pensacola hilton, including elizabeth taylor and bob hope, and some of the blooms went for vegetarian meals, workers said
when michael left, i went up to the presidential suite to collect the vases and they were everywhere, everywhere,'' said gehrig galloway, owner of gehrig's flower shop at the hilton
i walked into the kitchen once when damien was cooking,'' said thaisa betts-hester, the hotel's room division manager, referring to the chef jackson brought from los angeles. ``damien was cooking with an odd-looking flower with brown petals that he kept in a zip-loc bag. i asked him what was in the bag and he said, `flowers.'''
jackson also ordered 32 cases of evian mineral water for drinking and bathing, baby corn, fresh herbs and sun-dried tomatoes from orlando, hotel employees said
