remember edb? four years after the grain fumigant was banned as a possible cancer risk amid panic over contaminated popcorn, breakfast cereal and muffin mix, the public has nearly forgotten it
judy heckman, chief of pesticide disposal for the u.s. environmental protection agency, hasn't. heckman plans to fly to texas to preside at the burning of the last 330,000 gallons of the pesticide early next week
the edb, or ethylene dibromide, to be incinerated was taken from a warehouse and put on a train in liberty, mo., that left last week for an industrial park in deer park outside houston. more trains will leave with the remaining gallons every monday until june, officials said
the federal government paid $2.5 million for what was left of the chemical and may spend up to $8 million to get rid of it, epa officials estimate
it is the costly end of a story of national panic that erupted after edb was discovered in groundwater in florida, georgia, california and hawaii in 1983. worried about its potential to cause cancer, the epa in september 1983 banned the use of edb as a pesticide for spraying on the ground
it was not until feb. 3, 1984, however, that edb was banned as a fumigant for stored grain and limits were set on amounts in foods
although the extent of the cancer risk remains uncertain, edb was banned amid a public outcry that the government was dragging its feet
calls poured in to poison control centers across the country with worried questions about edb
massachusetts authorities ordered tainted baby foods tossed out, and florida's agriculture department had scores of products swept from grocery store shelves
pillsbury co. alone claimed it lost $70 million as a result of what u.s. agriculture secretary john block referred to at the time as ``some hysteria out there that really isn't warranted.''
at the time it was a major environmental catastrophe and now nobody's heard of it,'' said rick johnson, the epa official who headed the federal effort to investigate and eventually ban edb. ``so we must have done something right.''
edb had been widely used on farms and in storage silos since 1948. it was used mainly to kill fungus on stored grains, but also was sprayed on citrus fruits to kill fruit flies and on soil before crops were planted
scientists continued to give it their blessings through the 1950s when they were unable to detect any residue after the chemical evaporated. but when more sensitive detection techniques were developed, they revealed that minute traces of edb were clinging to the wheat and other grains all the way to the supermarket
in 1975, the national cancer institute said the pesticide was suspected of causing cancer in laboratory animals
by 1980 the epa proposed to ban it after studies found the health risks of cancer, genetic damage and reproductive disorders outweighed its economic benefits
johnson said such a risk assessment makes sense for the government, but can be hard to put into perspective for the public
the difficult thing is to explain a very complicated science and policy issue to a naive public,'' he said. ```can i eat this muffin mix?' of course you can eat it.''
others see edb as a case study in government overreaction
stephen klaidman of the institute for health policy analysis at georgetown university in washington is including a chapter on edb in a book he is writing about the influence of the media on public policy
the central question is whether the stuff was taken off the market too quickly before they knew what (pesticides) they were replacing it with (and) whether there was a panic reaction to a chemical that was in the food chain for 30 years,'' klaidman said. ``as far as i know, nobody has been able to connect a single death to edb from ingesting it.''
a man was sentenced to two days in jail and fined $45 for riding a motorized skateboard without a driver's license
damian vincent ghiardi, 21, of richland was convicted tuesday of driving with a revoked license and negligent driving. he ran a stop sign in november on a skateboard powered by a chainsaw motor and was knocked unconscious by a car
defense attorney nathan kirk had argued that the skateboard was not a motor vehicle because ghiardi had to push it a block with his foot to get up speed, but benton county district judge eugene pratt disagreed
prosecutor bob swisher said the case was treated seriously because of the potential for more serious injury
ghiardi's driver's license had been revoked last year when he was convicted of attempting to elude a police officer, court records show
the streets of this city shut down by arab strikes teemed with israeli soldiers as the muezzin called the faithful to pray on the moslem sabbath. the soldiers waited for the inevitable violence
noon prayers every friday have surpassed religious significance since palestinians in the occupied west bank and gaza strip began their protests 11 weeks ago. mosques have become the rallying point for dissent and the release of pent-up frustrations
the latest violence came at the al-omari mosque in gaza on friday, as it did elsewhere in the territories. and, as expected, the soldiers wasted little time breaking up the demonstration, responding to the stone-throwing with tear gas and rubber bullets
this time, there were no injuries a al-omari, the main mosque in gaza city, capital of the territory snatched from egypt during the 1967 middle east war. the building was erected by the romans and later transformed into a mosque
friday's sermon by khamis murtaja, a lecturer at the islamic university in gaza, was moderate. a worshipper whispered to a visitor seated discreetly in the rear of the mosque that murtaja, like other speakers, has been warned by israeli authorities to avoid inflammatory rhetoric
murtaja's sermon to several hundred listeners called for patience and prayer in the face of the current difficulties
god will help those who remain patient,'' he said. ``it is a test of their faith. if we cannot remove injustice by force, we must be patient. don't despair. don't complain. the solution comes only from god. if you complain to other than god, it is submission.''
but as murtaja called for moderation, leaflets signed by the fundamentalist islamic jihad organization were being circulated in the mosque. their message was vastly different
the land of palestine is the center of the struggle and the essence of the universal conflict,'' said the leaflet from islamic jihad, whose influence has been growing, particularly in the gaza strip
the salvation of the arab people, in particular the palestinian people, and the salvation of all human beings is related to the destruction of this hateful, racist entity,'' the leaflet said, refering to israel
it called on the people to escalate the fight against israel, saying ``the mosques must be transformed into centers of confrontation.''
the moment the prayers were over, dozens of youths rose to their feet shouting ``allahu akhbar,'' arabic for ``god is great,'' and dash for the exit
outside they picked up stones and pelted the nearest group of soldiers, shouting taunts and curses
the soldiers charged, firing tear gas canisters and rubber bullets. the youths scattered, darting into the myriad of sidestreets and alleys. the army declared the area a closed military zone until calm is restored
army vehicles raced up and down the streets, three abreast, chasing demonstrators. a woman ran down a main avenue waving her arms and screaming: ``they have seized two mosques.''
it is not true. at least not here. but numerous witnesses said soldiers raided a mosque in the nearby jabaliya refugee camp, where one palestinian youth died and about 20 injured in the clashes
new york gov. mario cuomo, insisting he doesn't want to play the role of presidential candidate or kingmaker if there's a brokered national convention, headed for north carolina today to help a fellow democrat
against the backdrop of brokered convention talk, cuomo was to appear twice over the next several days in an area of the nation that could be very important to democrats come november
tonight, cuomo was to be in raleigh, n.c., as the featured speaker at a fund-raising event for sen. terry sanford. on tuesday, cuomo is to be in san antonio, texas, for an address at trinity university
was it coincidence that cuomo was heading south just before the crucial march 8 super tuesday primaries?
oh no, that's a plan,'' joked cuomo on friday. ``you see, i'm going to be march 1 in texas and if it really goes well, then march 2 i'm going to announce i'm running.''
the new york governor, the most prominent of the democratic non-candidates, said friday that he still didn't believe there would be a deadlocked convention
i would have no role,'' cuomo said of a possible brokered convention. ``they (the announced candidates) would confine themselves to people who were candidates and talk to one another.''
pittsburgh mayor richard caliguiri has endorsed massachusetts gov. michael dukakis for the democratic nomination for president
as the only democratic candidate for president who has ever managed a large government, mike dukakis has balanced nine straight budgets and cut taxes in four of the last five years while transforming his state into one of the models of economic success in america,'' caliguiri said friday
allegheny county commissioner pete flaherty and erie mayor louis tullio were among other pennsylvania democrats who announced their support for dukakis on friday
the coordinator of democrat paul simon's presidential campaign in oklahoma says she hasn't been paid in a while, but the organization will continue to operate
glo henley says the simon campaign is ``not going to be doing anything that requires great supplies of money. we won't do a lot of long-distance calling.''
she said it's been awhile since she's seen a paycheck from the campaign, but ``i would continue working for him whether i got paid or not.''
the illinois senator has announced that he can't afford to campaign in the 20 states scheduled for the march 8 super tuesday presidential primary
ms. henley said she has not changed her assessment of simon's chances in oklahoma, saying she still would be happy to see him garner 15 percent of the vote
despite its religious overtones, a new book telling the spiritual side of vice president george bush is not intended to counter pat robertson's challenge in the gop presidential race, the publisher says
we want people to know that george bush is a christian but he's more than a christian. he has great political experience,'' bob hawkins sr., president of harvest house publishers, said friday
based on interviews with bush and his family, ``man of integrity'' is being rushed into print in time for the super tuesday primaries and caucuses on march 8. the 224-page book will roll off the presses monday
it was a typical operatic tale _ a crisis night with a storybook ending at the royal opera, covent garden
the lead singer felt terrible but sang on bravely
the second lead singer had a triumph, although he had never sung his role before when he was summoned to london at short notice
when the first-night revival of giuseppe verdi's ``a masked ball'' ended friday night, it was cheers from a grateful audience and nine curtain calls for cast and conductor
the story went like this:
italian baritone giorgio zancanaro, who was booked for the second lead, fell ill with an ear infection which upset his sense of balance and prevented him from traveling
so romanian alexandru agache, who had never even sung in a major opera house in the west took over, learning the role in just over two weeks
i think this is the start of a big international career for him,'' said conductor richard armstrong
spanish tenor giacomo aragall had a valiant night
he also had an ear infection _ and bronchitis. but he got on with the job and sang well, wavering at times, but hanging in there even with his voice breaking in the last act
what a night,'' said sir john tooley, just retired director at covent garden, when he called at agache's dressing-room to congratulate him
the human voice tends to be a recurring crisis. it causes opera house managements the most awful headaches,'' tooley said
opera is full of problems, some of which you can deal with away from the public gaze. but opera is the voice and a voice crisis means you have got the public out front and the whole performance to worry about _ your crisis is very visible,'' tooley said
you were stunning,'' tooley told agache. ``you coped brilliantly with the acting and the singing.''
you are very kind,'' murmured the romanian, a big man with a black beard, dripping sweat after the biggest test of his life
aragall had a big problem, but he said he felt all right and went on with it, but he sang under extreme difficulties all evening,'' tooley said
agache, 33, lives in cluj, in the heart of romania's transylvanian country. he has sung in budapest, dresden, east berlin, japan, yugoslavia and france, and was expecting to make his debut later this year in a major western opera house, la scala in milan. but covent garden got in first
agache auditioned at covent garden on jan. 19 and sang some verdi arias
he was recognized as having outstanding potential as a verdian baritone. he absolutely thrilled me as a singer,'' armstrong recalled
two days later, agache was in leghorn, italy, when his agent in frankfurt telephoned to say london wanted him as the ``perfect replacement'' for zancanaro
i sang a minor role in `a masked ball' in my debut with cluj opera, but i had to start learning the major role of anckarstrom for covent garden,'' agache said
he joined the rehearsals in london feb. 9
in the opera, anckarstrom is the secretary and friend of king gustavus iii of sweden, sung by aragall
the secretary, burning with jealousy after discovering his wife and the king are in love, joins a group of conspirators and stabs the king to death at a masked ball
in history, the king _ one of the great rulers of the 18th century _ was assassinated in 1792 at a masquerade in the stockholm opera house. he was shot in the back by a former royal bodyguard named anckarstrom
the assassin had his pistol hand cut off before he was beheaded and his body quartered. but verdi spared opera lovers and ended with the king dying, ordering his assassin's release and pardoning the conspirators
it's a difficult role because you have to marry very dramatic acting and a big vocal part,'' agache said
but it's a wonderful role, one of the great baritone parts, and a pleasure to sing,'' he added
verdi and ``a masked ball'' are much loved in london, which has a vibrant and wealthy italian community. the house was crowded
the pentagon says the remains of what may be 20 american servicemen missing from the vietnam war are to be delivered to u.s. officials in hanoi on wednesday and then transported to an army identification laboratory in hawai
the pentagon announced friday that the vietnamese government had agreed to repatriate the remains, which will be taken to the central identification laboratory in honolulu for identification
it will be the fourth-largest such transfer since the end of the war. the largest occurred in august 1985, when the vietnamese returned 26 remains at once
a u.s. trade official says the failure of foreign governments to crack down on foreign piracy of u.s. patents, trademarks and copyrights is a growing problem that distorts interrnational trade
u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter said friday that the annual drain on u.s. companies because of ``inadequate protection of intellectual property'' may run as high as $43 billion to $61 billion
the failure of our trading partners to provide effective protection for intellectual property is a severe and growing problem that distorts trade,'' yeutter said at a news conference
the u.s. international trade commission released a report at the news conference that said u.s. companies surveyed by the government reported losses of $23.8 billion in foreign piracy. the itc said actual losses are much greater because not all companies filled out questionaires on the subject
the air force says it plans to hold special meetings for residents living near 11 bases selected to handle rail-mounted mx missiles in order to ``identify environmental issues.''
the service announced a year ago it had selected f.e. warren air force base in wyoming to become the main operating base for any rail-mounted mx missiles and 10 other bases for consideration as additional ``rail garrisons.''
the service said friday it had launched an environmental impact study of the bases and that it would review a number of deployment alternatives, including the fielding of 100 mx missiles on rail cars instead of just 50 missiles
besides f.e. warren, the list includes blytheville air force base, ark.; little rock air force base, ark.; whiteman air force base, mo.; barksdale air force base, la.; dyess air force base, texas; fairchild air force base, wash.; grand forks air force base, n.d.; minot air force base, n.d.; malstrom air force base, mont., and wurtsmith air force base, mich
a fourth cia official involved in the iran-contra weapons deals is leaving the agency
alan fiers, who established a secret supply network for nicaragua's contra rebels, has resigned effective march 4, bill baker, the agency's spokesman, said friday
fiers, who plans to go into private business, was one of several cia officials involved in the iran-contra affair who was reprimanded last year by cia director william webster because of his role and his failure to inform congress about the activity
despite that disciplinary action, fiers had continued to handle central american matters and had briefed members of congress as part of the reagan administration's efforts to win renewed military aid for the contras
most latin american governments expressed support for eric arturo delvalle's failed attempt to fire military strongman, gen. manuel antonio noriega, which cost delvalle the presidency of panama
nicaragua and cuba appeared alone among latin american nations in announcing their support for noriega, whose backers in panama's national assembly ousted delvalle early friday after he tried to dismiss the general
ending a three-day meeting in cartagena, colombia, the foreign ministers of seven latin american countries said they had suspended panama from their group of eight, a regional organization for political and economic cooperation
the foreign ministers of argentina, brazil, colombia, mexico, peru, uruguay and venezuela said in a communique that the suspension was ordered because participation in the group requires ``the clear operation of democratic institutions among members.''
the communique said the suspension would last ``until a new evaluation of the circumstances'' in panama, where noriega controls the 15,000-man military and police as defense forces chief
in managua, president daniel ortega on friday pledged ``unconditional solidarity'' with noriega, who was indicted on drug trafficking charges in florida earlier this month
ortega said the general's problems began when ``the united states government arrived and told gen. noriega: `gen. noriega, we need you to support us in an invasion against the nicaraguan people' and gen. noriega and the defense forces of panama said no.''
panama helped the leftist sandinistas in their guerrilla war against the nicaraguan government of president anastasio somoza, who was ousted in july 1979. noriega, considered the real power behind panama's civilian government, was instrumental in the effort
in havana, the cuban foreign ministry issued a statement blaming the situation on an alleged u.s. campaign aimed at extending u.s. control of the panama canal, the cuban news agency prensa latina said in a dispatch monitored friday in mexico city
under a 1977 treaty with the united states, panama is to take over the canal and its defense in 1999
in washington, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said friday that the united states was not considering military intervention in panama, where the u.s. southern command and its 10,000 troops are based
in a statement, the venezuelan government expressed support for delvalle's dismissal order of noriega and called on panama's armed forces to respect it
the venezuelan government reaffirms its unequivocal position on the respect that the military forces in panama owe to the civilian power, as dictated by panama's constitution,'' said the brief communique issued in caracas
in a brief statement, the argentine government said friday it ``would like to make publicly known its solidarity with president eric delvalle.''
el salvador's vice president, rodolfo castillo claramount, called delvalle's ouster ``nothing more than a simple and vulgar coup d'etat carried out by a group of military gorillas headed by noriega.''
castillo calamount told a news conference friday that the salvadoran government ``is seriously considering the possibility of suspending diplomatic relations with the new panamanian government.''
a last-minute plea by gov. evan mecham's new defense team failed to win a delay in his impeachment trial as the arizona supreme court refused to intercede
the four justices who heard his appeal for an emergency stay friday cited constitutional separation of powers in refusing to intervene in the trial scheduled to begin in the state senate monday
however, they said they would consider a more detailed request during the court's regular conference tuesday
senate minority leader alan stephens, a democrat, predicted the justices would not interfere with the nation's first impeachment trial of a governor in half a century
the court's rebuff to mecham capped a turbulent day for the first-term republican governor, who also faces criminal charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan
first, mecham's chief lawyer, murray miller of phoenix, disclosed he had resigned. he said jerris leonard, a washington lawyer and former assistant attorney general under president nixon, was taking charge
we brought in a number of new people and murray chose to leave,'' mecham told the associated press friday night. ``we parted as friends. i've got the best of representation.''
leonard and another addition to the defense team, thomas crowe, promptly launched a last-ditch effort to win a delay that the senate had refused to grant wednesday night
by late friday afternoon, they had filed a stack of legal documents with the supreme court, and the emergency hearing was granted
crowe argued that the governor's constitutional right to due process would be violated if the senate judged him before a jury trial scheduled to begin march 22 on the criminal charges. the arizona civil liberties union filed a friend-of-the-court brief making the same argument
the justices immediately expressed concern about breaching the separation of judicial and legislative powers
even if i agreed with everything you said in your papers,'' said vice chief justice stanley feldman, ``what jurisdiction does this court have to tell the senate what to do in a job that the constitution says should be done by the senate and not the judiciary?''
feldman presided in place of chief justice frank x. gordon, who recused himself because the state constitution requires him to preside over the impeachment trial
attorney john lundin, representing the senate, told the justices: ``you are being asked to enter an arena that has never been entered into by any court in this nation.'' he said they should decline to take that step
mecham was impeached feb. 5 on a 46-14 house vote, forcing him to turn over power temporarily to secretary of state rose mofford
several days later, the house approved 23 impeachment articles, charging mecham with concealing the $350,000 loan to his 1986 campaign, misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by lending it to his auto dealership, and trying to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official
miller, who had represented mecham since october, bowed out abruptly. at first he would not say why, but later expressed bitterness at the way leonard had walked into his office early in the week and announced that mecham had hired him to take over the case
he said leonard, who entered the case tuesday, told him he could not begin such a complex case by monday because ``that would be malpractice.'' but he said leonard later changed his mind
on friday night, leonard and crowe filed a certification with the senate that they are ready to proceed
among those opposing leonard's participation in the case were partners of his own law firm. he was forced to resign from the prestigious washington firm of manatt, phelps, rothenberg, tunney and evans because of his decision to represent mecham
charles t. manatt, senior partner in the firm and a former democratic national committee chairman, said the firm wasn't interested in representing mecham for ``lots of reasons,'' but would not elaborate
sikh extremists were suspected fo killing a hindu police investigator early today and seven members of a sikh family, police in punjab state said
the sikh family was murdered friday night at their farmhouse in the village of talwandi chamchuk, about 25 miles west of amritsar, by six sikh men armed with automatic rifles, said amritsar district chief of police izhar alam
the united news of india news agency quoted unidentified police sources as saying the family apparently refused to pay extortion money to members of the khalistan liberation force, one the of sikh underground separatist groups
khalistan is what the extremists call the independent sikh homeland they have been fighting to establish in the northern indian state since 1982
the victims were identified as pirana singh, 55, his wife, surinder, 50, two sons and two daughters and a visiting relative
the hindu police investigator, jeewan lal, was killed near the town of ludhiana, southeast of amritsar, police said
the latest slayings raised to at least 304 the number of people killed this year in attacks blamed on sikh extremists. nearly two-thirds of the victims have been sikhs
last year, more than 1,000 people were killed in punjab by the militants
sikhs, whose religion is an offshoot of hinduism, claim they are discriminated against by india's hindu majority. sikhs comprise about 2 percent of india's 800 million population but are a majority in punjab

