a popular television actor says he can take his toupe off now that chun doo-hwan is no longer president
park yong-shik, 44, said friday he was forced to wear a hairpiece during chun's seven-year term because he looks strikingly like the balding former president, who was succeeded thursday by roh tae-woo
park said he was banned from appearing on state-run television in 1981 without explanation. park said he found out later it was because he resembled the 57-year-old chun
in 1982, park said, his proposal to wear a toupe and grow a beard to change his appearance was accepted. however, he lost important roles in soap operas and other programs and only received minor parts in historical dramas
i hope such a comic thing will never happen again,'' park said
federal indictments alleging a cuban role in cocaine shipments from colombia marked the third time in recent months that the caribbean island nation has been linked to the narcotics network
the two indictments unsealed friday charged 17 people with smuggling cocaine into florida through a cuban military base, and a federal drug official said the operation apparently had official cooperation
nine defendants had been arrested by friday night, said jack hook, a drug enforcement administration spokesman
cuban president fidel castro's name surfaced in the indictment earlier this month of panamanian strongman gen. maneul antonio noriega. last october, members of a similar drug ring allegedly operating in part through cuba were indicted here
in an interview broadcast on nbc-tv thursday, castro denied there is drug trafficking of any type in his nation, calling cuba ``the cleanest country in the world.''
the evidence in the latest indictment ``does not make a statement that the cuban government has an official policy of assisting drug traffickers,'' said jack. ``what it does say is that when a drug-trafficking, private, light aircraft lands on a military base in cuba and the cocaine is offloaded and placed onto boats destined for the u.s., it is quite clear that somebody on that base in an official capacity is involved.''
the indictments, returned earlier this week by a grand jury here, make no mention of involvement by cuban government officials, said ana barnett, a spokeswoman for the u.s. attorney's office
one indictment charges five people, the other 12
the indictments described four cocaine loads totaling 3,800 pounds. two came through cuba in april and may, one through haiti in october and one through the bahamas. the date of the bahamas shipment was not available
this does not indict or name or allegedly name any cuban officials,'' said hook. ``but it is significant in proving that cuba is most definitely being used as a transshipment point for colombian cocaine destined for the united states.''
hook said he had no information on how far that involvement goes in cuban government
one defendant told an informant that he could arrange cuban coast guard escorts for drug boats leaving cuban waters for florida, he said
hook said the indictment shows that cuba, even with its strict security, is as susceptible to drug trafficking as are other caribbean nations, such as the bahamas and haiti
in october, police broke up a ring that allegedly smuggled drugs into the united states through cuba and other caribbean islands. federal officials said there was no evidence of cuban government involvement
the indictment of noriega charged that castro was aware of the panamanian's drug activities and mediated a dispute over bribe money between noriega and colombia's medellin drug cartel. castro denied those allegations in the nbc interview
nbc also reported thursday that u.s. officials say they have solid evidence that cuban mig fighters and cuban coast guard boats have escorted and protected cocaine shipments on their way from colombia to the florida keys through cuba
authorities charged a fourth american soldier with smuggling cocaine to the united states aboard a u.s. military plane from panama
richard mark williams was charged friday before u.s. magistrate roberto schmidt monge in san juan with smuggling, possession and possession with intent to distribute 17 pounds of cocaine
he was brought from panama to puerto rico on friday, authorities said. his age, rank and hometown were not given
authorities said the cocaine was among 77 pounds confiscated jan. 30 during a u.s. customs service inspection of a u.s. military air command plane traveling from howard air force base in panama to the united states
the plane had stopped for refueling at the u.s. roosevelt roads naval station in northwestern puerto rico, a u.s. commonwealth
williams became the fifth person, four of whom are american soldiers, to be arrested and charged after the cocaine was found on the plane
if convicted, williams could be sentenced to up to 40 years in prison
federal officials said they were seeking one other american, stationed in panama, in the same investigation
information about the case was limited because indictments against the suspects were sealed in u.s. district court in san juan
williams was detained in panama, escorted by military personnel on a commercial flight and arrested by fbi and drug enforcement administration agents on arrival at luis munoz marin international airport in san juan, according to court sources who spoke on condition of anonymity
two other u.s. soldiers facing federal charges of possessing and importing 17 pounds of cocaine on the jan. 30 flight pleaded innocent thursday at their arraignment in the district court
the two, darrin taylor, 19, of chicago, and franklyn milton browne, 19, of far rockaway, n.y., were arrested jan. 30 along with another soldier, bruce morris mack, 20, of gary, ind., and rafael a. valladares, 29, a panamanian, who officials said was carrying false documents identifying him as a u.s. soldier
valladares, a civilian, was dressed in a u.s. army uniform and had dogtags and army travel orders when arrested
valladares and mack were working independently of the other two suspects and of each other, according to arthur barnes, assistant special agent in charge of the dea office in san juan
the san juan star, citing unidentified official sources, reported friday that one american had established drug contacts in panama shortly before or after being discharged from the army and the other had supplied members of a drug ring with bogus travel orders and military identification papers
it quoted the sources as saying one of the men had established contacts with panama's military chief, gen. manuel antonio noriega, who is under indictment in the united states on drug trafficking charges
the authorities now think that the ring had been using military aircraft for at least a year, making weekly trips to the u.s. with the drugs,'' the star reported
it said the ring used fake travel orders, and the men who would transport the drugs would leave on fridays from howard air force base and travel to south carolina and texas, where the narcotics were unloaded. the carriers would be back on the howard base by monday, before they could be declared absent without leave, the newspaper said
a 36-year-old east german man fled uninjured over the heavily fortified border to west germany by climbing fences under cover of darkness, border police said
the man crossed the frontier late thursday near the west german community of philippsthal, 90 miles northeast of frankfurt, said border police in kassel. the escapee was not identified
at least 17 people have fled over east germany's border with west germany and the communist-constructed berlin wall since jan. 1, according to west german officials
senior leader deng xiaoping, who has criticized the personality cult that surrounded mao tse-tung, is the subject of a government-published biography that includes 500 photographs dating back to 1921
among the pictures, half of which are being published for the first time, are shots taken by deng's daughter when mao exiled deng to the countryside during the 1966-76 cultural revolution, the official china daily said today
deng, 83, was branded a capitalist during the upheaval but came back after mao's death in 1976 to steer china on a course of market-oriented reform and opening to the outside world that has significantly improved living standards
the 304-page book, compiled by the official xinhua news agency and the communist party's department on party literature, was described as the most complete and accurate introduction of deng printed in china
the book also contains wartime photos of deng with his wife zhou lin and pictures of him playing billiards and cards, swimming and mountain climbing
more than 250 people, including politburo standing committee member hu qili, gathered at the great hall of the people friday evening to celebrate publication of the book, china daily said
deng, who has cut down his public appearances since retiring from most of his top posts last fall, did not attend the party. although in semi-retirement, he is still regarded as china's most powerful politician
the book has been published in chinese and english, with french, japanese and german editions to come out later
the celebrated case of a wealthy chinese peasant who bought a cropduster for his village has become a tale of woe with the revelation today that the plane never has been used by the farmers
guo yuanying of central henan province bought the ``bee-3'' model ultralight aircraft for $7,258 in april 1984 to help neighbors in spraying pesticides and fertilizer, china's domestic china news service reported
china's official xinhua news agency said at the time that guo, then 37, was the country's first peasant to buy an airplane, drawing from his textile accessory factory's hefty profits
that report said the local government planned to send three peasants to the beijing aeronautical engineering institute to learn to fly and would build a small airfield
but today's report said the local government did not have the money and that the airplane remained at the zhengzhou airport for two years before being donated to a tourist resort near the yellow river, where it has languished in a warehouse
the domestic news service noted that guo's village is in a region plagued by locusts and asked, ``why is it so difficult to utilize modern technology?''
problems forced an army helicopter to land twice before it crashed in a north texas cow pasture, killing 10 soldiers and seriously burning eight, witnesses said
the chinook ch-47d helicopter had been on a routine transport flight from fort hood in central texas to fort sill, okla., when it crashed thursday near chico
the helicopter landed immediately after takeoff from fort hood when pilot ronald w. bender reported that a ``fault light'' on his instrument panel had come on, base spokesman mike miller said
after checking the helicopter, bender again received clearance to take off, and left the base, miller said. the spokesman said it was not unusual for pilots to land to check out warning lights
about 20 minutes later, the helicopter landed near cranfills gap about 45 miles north of fort hood on land owned by rancher john david abdnor
abdnor said the aircraft's engines stopped. he said the helicopter was on the ground about 20 minutes before lifting off and heading north
they opened up the engine on the right side of the back end,'' said capt. calvin turner of killeen, who survived the crash. ``we got back in, strapped up, started flying and all of a sudden we heard a lot of noise
smoke started coming out. we all ran up to the cab (in the front). there was a lot of black smoke, and that's all i remember.''
the seven remaining chinooks at fort sill were grounded and inspections ordered before they can be returned to service, base spokesman richard brown said
investigators were tight-lipped friday on the cause of the crash
we don't have any information about what happened on board. what we're telling ... is that the army is investigating the crash, but anything else i tell you would be either rumor or speculation,'' said fort hood spokesman capt. michael monett
the army just does not discuss an ongoing investigation,'' he said
a pentagon source who asked that his name not be used said army officials had been told ``there was some maintenance work done on the ground after the chinook landed at fort hood.''
but whether that's germane to anything remains to be seen,'' the official added. ``the investigators will have to check into that. there's no indication yet that mechanics worked on something at hood that later could have caused a fire.''
monett said the probe could take a year
seven men, including bender, died at the scene, including one of two soliders who leaped from the flaming aircraft before it crashed
two of the injured were in critical condition today at brooke army medical center in san antonio, three at parkland hospital in dallas were in stable condition, and two at harris methodist hospital were in serious but stable condition, officials said. the eighth was picked up by an army ambulance from bridgeport hospital in wise county
no orders have been issued to ground the entire fleet of ch-47s, said maj. phil soucy, an army spokesman at the pentagon
the army grounded its entire fleet of 63 chinooks for 1{ months in 1985 after an accident in honduras injured eight soldiers. the ch-47d, which has a troop capacity of 44, is a modernized version of the craft used heavily in vietnam
