the government said it freed more than 2,000 prisoners today as part of a ``grand amnesty.'' opposition leaders called the clemency deceitful, claiming 1,200 political prisoners were still in jail
release all prisoners of conscience,'' the national coalition for democracy, the main coalition of dissident groups, said in a statement
the new government of president roh tae-woo said it released 2,134 people from jails today and 5,100 others had their sentences reduced or their civic rights restored
about 125 dissidents were among those freed and 1,606 others had sentences reduced or regained their rights. the rest of the people included in the amnesty were common criminals
dissidents and other prisoners were released early today from prisons in seoul and other cities
roh, who took office thursday with a promise to introduce sweeping democratic reforms, said the amnesty was to build public confidence and underline the government's determination to end decades of authoritarian rule
but the amnesty did not include dissidents who had refused to repent or ``fundamentally reject free democracy,'' the government said. dissidents who had committed serious crimes such as murder or arson were also excluded
among the excluded were prominent dissident leaders chang ki-pyo and kim kun-tae, both serving seven-year terms for inciting riots. amnesty international and other human rights groups have demanded kim's release
about 100 radicals and relatives of jailed dissidents staged a protest today in seoul outside the national council of churches building. they shouted ``release all the prisoners,'' but passersby showed little interest
scuffles, kicking and punching broke out as riot police barred the way when the protesters tried to march. furious protesters hit police with placards and fists and seized several riot shields and smashed them, but they were prevented from marching
dissident leader rev. moon ik-hwan, who had his civic rights restored under the amnesty, told the protesters the amnesty was a fraud. ``as long as there is a single dissident in jail, democracy cannot be achieved,'' he declared
in announcing the ``grand amnesty'' friday, culture and information minister chung han-mo said it was intended to promote ``national harmony and restore public confidence'' in the government
at a news conference today, opposition leader kim dae-jung called for ``total'' amnesty, complaining that the number of political prisoners released constituted only a small portion of political detainees. he called on the government to free all but those who admitted to being communists
communism is outlawed in south korea
kim dae-jung later denounced roh's government at a rally in seoul attended by about 4,000 people. he reiterated his claim that presidential elections in december had been rigged, and urged people to vote for the opposition in upcoming legislative elections
but the veteran opposition leader also said he was willing to give roh a chance to meet his promise to usher in full democracy
i can cooperate with roh as the incumbent ruler in power if he carries out sweeping reforms, including complete freedom, release of all politicl prisoners and full guarantee of other civil rights,'' he said
kim dae-jung and rival opposition leader kim young-sam were both defeated by roh in the presidential balloting, though the winner did not receive a majority of the ballots cast
government officials say 276 political detainees are still behind bars _ 216 still awaiting trial and 60 others serving sentences for serious crimes
the authorities hinted that some of those awaiting trial may be freed when judicial processes are completed
