a federal grand jury has indicted two music promoters, a former radio executive and the wife of one promoter on charges of tax evasion and paying more than $270,000 in cash plus cocaine to get records played on the air
employees of nine radio stations in eight cities were named as receiving the payola between 1980 and 1986, but weren't indicted. some were cooperating with authorities, the government said
two of the stations are in fresno, calif.; and one each in el paso, texas; kansas city, mo.; atlanta; cincinnati; jacksonville, fla.; memphis, tenn.; and charlotte, n.c
the investigation is continuing, but u.s. attorney robert bonner declined to say if more indictments were expected
the three indictments announced friday stem from an investigation that began two years ago
the independent promoters were acting on behalf of virtually all record companies in this country,'' bonner said. but he said there was no evidence that the record companies were aware of the payola
among those indicted friday was independent promoter ralph tashjian, an associate of joseph isgro, a los angeles-based promoter who also has been under investigation but wasn't named in the indictments
tashjian, 39, of san mateo, calif., was accused of giving cash, cocaine and ``other valuable considerations'' to radio station employees. among the records he pushed were duran duran's ``wild boys'' and former led zeppelin lead singer robert plant's ``principle of.''
tashjian also was accused of obstructing justice by falsifying records of his company, ralph tashjian enterprises inc., after learning he was under investigation
tashjian and his wife, valerie, were accused of under-reporting income by $303,988 for 1983, 1984 and 1985, to evade $101,579 in federal taxes
david kenner, attorney for the tashjians, who were arrested at their home thursday, said the couple ``categorically denies any wrongdoing.''
in a second indictment, independent promoter william craig, 42, of scottsdale, ariz., also known as william craighead, was accused of making illegal payments to get records on the air, willfully aiding in the preparation of fraudulent federal tax returns and attempting to evade individual income tax
craig promoted records by janet jackson, culture club, new edition and the eurythmics, among others
a woman who answered one of craig's telephone numbers took a message but said it was doubtful the call would be returned
a third indictment accused george wilson crowell, also known as george wilson, 59, former vice president and general manager of radio station kiqq in los angeles, with willful failure to file federal income tax returns for 1984, 1985 and 1986
crowell's attorney, sidney sodas of milwaukee, wis., had no comment on the indictment
crowell of denver and craig are expected to surrender within the next few days, bonner said
maximum penalties for those indicted are: craig, 18 years in prison, fines of $1.64 million; tashjian, 23 years, $1.53 million; mrs. tashjian, 15 years, $1.5 million; and crowell, three years, $75,000, bonner said. picks up 10th graf pvs, `in the arab ...' ^by karin laub</note>
