secretary of state george p. shultz took his middle east peace plan to syria today after jordan rebuffed his attempt to exclude the soviet union and the plo from middle east peace negotiations
obviously that's their point of view,'' shultz said in amman after hearing jordanian demands sharply at odds with u.s. and israeli positions
shultz has called for palestinian participation in negotiations, but not participation by the palestine liberation organization
shultz also opposes an active role for the soviets in shaping a middle east settlement to end the arab-israeli dispute
but jordanian foreign minister taher masri, while calling shultz's meeting with jordanian officials ``serious and useful,'' said the only way for a peace settlement was through an international conference, including the soviets and the plo
in israel, shultz also encountered resistance from prime minister yitzhak shamir to his plea for an accelerated timetable for negotiations leading to talks on a final settlement by december
israeli sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said shamir urged shultz to move slowly on the issue of palestinian self-rule despite the 11 weeks of anti-occupation unrest
the u.s. plan calls for immediate talks on palestinian self-rule and negotiations by december on the final status of the west bank and gaza strip, which israel seized from egypt and jordan in the 1967 middle east war
shultz had hoped with his mission to diffuse unrest on the occupied territories, where palestinians have clashed with israeli soldiers almost daily since since dec. 8
a further setback was a boycott friday in jerusalem by 15 palestinians invited by shultz to discuss their aspirations for national rights
after the boycott, shultz read a statement carried on israeli television to arabs in the region saying, ``opportunity knocks loudly on your door. now is the time to get to work.''
in amman, the plo said today it is willing to meet u.s. officials ``on any level,'' and said american rejection of a meeting shows the united states is not serious about arab-israeli peace
u.s. policy forbids american diplomats to meet ranking plo officials because the the administration regards the plo as a terrorist organization
shultz pushed on and flew to damascus to discuss the gloomy outlook with syrian president hafez assad, whom he has described as a key player in any middle east settlement
shultz is the first u.s. secretary of state to visit damascus since 1983
in amman, masri said the permanent members of the u.n. security council _ the united states, the soviet union, china, britain and france _ and the plo must be invited to peace talks
israel refuses to deal with the plo, which is waging a guerrilla war against the jewish state, and israel has u.s. backing for this position
shultz also supports shamir in trying to keep the soviets from trying to influence the outcome of any peace talks
in jerusalem, u.s. diplomats tried again to arrange a meeting between shultz and palestinian figures
in his television statement friday, shultz implied the palestinians were afraid to meet him because they would be defying the plo, which instructed palestinians in the occupied territories to boycott shultz's invitation
peace-making is difficult,'' shultz said. ``peace has its enemies, but peace is a necessary ingredient to a decent life.''
the stopover in amman was not considered critical, since king hussein is in london, where he will meet with shultz on tuesday
on sunday, shultz meets again with shamir and foreign minister shimon peres before leaving for cairo to see egyptian president hosni mubarak
shultz returns to jerusalem again sunday night for further talks with shamir
a u.s. navy ship docked in the southern port city of pusan on saturday and discharged the first u.s. soldiers and equipment to arrive for large military exercises, news reports said
the yonhap news agency said the 26,000-ton regulus arrived from takoma, wash., carrying 714 u.s. soldiers, 14 helicopters, three tractors and 1,036 trucks
the united states and south korea plan to deploy about 200,000 soldiers in the annual ``team spirit'' exercises, scheduled to run from late february to early may
u.s. officials said the exercises this year will involve about 60,000 u.s. military personnel along with u.s. and south korean jets, a u.s. aircraft carrier and escorting warships
about 40,000 u.s. troops from bases in the pacific and the united states are to be brought in to join american troops based in south korea
north korea has strongly opposed the exercises
mozambican rebels sank six military patrol boats on lake nyassa in northwestern mozambique after killing dozens of soldiers elsewhere in the country, the rebels said saturday
the mozambican national resistance said in a statement distributed in lisbon that it sank the boats feb. 20 at the metangula base on the eastern shore of lake nyassa, which borders mozambique, malawi and tanzania
the statement said the attack put a company of 100 mozambican marines out of action, but it did not mention casualties. rebel spokesmen could not be contacted for comment saturday
guerrillas also captured three towns in northeastern niassa province feb. 22 and 23, the statement said. it gave no further details
the right-wing rebels, also known as renamo, have been fighting since 1977 to topple mozambique's marxist government. south africa denies mozambican charges it supports the group
the rebels also said they killed several cuban and soviet advisers and captured 43 mozambican soldiers feb. 17 in an attack on the town of bela vista, 30 miles south of the capital, maputo
on the day same, the rebels claimed they occupied the town of lugela in central zambezia province, killing 18 mozambican troops and 17 tanzanian soldiers fighting for the government
there was no independent confirmation of the claims nor any indication of rebel casualties
since mid-1985, top leaders of the united democratic front have been facing treason charges in a trial viewed as a likely prelude to a ban on the nationwide anti-apartheid coalition
last week, the government decided not to wait for a verdict
it banned all the group's activities and imposed severe restrictions on the few coalition leaders still free. most of the 18 groups banned from political activity last week were affiliated with the front
the apparent goal of the ban was to stamp out a grass-roots movement that in less than five years had become the largest _ and in many ways the most potent _ opposition group in south africa's history
the united democratic front has proved resilient before, and it may survive this latest blow. even if it does not, its legacy seems assured
the (coalition) was the most effective political force that has operated in black townships ever,'' said tom lodge, a political scientist at johannesburg's university of the witwatersrand
the activist spirit fostered by the group ``will continue under different forms and will always present a challenge to the government,'' lodge said
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
before aug. 20, 1983, when the united democratic front was launched at rally near cape town, south africa had never experienced anything like the coalition
it represented the first attempt to meld local and regional anti-apartheid groups into a single network. it pledged itself both to militance and to non-violence
and though it has always been predominantly black, it welcomed white and asian members who embraced its ideals
the coalition grew to encompass more than 600 organizations with about 2 million members. the affiliates include church, civic, educational and youth groups extending into virtually every black township in the country
its original goal was to oppose formation of the tricameral parliament, which has chambers for whites, asians and people of mixed-race but excludes the black majority. it backed a boycott of the 1984 elections for the asian and mixed-race chambers, contributing to turnouts of less than 30 percent
since then, coalition affiliates have waged a variety of campaigns, ranging from prolonged rent boycotts to advocacy of greater black control over education
some analysts say the group's most impressive achievement has been psychological _ convincing ordinary people that it was worth organizing to build unified opposition to apartheid
the rev. allan boesak, a prominent activist who helped found the coalition, said after learning of wednesday's crackdown that the group's day-to-day operations were less important that its symbolism to blacks
it's a living sign that our of belief that the days of white dominance are over,'' he said. ``that's something you cannot ban.''
twice, the government has charged groups of prominent united democratic front officials with treason in an effort to prove that the coalition conspired with the outlawed african national congress guerrilla movement to provoke violence and make south africa ``ungovernable.''
one group, including co-presidents archie gumede and albertina sisulu, went free after the case against them collapsed for lack of evidence
but three other officials, including its national secretary and its chief spokesman, have been held since 1985 during the country's longest-running political trial. they and 16 co-defendants who are free on bail dispute government charges that the organization instigated the black unrest that broke out in september 1984 and claimed some 2,500 lives over the next three years
many activists had predicted that a guilty verdict at the treason trial would be followed by a ban on the coalition
the trials have been only one of several tactics used by the government to weaken the coalition, which in many instances has been forced to operate clandestinely. virtually all of its national executive committee members have been detained or gone into hiding during the 20-month-old state of emergency, and the few who remained in the open were issued banning orders last week barring them from united democratic front activity
according to monitoring groups, about 75 percent of the estimated 30,000 people detained for varying periods during the emergency belonged to the coalition's affiliates
the government has accused the group of contributing to a ``revolutionary climate'' in which its followers rejected established institutions and harassed or killed blacks linked to the white authorities
gumede, in recent interviews, acknowledged that some coalition followers had resorted to coercion and said the government's restrictions on the group's leaders made it difficult to instill discipline
we are on the run,'' he told leadership magazine late last year. ``sooner or later, we are going to find ourselves in a real jam, because people do not have sufficient time to think.''
gumede is now banned from giving interviews or speaking publicly. his co-president, mrs. sisulu, is under police orders to stay in her home between 6 p.m. and 5 p.m
as they learned of the restrictions, an unsigned coalition statement was distributed to the news media
its closing message: ``nothing, we repeat nothing, will stand in the way of the united democratic front as it carries out its historical task and duty of uniting the oppressed and silenced people of our country.''
