teen-age aids victim ryan white is going to washington, d.c., this week in hopes that his experience with the disease will help schools cope with others like him, his mother says
he wants to try to make it better for everybody else,'' jeanne white said friday
ryan and jill stewart, student council president at hamilton heights high school, are scheduled to speak to the presidential commission on aids at a public hearing thursday
after ryan, 16, was diagnosed as having acquired immune deficiency syndrome in december 1984, kokomo school officials and parents fought to keep him out of school. the whites moved to cicero, where ryan was accepted by the community and enrolled in classes
ryan plans to read to the commission excerpts from a paper he wrote for his school english class. the paper, titled the odyssey, recounts the problems he encountered at kokomo, white said
he wants to tell why education is important to him and why he wanted to go back to school. it outlines the fight to go back to school and some of the fear and panic that happened while he was attending school there.''
