former interior secretary james watt says he thinks cuba's purported use of isolation camps for aids victims is a good idea, but he says the united states lacks the courage to do the same
watt, who served under president reagan from 1980-83, said he favors a quarantine and called aids ``the first politically protected disease in america.''
when a member of the audience asked whether such tactics would violate human rights, watt responded, `do you want an aids victim to sneeze on your salad when he's serving you at a local restaurant?''
experts say that acquired immune deficiency syndrome cannot be spread through casual contact. the disease, caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, is spread most often through sexual contact and needles or syringes shared by drug abusers
speaking thursday at weber state college, watt said it was his statement about the ethnic makeup of his staff that forced him to quit. he described his staff as including ``a black, a white, two jews and a cripple.''
watt said he now agrees it was an ``insensitive statement,'' but feels the only offensive part of the comment was the use of the word cripple
the new word is handicapable,'' watt said. ``i'm from wyoming and didn't know that.''
students walking by the little red schoolhouse on the grounds of governor dummer academy, the nation's oldest boys boarding school, are likely to be thinking about calculus or on their way to play soccer
but 225 years ago, when the school opened, the tiny schoolhouse contained the only classroom on campus and the emphasis was on greek and latin
on march 1, 1763, 27 boys with names like theophilus parsons, eliphalet pearson and samuel sewall crowded into the two rooms. of the early graduates, one became a signer of the u.s. constitution, another the first u.s. postmaster general, two were appointed president of harvard and 16 served in congress
the gulf that separates that fledling institution from today's school, one of about 100 new england boarding schools, may seem tremendous. but students and faculty at the picturesque school 33 miles north of boston said the traditions that bound the first graduates have not changed
david williams, 60, has taught at governor dummer since 1951. like samuel moody, who greeted the first boys at the school in 1763, williams is a ``senior master,'' a teacher considered a ``24-hour-a-day influence.'' he has also coached athletics and served as a dorm master for years
williams typifies the school's philosophy of combining a family atmosphere with strict discipline and a heavy dose of sports
williams said he remained at the school ``because i loved the kids. i never encountered such a genuine relationship between old and young.''
many of the 342 students at the school, where girls were admitted in 1971, echo such sentiments
stephen kim, 18, of concord, transferred here from the middlesex school and said ``i'm a lot happier. it's a much better environment.''
it's more of a family atmosphere,'' said amy russell, 16, from hampton falls, n.h. ``there's a lot of bonding here because you know everybody.''
both students and faculty here claim that their school is less stereotypically elite than more prestigious schools like phillips exeter academy in new hampshire, or choate, in connecticut
it's not as cliquey here,'' said amy shafmaster, 15, of durham, n.h. ``you can't really tell how rich someone is here the way you can at other schools.''
faculty and students admit that the cloistered environment of today's school is more removed from the real world than it was when the school was first founded by the will of lt. gov. william dummer of the massachusetts bay province
we're babied a little because we're so sheltered here,'' said michelle kahn, 16, from atlanta. ``we should have to make more decisions.''
the curriculum is strict but well-rounded; art is a required course. a senior's typical workload might include advanced biology, calculus, religion, u.s. history, english and ``advanced improvisational music.''
the cost for boarding school students is $12,700; nonboarding day students also attend. school officials said almost all graduates enter college
drugs and alcohol have been an issue on campus but discipline problems at the school seem trite by comparison with public schools. one student was expelled recently for stealing several cases of soda from the headmaster's house
peter bragdon, 52, the school's 26th headmaster, dismisses any notions that boarding schools like governor dummer are arcane ivory towers
there are eternal laws and values that do not vary over time,'' bragdon said about the conventional values still taught at the school. he said boarding schools offer students superior academic standards as well as a more stable adolescence
boarding schools often give fairer treatment to (teen-agers) than parents do,'' bragdon said
a bomb attached to a motorcycle exploded saturday in a town near the afghan border, killing five people and injuring 11, officials said
police, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the blast occurred in the afternoon at the main bazaar in tal, about 10 miles east of the afghan border
they said three of the dead and nine of the wounded were afghan refugees
about 3.5 million people from afghanistan have sought shelter in pakistan since afghanistan's civil war broke out in april 1978
there was no immediate claim of responsibility for the explosion. the pakistan government has blamed a spate of terrorist bombings in the past year on agents of afghanistan's soviet-backed government
an estimated 115,000 soviet troops are in afghanistan helping the marxist government fight a moslem insurgency
democrats are vowing to continue the fight for campaign spending reform that led to a 53-hour filibuster last week, possibly by introducing a constitutional amendment that would allow congress to set federal limits
we must not and we will not give up this fight,'' sen. david boren, d-okla., said saturday in the weekly democratic radio address
this issue simply does not grab the headlines, like a foreign policy emergency or a financial crisis. yet it is just as serious,'' said boren, a principal author of the scuttled bill that would have set voluntary limits
the way we're financing campaigns in this country is like a silent deadly cancer eating away at the very heart of our democratic system. too much money pumped into campaigns, too many special interests threaten the integrity of the election process itself.''
senate majority leader robert byrd, d-w.v., already has said he plans to continue the quest to combat the escalating cost of winning senate seats
this issue will come back again and again,'' byrd said. ``it will not be swept under the rug.''
a senator in the middle of the partisan battle said democratic leaders are thinking about bringing a proposed constitutional amendment to the floor to replace the legislation effectively killed by stubborn opposition from minority republicans
the proposed amendment that would give congress the specific authority, now lacking because of a 1976 supreme court decision, to set mandatory limits on how much federal candidates can spend on campaigns
it's a distinct and likely possibility the constitutional amendment will surface in the next few weeks,'' said the senator, who spoke on condition of anonymity. the senator was a leader in last week's failed effort by democrats to get a vote on their bill to set voluntary spending limits
byrd would not say whether he planned to push the proposed constitutional amendment. ``that is one of the options,'' he said, and did not elaborate
the campaign spending bill, carrying 52 of the 100 senators as co-sponsors, was scuttled for the 1988 session friday when democrats fell seven votes short of the 60 they needed to curtail a gop talkathon and force a vote on the bill
the 53-41 roll call represented the eighth time since last june that republicans had defeated attempts by byrd to limit debate on the campaign spending bill
boren, in the radio address, called it a ``tragedy'' that members of both political parties could not agree on limiting campaign costs. he said the average cost of running a successful race for the u.s. senate has gone up 500 percent in 10 years to about $3 million and declared, ``it is time for us, all of us, to wake up and speak out before it's too late.''
we're not going to give up, either,'' said acting minority leader alan simpson, r-wyo. ``we have slayed the dragon eight times. ... the deed is done, and we ought to move on to other things.''
republicans refused to negotiate with democrats over spending limits, saying such restrictions would doom their party to minority status in states where democrats have a big edge in voter registration
they offered to discuss restricting how much special-interest political action committees can give to senate candidates, but democrats said that without spending limits, pacs would find other ways pump money into political campaigns
the proposed constitutional amendment has been laying fallow in the judiciary committee. its principal sponsor is sen. ernest hollings, d-s.c., who was not a co-sponsor of the voluntary limits bill
the hollings legislation is a response to the supreme court's buckley vs. valeo ruling in 1976 that held congress, absent a constitutional change, cannot restrict how much money a candidate can on a campaign
hollings' proposal, which has 19 sponsors, states simply that ``the congress may enact laws regulating the amounts of contributions and expenditures intended to affect elections to federal offices.''
a proposed amendment needs 67 votes to pass the senate, a similar two-thirds margin in the house and then ratification by at least 38 states
mathematics seem to be against byrd if he brings the hollings legislation to the floor. he needed 60 votes to force a roll call on the voluntary limit bill and never had more than 55, including two missing from friday's vote
however, the sponsor mix on the hollings bill is different than the one debated last week. three of its cosponsors _ richard shelby, d-ala., ted stevens, r-alaska, and strom thurmond, r-s.c. _ opposed cloture
if byrd could hold his 55 votes and pick up these three senators, he would need to find only two more to break any gop filibuster against the hollings bill
once this measure came to a vote, he would have to find the other votes for passage from a handful of republicans who are said to support spending limits but who stayed loyal to their party's position against the voluntary limit proposal
a woman celebrating her birthday was burned and temporarily blinded by a snail that exploded on her plate at a city restaurant, police said saturday
karen j. prouty, 36, of north syracuse, was about to take her second bite of a bubbling order of escargot friday night when one of the snails exploded, burning her around her right eye, police said. she couldn't see for about 90 minutes afterward
i just immediately broke down crying,'' prouty said saturday. she was treated at university hospital in syracuse and released friday night
the dinner at pascale's wine bar and restaurant was a birthday surprise arranged by her husband and sister, prouty said
the restaurant's owner, charles pascale, assured her he would pay for any medical expenses and for damage to her white linen dress, prouty said. he also offered her a free dinner
a restaurant worker referred a call saturday to maitre d' fred rosener, who was not immediately available for comment
but pascale told police the snail probably was blown apart by the pressure of steam building up in an air pocket
i enjoy escargot, but i probably will be very hesitant to order it again,'' prouty said
rear adm. anthony a. less took command saturday of the u.s. navy's escort squadron in the persian gulf, inheriting a force that u.s. officials say has lost no clout despite a cutback in strength
hours before the ceremony, two u.s. warships sailed through the strait of hormuz into the gulf to complete the restructuring that leaves 25 american warships in the region, including 16 in the gulf-based middle east force
less, a career aviator who once commanded the navy's famed ``blue angels'' jet acrobatics team, became the 36th commander of the middle east force in a shipboard ceremony that dates back to the british navy at the time of the american revolution in 1776
government officials and gulf area diplomats attended the wind-chilled, sunset event aboard the 17,000-ton amphibious assault ship coronado, newly designated flagship of the middle east force
the force has operated in the gulf since 1949, assigned to represent and protect u.s. national interests in the vital oil waterway
it attracted little recent attention until last year's controversial decision by the reagan administration to register 11 kuwaiti tankers under the u.s. flag, qualifying them for american protection from iranian attack
following that move, and the may 17 attack by an iraqi jet on the u.s. frigate stark in which 37 americans were killed, the navy's forces in the region grew to a peak strength of nearly 40 ships, including two battle groups in the arabian sea and indian ocean
inside the gulf, the force nearly tripled from about half a dozen vessels to 17 at the start of 1988
in a speech on board the coronado, gen. george b. crist, a marine who heads the u.s. central command, noted that a year ago the united states had only about six ships in the gulf
this rapid buildup of deterrent power and the successes we have achieved did not come easily,'' crist said. ``dramatic and often traumatic decisions and efforts were required.''
crist's tampa, fla.-based headquarters is responsible for u.s. military concerns in 19 countries from africa to pakistan, encompassing the middle east region
crist also said he understood the new commander's motto was ``do more with less,'' an allusion to the pentagon's move to trim the cost and size of the escort operation by cutting the force from 17 to 16 ships
on feb. 3, the 50-year-old less also assumed command of the joint task force middle east, the arabian sea support group that also has been scaled down
in saturday's ceremony, less replaced rear adm. harold j. bernsen, who has headed the middle east force since july 1986 and before that was skipper of the flagship la salle during the 1979 hostage crisis in iran and the outbreak of the iraq-iran war in 1980
u.s. officials recently estimated the cost of the operations at $15 million to $20 million a month, but said the cutback did not result from a budget squeeze or a lessening of the iranian threat
the united states will make no reciprocal gesture to moscow's decision to withdraw some nuclear missiles and troops from eastern europe, the u.s. ambassador to nato said saturday
alton g. keel jr. said the soviet move, rather than being a meaningful expression of good will, was part of an orchestrated campaign to convince west europeans that the soviet union is changing its ways
we, obviously from the u.s. standpoint, welcome the fact that they're withdrawing the missiles, but there'll be no similar action on the part of the u.s.,'' keel said in an interview at his official residence outside brussels
soviet soldiers on thursday left two bases in east germany and one garrison in czechoslovakia, taking with them the first nuclear missiles dismantled under a u.s.-soviet treaty eliminating all land-based nuclear rockets with ranges between 310 miles and 3,100 miles
the missiles moved out of east germany and czechoslovakia, known in the west as ss-12s, have ranges of up to 550 miles
the treaty signed by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev last dec. 8 does not require either side to withdraw or destroy any missiles until it has been ratified by both governments. the u.s. senate is expected to approve it by late spring
keel said washington could not withdraw any of its more than 400 tomahawk cruise and pershing 2 ballistic nuclear missiles from western europe until after the senate decides whether to ratify the treaty
he noted that the soviets have said they will not actually destroy any of the withdrawn ss-12 missiles until after the treaty has been ratified by the senate and by the soviet parliament, the supreme soviet
they obviously want to take as much advantage of their having been willing to enter into this agreement as possible, use it to advantage, try to convince european publics that there's been major new thinking in the soviet union,'' he said
keel said the united states already had shown its good will by voluntarily halting deployment of cruise and pershing 2 missiles as soon as the treaty was signed
we actually did concede something unilaterally, we conceded that we would no longer deploy systems,'' even though nato had not yet reached its original target of deploying 572 of the medium-range missiles, he said
the soviet move, he said, did little to increase the security of nato nations, which continues to be threatened by the existence of more than 1,400 short-range soviet nuclear missiles in europe and a warsaw pact numerical edge over the western alliance in non-nuclear arms
keel said it ``would be meaningful'' if moscow unilaterally withdrew some of its shortest-range nuclear arms and conventionally armed troops, but that nato would make no reciprocal gesture because its forces already are at a bare minimum to deter a possible soviet attack
here is the text of the democratic party's response, delivered by sen. david l. boren of oklahoma, to president reagan's radio address on saturday:
i welcome this chance to talk with you today, not as a democratic senator from oklahoma, but as a fellow american, about a problem that should concern all of us
have you ever had the urge to start shouting, ``wake up, wake up,'' to those around you to warn them about some danger that they just don't seem to see?
i had that feeling this past week as we debated about campaign reform in the u.s. senate
this issue simply does not grab the headlines like a foreign policy emergency or a financial crisis, yet is just as serious. the way we're financing campaigns in this country is like a silent deadly cancer eating away at the very heart of our democratic system
too much money pumped into campaigns by too many special interests threatens the integrity of the election process itself. did you know that in just 10 short years the average cost of running a successful race for the u.s. senate has gone up 500 percent, and that the average cost, in even small states, rose to $3 million?
that means that in order to finance a successful campaign for re-election, a sitting senator must raise an average of $10,000 in campaign contributions every single week of his or her six-year term. that's $10,000 every week for 300 weeks in a row
this money chase for campaign contributions raises several problems. first, it means that congressmen and senators are having to spend their time and energy raising campaign money instead of working to solve the serious problems facing our country
we need our congress on the job, and not having to go out and raise campaign funds. second, campaigns now cost so much that members can't raise enough to finance them from their home states alone. they have to fly all around the country to cities in other states where they can raise campaign funds instead of spending time in their own states listening to the people back home to learn about their problems
finally, to raise the millions of dollars in needed campaign funds, congressmen and senators have turned more and more to special interest groups and political action committees known as pacs. in the last election, almost 200 members elected to congress received over half of their campaign funds from pacs, often controlled by lobbyists in washington, instead of from the people back home
what's going to happen to grassroots democracy if this trend continues? americans must ask themselves, is it good for our country that the cost of campaigns has skyrocketed to $3 million? is it good for our country that the fastest growing source of these funds is from narrow special interest groups based outside a member's home state?
the american people say no. in a recent harris survey, 91 percent of those surveyed said this explosion of campaign costs is a serious problem and it must be addressed. ninety-one percent of the american people, democrats and republicans alike, want their respresentatives to act. this last week the senate tried to act. fifty-two senators, over half of the members, joined in sponsoring a bill to put limits on runaway campaign spending
tragically a determined minority blocked the senate from even being able to consider this bill. among democrats the vote was 48 to 2 in favor of action. among republicans, it was 38 to 3 against proceeding. i call this a tragedy because we should not break down along party lines. we need to unite as americans to solve this serious problem which affects all of us
the supporters of the bill offered to change it to make sure it would be fair to both political parties. but opponents said that they would never even discuss putting limits on campaign spending. we must not and we will not give up this fight
in a few weeks congressmen will spread out across this country to speak at high school graduating ceremonies. when we urge those students to some day think of running for office to serve their country, will we also to have to tell them that at the current rate of increasing campaign costs, 12 years from now when they're old enough to run, the average u.s. senate race will cost $15 million? will we have to challenge them not only to think about what they'd like todo to help their country, but also to think about how they will raise $15 million to run for the u.s. senate?
we must not let that happen to america. we must not cloud the future of the next generation. it's time for us, all of us, to wake up and speak out before it's too late
