we must not let that happen to america. we must not cloud the future of the next generation. it's time for us, all of us, to wake up and speak out before it's too late. iranian claims that iraqi helicopters downed. picks up 10th graf, `the iraqi ...'</note>
iraq said waves of its fighter-bombers attacked iran's key oil refineries in tehran and other cities saturday in strikes aimed at crippling iran's economy
iran responded quickly by shelling a border town. later it also shelled the southern iraqi port, basra, and vowed to strike baghdad
an iraqi military spokesman warned that if any iraqi city was hit ``all iranian cities, including tehran, will become targets for our missiles, air force jets and other weapons.''
saturday's raids and threats rekindled fears of a flare-up in the ``war of the cities,'' which has left thousands dead since 1984
tehran radio, monitored in nicosia, said at least one civilian was killed and an undisclosed number were wounded in the raid on the capital's southern suburbs. it did not mention the other raids
baghdad's official news agency said iranian artillery gunners retaliated by shelling basra and the border town of al-qurna, just north of the port city. it said five civilians were killed and 14 others wounded in basra. two civilians were killed and two others wounded in shelling on al-qurna, the agency said
iraqi authorities also reported carrying out evacuation exercises in baghdad, basra and other cities at risk of reprisals from iranian air, missile or artillery
the iraqi news agency said that apart from the raids on economic targets, the iraqi air force saturday flew 101 combat missions against iranian troops concentrations, the highest one-day total in months
helicopter gunships flew another 72 missions, it added
tehran radio said two iraqi helicopters were shot down. iraq's news agency denied the claim
the iraqi raids marked a sharp escalation in the stalemated 7-year-old war and came as iraq's army braced for new iranian ground offensives
tehran radio and ina, also monitored in nicosia, said the air raids took place just before noon
ina reported the iranian refineries were ``destroyed ... and shattered'' and left shrouded in flames and smoke. but it did not identify them
iran's main refineries are located near tehran, the northwestern city of tabriz, the central city of isfahan and the southern city of shiraz
a sustained air offensive against iran's industrial centers in 1986 cut its refining capacity of 625,000 barrels a day by almost half, forcing tehran to import petroleum products and ration gasoline for the first time since the war began
it was not clear whether saturday's reported raids marked the start of a new air offensive to throttle iran's war-battered economy. but the iraqi air force has been concentrating in recent months on hitting iran's oil exports, the country's economic jugular
ina quoted a military communique as saying ``large numbers'' of iraqi jets took part in the attacks ``deep inside iranian territory.''
it said all the planes returned safely to their bases
the refineries were iran's ``economic mainstays and linked with the war effort'' of ayatollah ruhollah khomeini's fundamentalist regime ``for prolonging aggression on iraq,'' the communqiue added
iran's war information headquarters in tehran swiftly announced that ``iraq's military and economic centers'' in baghdad and basra will be hit ``within the next few hours'' and urged civilians to evacuate areas around likely targets
it did not specify how iran would hit back. but the iranians, their badly depleted air force outnumbered 8-1 by iraq, usually retaliate against baghdad with soviet-made scud-b missiles supplied by libya and syria
basra is within easy range of iranian artillery and has been repeatedly bombarded in the last 18 months, with more than 1,500 civilians killed by some 62,000 shells
at appalling cost, iranian revolutionary guards battled to within six miles of basra a year ago and still hold a bridgehead in marshland east of the city
the iraqi air force last attacked major economic targets deep inside iran feb. 11, when its soviet-built mig-21 and sukhoi su-20 fighter-bombers raided a power plant and fuel depots in southwest iran and an electronics factory in shiraz
the iranian air force, despite chronic shortages of spares that have grounded most of its aging u.s.-made f-4 and f-5 planes, has also seen action recently, mainly attacking iraqi defenses and supply dumps around basra
these almost daily raids have heightened iraqi fears that the iranians plan a new offensive against the strategic city that lies on the shatt al-arab waterway, the prewar southern boundary between the two countries
the iranians have been massing troops in the southern sector since november, but have so far not launched any significant thrust there
western military analysts and diplomats in baghdad said the iranians have concentrated up to 150,000 men in the south
but the analysts believe iran cannot launch an all-out push because it has not been able to mobilize enough men to wage a sustained campaign
the white house cleanup crew was at work once again last week, attempting to clarify remarks president reagan made at his wednesday evening news conference
the president's comments were only the latest in what is an increasingly bulging file of eyebrow-raising statements he has made at news conferences over the years. the gaffes have ranged from erroneous economic statistics to misconstrued versions of events around the world
at wednesday's session, reagan remarked that palestinian unrest in israeli-occupied territory has been caused by ``outsiders coming in.''
it was followed quickly by a comment from secretary of state george shultz, who told reporters the conflict's ``fundamental origins are essentially indigenous.''
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the two answers were ``totally consistent as far as we're concerned.''
the president also asserted that shultz and former defense secretary caspar weinberger had not objected to the secret arms sale to iran on the grounds that it was an arms-for-hostages deal
shultz and weinberger have insisted that they did raise such objections, contentions supported by congress' iran-contra report and by a comment the president himself made a year ago
and reagan also spoke of divisions among blacks in white-ruled south africa, stating, ``it is a tribal policy more than it is a racial policy, and that is one of the most difficult parts here.''
fitzwater said he could not elaborate on the remark
the confusion that trailed reagan's comments echoed the discrepancies that have emerged from many of the previous 41 news conferences the president has held during his seven years in the white house
at a june 11, 1987, news conference at the economic summit in venice, italy, the president sent his aides scrambling when he stated that he believed the dollar's value could decline further ``within reason.''
the administration was trying to halt the dollar's slide at the time, and fitzwater quickly issued a statement denying that the president wanted the decline to resume
he wants stability in the dollar,'' the spokesman said
on nov. 19, 1986, as the iran-contra affair was emerging, reagan told reporters that the united states ``had nothing to do with'' and ``did not condone'' arms shipments to iran by third countries
soon after the news conference ended, white house officials issued a statement conceding that a third country was involved in the secret shipments. the country turned out to be israel
at that same news conference, reagan said the tow anti-tank missiles included in the shipments to iran are ``shoulder-carried,'' when in fact they are much too large for that and are normally fired from a jeep
the president ignited a controversy june 11, 1986, when he said that if any americans were starving or undernourished, it was from ignorance about where to get free food, not from lack of sustenance
i find it difficult also to find any cases of starvation and undernourishment,'' he said
democrats criticized the president for terminating a program that publicized the food stamp program. rep. leon panetta, d-calif., said there were hungry people ``a few blocks from the white house.''
on feb. 18, 1982, reagan offered an account of the early years of u.s. involvement in vietnam. he stated that president kennedy authorized the sending of the first combat troops into vietnam, which did not occur until president johnson's administration
reagan also said north vietnamese leader ho chi minh had ``refused to participate'' in national elections after the french withdrawal from indochina. in fact, the south vietnamese government refused to hold preparatory talks with north vietnam, and documents showed that american diplomats urged the south vietnamese to insist on conditions the communists would not accept
the elections were never held
the associated press and other news organizations double-checked comments the president made at a jan. 19, 1982, news conference, and challenged six statements
reagan said 1 million more people were at work than in 1980. in fact, there were 94,000 fewer people with jobs in december 1981 than in december 1980, according to official government figures, and the white house later conceded that reagan ``misspoke.''
among other statements at that news conference, reagan said:
_ the steel industry had commenced a multi-billion dollar expansion program. industry officials said there were plans to modernize some factories, but that there were few proposals to expand
_ a pima county, ariz., program for feeding the elderly saved $50,000 by eliminating administrative help and doubled the people they served. the program director denied that
_ interest rates had dropped during his year in office. although some short-term rates had fallen, rates on long-term government bonds _ the best indicator of long-term rates _ and home mortgage rates had increased
demonstrators stoned the israeli embassy and broke several windows saturday during a protest against the crackdown on palestinians in israeli-occupied territories
about 200 greek cyriots broke through a police cordon and barbed wire barricades blocking access to the embassy building in a narrow suburban street
they stood outside the tall wire fence of the embassy compound and burned an israeli flag, threw stones at the building and chanted anti-israeli slogans
police reinforcements managed to drive the protesters away within a few minutes
we have had many windows broken, but nobody has been hurt,'' said an israeli diplomat at the embassy who answered a telephone call from the associated press. he declined to give his name
the demonstrators marched to the embassy after staging a protest rally in the capital's main square
one of the placards carried by the demonstrators said ``dachau lives again,'' a reference to one of the nazi death camps where millions of jews were incinerated during world war ii
other placards said ``palestinians have a right to self-determination,'' and ``israel, stop killing palestinians.''
the demonstration coincided with the opening session in nicosia of a hearing by the international secretariat of the inquiry commission into israeli crimes against the lebanese and palestinian people
the inquiry, which held its session at a nicosia hotel, includes european judicial and legal personalities sympathetic to the palestinian cause. it is headed by british lawyer john platts-mills
nasreen bsisso, a palestinian woman expelled from israel two years ago, told the inquiry that 138 palestinians have been killed and more than 2,000 have been seriously wounded since the unrest in the west bank and gaza strip started on dec. 8
u.n. figures place the number of dead at 69
jabril mahmoud rujub, 35, one of four palestinians expelled from israel last month, said he had spent 17 years in israeli prisons and gave extensive testimony to the inquiry about prison conditions
since there is no death penalty in israel, they try to kill the prisoners through torture and illtreatment,'' he said
yasser arafat, chairman of the palestine liberation organization, said in a message to the inquiry that its work ``will unmask and expose israeli crimes and barbaric practices.''
he said israel ``would not be able to carry out these barbaric crimes without the total support and unlimited aid it receives from the american administration.''
five people accused of planting bombs in iran were sentenced to death and executed saturday, tehran television reported
the television did not identify the five nor say whether they were among 30 people arrested earlier for allegedly planting bombs in tehran and western iran in recent weeks
the television broadcast, monitored in nicosia, said: ``the islamic revolutionary court announced that five agents related to the global arrogance who were accused of planting bombs that caused some death and injuries, were sentenced to death and executed saturday evening.''
it gave no other details. but iranian leaders and the news media usually refer to the superpowers as global arrogance
the arrest of the 30 people was disclosed earlier saturday by an iranian security chief in a statement broadcast on tehran radio
sarajeddin mussavi, commander of the islamic revolutionary committees, had said the alleged bombers were ``paid iraqi agents'' who will shortly be handed over to revolutionary courts for trial
most saboteurs are branded iraqi agents by iranian authorities. death is the usual penalty for those convicted of bombings and several have been executed by firing squad in recent months
mussavi said in an interview on the state-run radio that the alleged saboteurs had confessed to two bombings in tehran earlier this month
the last reported bombing in the iranian capital was feb. 18, when a car bomb exploded on the mohammed ali jenah expressway, wounding two people. another 10 people were reported wounded three days earlier in a bomb blast in north tehran's martyr bahonar street
iran and iraq have been at war since september 1980
brothers david and jon fone made their double wedding a family affair saturday when they married janette browne and her daughter, rachael
david fone, 23, married janette, 37, making him rachael's stepfather as well as her brother-in-law
jon fone, 18, married rachael, also 18. he now has janette as both a sister-in-law and a mother-in-law
david also becomes the stepfather to janette's five children by her first marriage, as well as grandfather and uncle to jon and rachel's 1-year-old daughter, nikita
david has two children by his first marriage
confusing?
not at all, says rachael
we're just one big happy family,'' she said.``at first it was a bit difficult. it was a bit embarrassing talking about the things you talk to mothers about, just in case she told david and it got back to jon. but after a few weeks it was great.''
the two couples started double-dating every week in torquay, southwest england, ``and we became more like sisters than mother and daughter,'' rachael said
janette, whose other children range in age from 4 to 13, said that dating david brought her closer to rachael
david said: ``you could see janette getting happier and happier every time we all went out together. one minute she was a mother of six and never went out anywhere. the next she's going out drinking and dancing with her teen-age daughter. it actually made her younger.'' spelling of institution. subs 9th graf, `matta, 43 ...,' with 1 graf to clarify that constitution is honduras'. subs 11th graf pvs, `political violence ...,' with 1 graf to drop word `phenomena,' and replace it with `two.' ^an ap extra</note>
drugs and political murders have perturbed the calm that had made this central american country an island of peace surrounded by guerrilla wars
life in this bustling capital of narrow streets and low pastel painted buildings remains tranquil compared to the daily tribulations of neighboring el salvador, nicaragua and guatemala. civil wars in those countries have killed more than 100,000 people in the past decade
because of honduras' relative stability and its close alliance with washington, u.s. officials were particularly concerned about the increased use in recent years of this country as a transshipment point for american-bound colombian cocaine
after several seizures of honduran-routed drugs in the previous two years, federal agents in florida last november confiscated four tons of cocaine hidden in a shipment of honduran wooden doors. worth more than $1 billion, it was the biggest bust in u.s. history
elliott abrams, assistant secretary of state for inter-american affairs, said in an interview broadcast here last week that ``without doubt'' some honduran military officers and government officials are involved in the drug trade
honduras returned to civilian rule in 1982 after a decade of military regimes. but the civilian administration of president jose azcona hoyo remains weak and dependent on the support of the armed forces
abrams told the radio station hrn: ``as in any army, there are individuals, people in the honduran army who are not honest and perhaps have been bought by matta and the drug traffickers. but that does not mean that the army as an institution is dishonest, because that's not true.''
he referred to juan ramon matta, a honduran who escaped from a colombian jail two years ago and returned here, where he lives in an opulent home with a bodyguard of 10 former honduran paratroopers. matta, allegedly a major figure of colombia's infamous medellin cartel, was jailed for a few months upon his arrival back home. local media said he bought his way out
matta, 43, is wanted in the united states in connection with the slaying in 1985 in mexico of u.s drug agent enrique camarena salazar. the honduran constitution prohibits extradition of native hondurans
abrams said the honduran military asked a year ago for more u.s. help in combating the proliferating traffickers. the u.s. drug enforcement administration, after an absence of seven years, has re-established an office here
political violence has increased along with the rise in drug trafficking, though there is no apparent connection between the two. amnesty international, the london-based rights organization, reported wednesday that death squads linked to the honduran military are waging a new campaign of torture and terror against government opponents
the independent human rights committee, known as codeh, blames three slayings last month on officially sanctioned or tolerated death squads
codeh vice president anibal puerto, in an interview with the associated press, said there were 277 ``extra-judicial executions'' last year. he said that because of lack of investigative means, the committee could not say how many it blames on death squads. but he said most of the victims presented signs of torture, and that many had been active in labor, rights, student or campesino (peasant) organizations
miguel angel pavon, head of the codeh branch in the northwestern city of san pedro sula, and professor moises landaverde were talking in a car in front of the latter's home on jan. 14 when a motorcycle carrying two people pulled alongside. the motorcycle passenger shot each man twice and the bike sped away
a few days earlier, gunmen killed former army sergeant jose isias vilorio, reportedly an ex-member of a death squad. vilorio had been scheduled to testify in costa rica before the inter-american court on human rights hearing a case alleging that death squads operated with official backing here in the early 1980s. a banner of a tiny leftist guerrilla faction was left by the body, and the government says leftists killed him
rights activists, citing the importance of vilorio's imminent testimony, contend he was killed by a death squad and that the flag was a crude attempt to divert blame
amnesty said other abuses, including arbitrary arrests and torture of prisoners are widespread in honduras
consulted by the ap, foreign ministry spokesman eugenio castro termed the amnesty report ``somewhat pulled out of thin air ... when there is no proof.'' he said the murders of last month were being investigated
but puerto said the investigation is getting nowhere
carlos montoya, president of the national congress, called during a press conference wednesday for the abolition of death squads
we trust that the armed forces will make known the names of those responsible for so many crimes,'' he said
authorities here reacted with indignation to the reports of officers' involvement in the drug trade. armed forces spokesman col. manual suarez benavides told the ap flatly, ``there are no military officers involved in narcotics traffic.''
the foreign ministry demanded that the u.s. embassy provide the names of honduran officers allegedly involved in drug dealing
on feb. 19, ambassador everett briggs wrote to foreign minister carlos lopez contreras saying the u.s. government has no list of honduran officers involved in drug trafficking. briggs said that if and when u.s. authorities obtain such information, it will be passed on to honduran oficials
when explorer bartholomew gosnold visited this small island off the massachusetts coast in 1602, he named it in honor of his daughter and the grapevines he found growing abundantly on its open land
today undeveloped land on martha's vineyard is increasingly scarce, and an overwhelming majority of the resort island's residents are demanding a halt to rapid growth they say is stripping the island of its character and straining its police, hospital and other services
at one time, it was natural graces that brought people to the island. now that is being supplemented by the fact that this is also attractive as a straight out-and-out investment,'' said walter renear, chairman of the tisbury town planning board
a poll commissioned by the weekly vineyard gazette newspaper found that 95 percent of adult residents in the island's six towns believe development is creating serious problems. seventy-five percent of permanent residents and 82 percent of seasonal residents called the problems very serious
the poll of 800 people by louis harris and associates inc. also found a widespread distrust of developers and a belief among 82 percent of the respondents that the island will become unlivable if growth is not curtailed
the year-round population on the island is now 12,690, more than double what it was 15 years ago. the summer population swells to over 90,000 with visitors in search of the island's breezes, beaches, fishing and sailing
most respondents favored a broad, one-year moratorium on residential and commercial development and the adoption of island-wide planning goals to restrict the number and location of new developments
but renear said speculation has helped force land values up and a moratorium would likely draw lawsuits from developers and property owners
it's the investment aspect of the land that is fueling this development,'' renear said
many owners buy land and get permission to build. the permits become part of the land value, and an investor need not build to make money
for years there have been arguments about island development, but vineyard officials say the poll is the first indication that there is near unanimity among residents about taking action to halt growth
i think it's a mandate,'' said james l. young, a member of the martha's vineyard commission, the island's regional planning agency. ``i think it's time to take a good hard look at our officeholders to see if they are indeed reflecting the views of their constituents.''
the number of building permits for new residential units on martha's vineyard jumped 302 percent from 1976, when 158 permits were issued, to 1986, when 636 new units were approved island-wide. another 517 units were approved in 1987, according to vineyard commission records
open land has become a commodity on the 100-square-mile island, a summer haven seven miles off the cape cod shore. land records show that scores of undeveloped lots have changed hands several times in recent years, each time at a higher price, without being developed
ironically, an agency created in may 1986 to help preserve some of the island's scenic and historic land is benefiting from the land deals
the martha's vineyard land bank receives proceeds of a 2 percent tax on all vineyard real estate transactions, and has collected nearly $7.4 million, its share of the $370 million in real estate deals on the island in the past 21 months
the land bank has used the money to buy outright or purchase development rights to 290 acres and is in the process of obtaining 183 more acres
efforts of the land bank and a handful of other island preservation groups won't be enough to stop rapid development, said brendan o'neill, executive director of the martha's vineyard conservation society
a one-year building moratorium, he said, ``will buy us time to forge an island-wide consensus about what we want to be as a community.''
but renear, 62, a lifelong vineyard resident, said a moratorium is more likely to land island officials in court
this is a solvable problem and with time we can get a solution,'' renear said. ``there's room for growth. i'm not saying that we have all the answers. but a moratorium is too simplistic. property owners will have you in court in two minutes.''
john magnuson, 32, who works for his father, a longtime builder on the island, said better planning is the answer to the island's growth problem
i don't think a moratorium is the answer,'' he said. ``i do think it has to slow down somewhat, but there are some areas in the back woods where growth is just fine.''
paul swallow threw up his hands and whooped when he crossed the finish line in his first ski race since he broke his neck eight years ago
a paraplegic with only limited use of his arms, swallow was back on the snow again with more than 100 other disabled veterans
sitting in a plastic ski sled made for disabled skiers and grinning widely in the bright sunshine at powderhorn ski area, swallow talked of ``paying for this in more ways than one'' but said he thinks ``everybody should get in one of these things.''
swallow, 32, from los angeles, tore some skin from his left elbow during his slalom run when his sled nearly overturned, but all he cared about was getting out of his wheelchair and going skiing
you get a lot of satisfaction out of this and it proves a lot to people,'' said swallow, a volunteer juvenile probation counselor. ``everybody can do something and there's no limit.''
encouraging disabled veterans to exchange their wheelchairs for ski sleds and pushing them beyond their limits is the idea behind the national winter sports clinic for veterans
only in its second year, the clinic drew 105 disabled veterans to powderhorn for a week of skiing, snowmobiling, wheelchair basketball and sightseeing
can you imagine if you were confined to a wheelchair the pleasure and thrill of being able to ski and going 40 mph?'' asked sandy trombetta, the veterans administration's chief recreational therapist in grand junction
trombetta said most of the participants ``never even dreamed of skiing before, and most have never pushed beyond their limitations before.''
the skiers ranged from near quadriplegics with only limited use of their hands to amputees and blind skier urban miyares of san diego
miyares skied with the help of sue haak of the denver va office, who is a ski instructor for the handicapped at the winter park area. she skiied next to miyares, calling out to him when to turn, slow down or speed up
amputees ski on a single ski with tiny skis fitted to the bottoms of their ski poles like outriggers
paraplegics with good upper body coordination and balance use a high-tech monoski, a plastic or metal shell perched on a single ski. they also use outriggers, and accomplished monoskiers blast through the same moguls and powder as expert able-bodied skiers
most who have lost the use of their legs and have suffered some injury higher toward the shoulders use the plastic sleds. they drag metal spikes in the snow to turn and the less experienced are tethered to a skier who follows to keep their speed under control
the plastic sleds officially are called ``sit-skis'' and cost between $1,400 and $2,200 each
the veterans came from 20 states, either paying their own way to grand junction or getting financial help from their local vfw or american legion groups. trombetta said it costs the va and several corporate sponsors $50,000 to stage the week-long clinic
a second-year participant, ray hill of detroit, says he can't get enough of skiing
from the moment i took my first run last year i wanted to come back,'' said hill, 45, who was left in a wheelchair by a hit-and-run driver
hill said only the will and the mind stand in the way of the disabled
you have to pick yourself up and do it again, and again, until you master it,'' he said. ``and you can always look around here and see somebody worse off than you are, doing the same thing
so if he's doing it, i can do it.''
the government on saturday approved the renewal of a defense cooperation pact with the united states that was signed by the two countries almost a year ago, the foreign ministry announced
the pact gives the united states access to a dozen military installations in turkey, including two electronic listening posts that monitor soviet military activities and nuclear tests
premier turgut ozal's cabinet, disappointed by the position of the u.s. congress on military aid to turkey, had been withholding approval of the agreement that will be in force until 1990
turkey contends it needs $1.2 billion in u.s. assistance a year to modernize its armed forces
last year, the reagan administration asked congress to give turkey $914 million in aid. the congress, citing budget constraints, cut the request to $570 million and reduced the amount to $490 million for the current fiscal year
the announcement said that in ratifying the agreement, the turkish government considered other aspects of the relationship with the united states besides defense cooperation. it did not elaborate
the announcement also noted that the united states, in the agreement, had pledged to make it easier for turkey to repay its foreign military sales credits and also pledged to improve trade relations between the two countries
it was not made public what kind of negotiations took place before the turkish government's decision to approve the agreement
the 1980 agreement expired in 1985, and it was extended until 1990 last march following intense negotiations
legally, the agreement goes into force after confirmation by the cabinet and publication in the official gazette
the announcement said the gazette will publish the government's decision on sunday
the united states lodged a protest with the government for failing to protect a u.s. navy supply ship during an anti-american demonstration on the island of crete, an embassy spokesman said saturday
four islanders and two american sailors from the supply ship saturn were injured during wednesday's dockside demostration at heraklion harbor. the ship, which sailed thursday, called at the port to pick up fresh fruit and vegetables for the 6th fleet in the mediterranean
the u.s. embassy has issued a protest over the lack of security afforded during the incident,'' said the embassy spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity
the spokesman said the protest was delivered to the greek foreign ministry friday by embassy charge d'affairs ed cohen
more than 1,000 demonstrators gathered at the port, sprayed ``americans go home'' in red paint on the ship's side, cut and set fire to a mooring cable, and hurled rocks, bottles and flares
demonstrators claimed that sailors aboard the saturn tossed the bottles, rocks and other objects back into the crowd. the protest was organized by a local peace group opposed to the american military presence on crete
the government is waiting ... for the heraklion port authority's report based on which a reply will be given,'' said government spokesman yiannis roubatis
he said that if the findings cast blame ``on the behavior of the american ship's crew during the demonstration, a protest will be made to the american side.''
there is an american air force base near heraklion as well as air and naval facilities for american warships at souda bay in western crete
an aeroflot airliner carrying 51 people crashed on a siberian runway and burst into flames as it finished the final leg of a cross-country trip, killing and injuring passengers, tass said
the soviet news agency quoted a local aviation official as saying the tu-134 ``fell within the airfield boundaries, broke up and caught fire'' at the city of surgut, an oil and petrochemical center on the ob river about 1,400 miles east of moscow
unfortunately, there were victims,'' tass said. an earlier report said: ``there is loss of life.''
tass said the tu-134 was carrying 45 passengers and six crew members, but did not specify how many people were killed and injured in the crash, which occurred shortly after 4 a.m. moscow time
it was the third reported fatal crash of a commercial jetliner in the soviet union this year
fire engines and rescue vehicles were at the crash site within two minutes and were giving first aid to the injured, tass quoted the local deputy chief of civil aviation, yuri evreinov, as saying
tass said 15 emergency vehicles were sent to the surgut airport to evacuate victims, who were taken to two hospitals
eight doctors also were brought in from the regional center of tyumen, tass said
tass said the 1,600-mile flight originated in the byelorussian capital of minsk, with stops in the volga basin industrial city of kuibyshev and tyumen, a siberian oil city, before a final scheduled landing in surgut, a city of more than 150,000 people located in western siberia
the tu-134 is a twin-turbofan plane designed for short- and medium-range flights, and can carry from 80 to 96 passengers, according to jane's all the world's aircraft
the causes of the crash are being investigated by a special government commission, tass said
the weather this morning was good, communications with the plane solid,'' evreinov was quoted as saying. ``but then the unforeseen happened.''
tass said the soviet government had conveyed its condolences to people injured in the crash and to the families of the dead
in the past, the soviet union rarely reported its plane crashes, but deputy civil aviation minister ivan vasin told the associated press last fall that aeroflot would begin publishing reports on its accidents this year
the policy change was clearly linked to soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's campaign for ``glasnost,'' or openness, on some social issues
on jan. 18, a tu-154 passenger jet crashed on landing at the caspian sea port of krasnovodsk, and soviet media said 11 people were killed and 12 hurt
those media reports, which were issued on the day of the crash, marked the first time the state-run soviet press and broadcast media reported on a domestic air accident the same day it occurred
on jan. 25, an aeroflot yakovlev-40 tri-turbofan passenger plane crashed near the airport in the siberian city of nizhnevartovsk. tass at the time said the crash caused ``loss of life,'' but did not say how many people had died
vladimir y. potemkin, deputy chief of flight services at the ministry of civil aviation, told a news conference earlier this month that a total of 47 people were killed last year in accidents involving aeroflot planes
the state department formally protested to the nicaraguan government saturday after two u.s. diplomats were threatened and one was roughed up by a crowd of policemen participating in a parade in managua, the department said
nicaraguan ambassador carlos tunnermann was summoned to the state department to receive ``a stiff formal protest'' about the incident, which occurred on friday, according to a department statement
the statement said two american diplomats were watching a rally commemorating the 10th anniversary of the nicaraguan revolution, when they were noticed by members of the ministry of the interior's uniformed police force
after a high-ranking ministry official identified the two diplomats as americans, five uniformed policemen grabbed one of the u.s. diplomats, pinned his arms and hoisted him in the air, the department said
other officers intervened to stop the five, but a crowd of more than 100 other ministry officers surrounded the americans and screamed at them for five minutes, according to the department. it said the diplomats then departed. seoul-dated last item</note>
park yong-shik can shed his toupee now that chun doo-hwan is no longer president
the popular television actor says he had to wear a hairpiece during chun's seven-year term because he bears a striking resemblance to the balding former president, who was succeeded thursday by roh tae-woo
park, 44, said he was banned from appearing on state-run television in 1981 without explanation. park said he learned later it was because he resembled the chun
authorities in 1982 accepted his proposal to wear a toupee and grow a beard to change his appearance, he said. however, he lost important roles in soap operas and other programs and only received minor parts in historical dramas
i hope such a comic thing will never happen again,'' park said friday
china's giant pandas, in danger of extinction since 1983 when their dietary staple of bamboo began to wither, are over the worst of the crisis, china's top forestry official was quoted saturday as saying
forestry minister gao dezhan said new bamboo has started to grow in the pandas' three native provinces of sichuan, shaanxi and gansu, the official people's daily reported
but he said the threat to the pandas is not over because the animals don't generally like young bamboo
gao called on the leaders of the three provinces to continue to guard the pandas' safety. the officials met friday in beijing to discuss the situation
at the meeting, gao called for strict punishment, including the death penalty, for hunters who capture or kill giant pandas
china's panda population, now just under 1,000, has been declining for the past five years in part because a rare flowering cycle of the arrow bamboo caused more than 275,000 tons of the plant to wither and die
eleven men were sentenced earlier this week to prison terms ranging from three years to life for killing two giant pandas in sichuan province
the governing liberal democratic party will not accept a united states request that japan lift restrictions on imported beef and oranges within two years, a party official was quoted as saying saturday
michio watanabe, chairman of the party's policy affairs research council, told a news conference that japan instead would offer the united states an increase in import quotas, kyodo news service reported
there are people in the united states saying many things, but we don't accept them,'' it quoted him as saying in reference to u.s. demands that imports of oranges and beef be liberalized
party officials were not immediately available saturday to confirm the report
on thursday, a senior economic planning agency official predicted that japanese import restrictions on beef would be lifted within two years, with a lifting of restrictions on citrus fruit coming even sooner
japan has been under pressure from the united states and australia to open its beef and citrus markets, with an agreement governing imports of the two products due to expire in march
but the ministry of agriculture, forestry and fisheries has opposed liberalization, arguing that it is unfair to single out japan and pointing to restrictions that the united states maintains on beef imports
japanese officials have said the quotas are neccessary to protect japanese farmers
the current agreement between japan and the united states called for japan to increase its beef import quotas from 141,000 tons a year in 1984 to 177,000 tons by 1988, and its orange quotas by 1,100 tons each year until 1988. the level was 82,000 tons in 1984, when the agreement was signed
whether belching with smoke or strangely silent, the mills of this once-mighty steel valley have been a magnet for visiting notables over the decades
britain's prince edward, later king edward vii, toured the area's mills and factories during his visit to the united states in 1860
prince don gelasio caetani, ambassador from italy to the united states, visited the mills of nearby homestead in 1923. sweden's prince bertil followed in 1938
the bold energy and ceaseless inventive imagination displayed by your industry seems to me to be the surest token of success for the future,'' prince bertil said
even soviet leader nikita khrushchev, traveling through the united states prior to a 1959 summit meeting with president eisenhower, toured a factory with his wife
krushchev startled everyone when he gave his watch to a steelworker who had offered him a cigar
constantine, crown prince of greece, saw a mill during a brief visit to pittsburgh in 1959. king bhumibol adulyadej of thailand and his queen toured a plant the following year
the latest member of royalty to venture into the monongahela river valley just south of pittsburgh will be britain's prince charles. he doesn't plan to tour any steel mills, but will travel past them on his way to a meeting with urban experts in homestead on friday
although the steel industry has declined precipitously, homestead acting mayor joseph little, like most everybody else around this town of 5,000, is proud of the crowd his valley has drawn
homestead was a great town. it still is a great town,'' little said. ``we've just got to get something going for us. there won't be any harm done as far as prince charles coming in.''
