the nude performer was arrested early saturday at the end of her first night club appearance in brussels after leaving the stage, a police spokesman said. the spokesman, not identified in line with police policy, said cicciolina had overstepped the bounds of decency, according to belgian standards, and that she had been warned in advance
she was taken to brussels police headquarters and was released at 6 p.m
her spokesman said she had decided to interrupt her tour, which included one more appearance in brussels saturday night and shows in other cities, and to return to italy
she also was making the tour to promote her candidacy for the european parliament in the 1989 election and to speak out in favor of sexual freedom, said her spokesman, who talked with reporters on the condition he not be identified
she was elected to the italian parliament last year as a representative for the radical party. marco pannella, former chairman of the party, said in a statement released here that the police acted against her because she is a member of the italian parliament
he said her arrest was ``obscene, not her show which i did not see and in which i am not interested.'' he added he would protest laws and regulations ``which hurt common sense and human rights.''
the police spokesman declined to say if cicciolina had been asked to leave the country or if charges might be filed
a spokesman for the german airline lufthansa said ms. staller left brussels on a flight to frankfurt at 6:35 p.m
reports from armenia's capital indicated the city was calm saturday, but a u.s.-based group claimed some armenians remained camped in a tent city in the region where several days of mass protests had been held
a hotel manager in yerevan, reached by telephone from moscow, said, ``everything is quiet'' in the capital city where at least five days of street protests brought an appeal by soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev for restraint
a telephone operator in yerevan also said the demonstrations had ended. efforts to contact armenian nationalist leaders were unsuccessful. both the operator and the hotel manager spoke on condition they not be identified
there was no direct word on the situation in nagorno-karabakh, the autonomous region where members of the ethnic armenian majority began the demonstrations to protest the soviet communist party's rejection of a proposal to give the region back to armenia. it has been designated part of the neighboring republic of azerbaidzhan since 1923
most telephone calls to yerevan have been cut off since the demonstrations began, and foreign reporters have been prevented from traveling to the small republic on the turkish border
gorbachev's appeal, read on armenian and azerbaidzhanian radio and television friday by a central committee official, was accompanied by a pledge from local party officials to ask the moscow-based communist party central committee to reconsider the territorial issue
reports from armenia said that after the appeal, the demonstrators in yerevan, said by some to have numbered up to 1 million, began to disperse
a washington-based group calling itself the armenian national committee of america quoted telephone reports from the region as saying nagorno-karabakh's main city, stepanakert, had been turned into a tent city by armenian villagers from the countryside
the group claimed azerbaidzhanis had killed 70 armenians in the region and that soviet troops were stationed around stepanakert to prevent further ethnic violence. there have been other reports of deaths in the region, but they have not been confirmed
relations between azerbaidzhan, a predominantly moslem republic, and mainly christian armenia have been tense for some time. last week, there were disturbances in the contested autonomous region, where the population is three-quarters armenian, and they spread to yerevan
the protests brought concessions from regional communist party leaders. they named a 56-year-old armenian, genrikh pogosyan, to head the party in nagorno-karabakh, replacing boris kevorkov who also is an ethnic armenian but apparently less popular than pogosyan
