vincenzo quinto was booked on a charge of second-degree murder, said metro-dade police spokesman rey valdes. quinto was admitted to a jail ward at jackson memorial hospital because of his age, valdes added
ana quinto, 76, died friday of ``blunt trauma to the head,'' valdes said
detective pat diaz said the couple met four months ago and married one week ago saturday. quinto had moved to miami a few years ago after retiring from his job as a contractor in new york
police on duty saturday did not know if it was quinto or his wife who wanted to take a cruise. york, picking up 5th graf pvs, `in the...'. subs 10th graf, `the coalition...', to correct amount of reward offered in new jersey case to $1,000 sted $10,000. note language in 3rd graf.</note>
a black woman was attacked by two white men who smeared her with excrement, painted markings on her face and clipped her hair, police said saturday
the injured woman was hospitalized for 12 days after the incident earlier this month, police said. they said they were unsure whether it was a ``copycat'' attack patterned after the highly publicized case of a black girl in wappingers falls, n.y
that girl, tawana brawley, 16, was found last november wrapped in a plastic garbage bag and covered with excrement. the word ``nigger'' and ``kkk'' were scrawled on her body and she said she had been sexually assaulted by six white men. some of her hair also had been chopped off
about 600 demonstrators marched peacefully through poughkeepsie, n.y., saturday to protest the treatment of miss brawley and the stalled investigation of the assault
we come to you with hate in our eyes,'' said lawyer alton maddox jr., addressing gov. mario cuomo rhetorically. ``we come to you with hate in our hearts. you are not talking to foot-shufflers.''
the protest leaders have been calling on cuomo to remove state attorney general robert abrams from the case. cuomo had named abrams as a special prosecutor to investigate the case after two local prosecutors claimed conflicts of interest
the leaders want a new, permanent prosecutor named for statewide race-related crimes. they have said the victim and her family won't cooperate with the investigation until then
the case has grown into a cause celebre among some civil rights activists, and actor bill cosby posted a reward for information in the investigation
in the newton case, the victim was attacked feb. 8 in a stairwell outside her downtown apartment. she was not sexually assaulted, police said
police detective john tomasula said he believes the attack was racially motivated because of statements the men made to the victim. tomasula declined to disclose what they said. the assailants were believed to be in their 20s
police believe the assault was not premeditated against the woman, hildegard smith
i'm sure if anyone went down (the stairwell), something was going to happen,'' tomasula said. ``she was in the wrong place at the wrong time and they just took advantage of her.''
ms. smith, 50, was treated for trauma for 12 days at newton memorial hospital, said the rev. william sadler, one of the leaders of a community coalition
the coalition, made up of mostly white clergy and civic leaders, is offering a $1,000 reward for information leading to the arrest of the assailants
ms. smith's family last week gave permission for the coalition to disclose her name and condition to help catch her attackers, sadler said
we wanted the people to know what had happened,'' he said. ``we wanted to support the woman and wanted to bring the whole community together to say we don't want this kind of thing to happen.''
rep. richard gephardt's democratic presidential rivals wrote an obituary for his trade policies saturday, but michael dukakis said ``burial has been postponed until after super tuesday in deference to the next of kin.''
gephardt, whose legislation would penalize foreign countries that have trade surpluses with the united states, told his opponents during a campaign debate that his measure seeks to discourage other countries from being protectionist
the house included gephardt's provision in the sweeping trade bill, but no such language appears in the senate's version of the legislation
house-senate negotiators say they are unlikely to take action on the proposal until after the super tuesday primaries march 8. most participants say they expect gephardt's amendment to be changed
the gephardt amendment is dead,'' dukakis told the missouri congressman during one exchange. ``you know that.''
i don't know that, mike,'' gephardt responded. ``where did you hear that?''
it's burial has been postponed until after super tuesday in deference to the next of kin, but it's dead,'' the massachusetts governor said to laughter from the audience
sen. albert gore jr., d-tenn., said it would be ``false and misleading'' to imply that unfair trading practices by other countries account for more than 10 to 15 percent of the u.s. trade deficit
the real answer is not just bashing other countries,'' said sen. paul simon, d-ill. ``the real answer is having an effective president who understands the issue and then moves.''
moments later, former sen. gary hart of colorado said, ``the worst idea put forward in this campaign is protectionism.''
he said gephardt's amendment ``will lead us toward a trade war, at least increase the likelihood of that trade war, which in turn could trigger market crashes and depressions.''
gary, your thinking is stuck in the past,'' gephardt said
yours is,'' said hart, as the two men, seated side by side, pointed fingers at each other
why do we continually apologize for unfair trade practices by other countries ... ,'' gephardt asked. ``all i'm saying is let's stand up for the fairness for our people.'' shultz arriving in israel, comments, plans for sunday. pickup 5th pvs: `jordan and syria ...</note>
leaders of jordan and syria told secretary of state george p. shultz saturday that his proposals for a middle east settlement were unacceptable
we did not reach any agreement,'' shultz said after a three-hour meeting with syrian president hafez assad, which followed a similarly unsuccessful meeting in jordan
we expressed our opinion in an open and frank way. no agreement was reached,'' said syrian foreign minister farouk al-sharaa who also met with shultz
after arriving back in jerusalem late saturday, shultz said he had not given up hope on his plan
the idea in negotiations of this kind is to get people to be realistic,'' shultz said. ``we are not there yet.''
he resumes his attempts to gain acceptance of accelerated negotiations on palestinian self-rule on sunday in talks with israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir and foreign minister shimon peres. shultz then flies to cairo to try to enlist the support of president hosni mubarak of egypt
shultz's failure to reach an agreement saturday centered around the involvement of the soviet union and the palestine liberation organization in negotiations for peace
jordan and syria, which has close relations with moscow, want the plo and the soviets to participate in an international conference on peace in the middle east. the united states and israel want to exclude the plo and to limit soviet influence
u.s. policy forbids american diplomats to meet ranking plo officials because the u.s. adminstration regards the plo as a terrorist organization
sharaa said the syrians had listened carefully to shultz's ideas
a solution to the problem of the middle east cannot be reached without the elimination of the israeli occupation of all occupied arab territories and safeguarding of palestinian national rights,'' sharaa said
syria's state-run television said assad and the u.s. secretary discussed ``the american ideas that shultz carried with him'' concerning the arab-israeli conflict
the u.s. plan calls for immediate talks on palestinian self-rule and negotiations by december on the final status of the west bank and gaza strip, which israel seized from egypt and jordan in the 1967 middle east war
the syrian side found that these ideas do not lead to a comprehensive peace formula,'' the television said
after the meeting, shultz flew back to israel from damascus
shultz was the first u.s. secretary of state to go to damascus since 1983
the reagan administration, accusing syria of supporting terrorism, attempted to isolate the country diplomatically in october 1986
but syria's influence in the arab world and its military strength makes it impossible to ignore when it comes to peace in the middle east
shultz took his peace plan to syria after running into stiff resistance from jordan saturday morning
jordanian foreign minister taher masri, after meeting shultz, also insisted on soviet and plo participation in the negotiations shultz is trying to set up
when shultz arrived earlier saturday, the official damascus radio broadcast a commentary noting signs of a positive shift in the united states' mideast policy
referring to reagan's statements at a news conference wednesday night, the state radio said reagan was looking for a comprehensive settlement because of palestinian unrest in israeli-held territories, which has left scores of arabs dead since december
but the shift was obviously not enough for the syrians
shultz last saw assad in 1983. he accused the syrian leader of undercutting a u.s.-backed pact between lebanon and israel that year
three years later, the u.s. state department accused syria of involvement in at least 40 incidents of terrorism and imposed diplomatic and economic sanctions
but shultz, on his way to israel wednesday night, said syrian involvement in terrorism ``seems to have declined'' and he intended to find out how helpful syria might be in a middle east settlement
before shultz's arrival, syrian state radio had been scornful of the u.s. mission, calling it ``nothing but a political airlift to rescue israel'' under pressure of palestinian uprisings
shultz is trying set up negotiations by the end of the year on a final arab-israel settlement that would resolve the palestinian problem
but israeli prime minister shamir urged shultz on friday to move slowly and to aim for a test period of limited palestinian self-rule
the plo, in a statement released in jordan hours after shultz's departure, said it is willing to meet u.s. officials ``on any level,'' and said american rejection of a meeting shows the united states is not serious about arab-israeli peace. army saying four soldiers will be tried in military court. pickup 7th pvs: the clashes in ...</note>
israeli soldiers killed three palestinians during clashes in the occupied territories saturday, hospital officials said. police detained two american teachers carrying posters listing the names of slain arabs
arabs burned tires and threw rocks in jerusalem and other israeli cities to protest the peace mission of u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz, while a group of israelis held a rally in support of the initiative
on the occupied west bank of the jordan river, protesters clashed with soldiers in hebron, the nearby village of halhoul and an arrub refugee camp. the army said soldiers killed two palestinians and wounded 15
hospital officials said three people were killed, including 17-year-old maged al atrash of halhoul who died of gunshot wounds to the abdomen late saturday at jerusalem's mukassad hospital. the doctors said 27 people were wounded
soldiers fatally shot nihad abdul ghafour, 20, of arrub and baker abdullah al bao, 17, of halhoul, according to the hospital officials. the deaths brought to 71 the number of palestinians killed by israelis since the recent wave of unrest began dec. 8
the army reported saturday that a 15-month-old jewish child suffered a broken skull when assailants hurled a stone at his family's car in jerusalem in an attack friday
israel radio quoted the army's west bank commander, maj. gen. amram mitzna, as saying saturday that four soldiers would be tried in a military court on charges they beat two arabs who were lying on the ground and had their hands tied behind their backs
the soldiers were detained friday and their commanding officer, a captain, was suspended after cbs television filmed the beatings thursday in the west bank city of nablus and showed the footage to mitzna. the general also ordered the release of the two arabs
the film was shown on television stations in several european countries, and foreign ministry officials said saturday that israeli embassies in europe received dozens of telegrams protesting the beatings
the clashes in halhoul and arrub began when masked youths blocked the main jerusalem-hebron highway, the army said. soldiers fired tear gas, rubber bullets and gunshots to drive the stone-throwers away from the highway
for several hours, soldiers surrounded hebron's alia hospital, firing tear gas at stone-throwing demonstrators nearby, said a nurse, speaking on condition of anonymity
the army imposed curfews on the areas around hebron, but allowed jewish settlers to move freely, military officials said. the army also extended curfews on four gaza strip refugee camps, restricting 120,000 people, or nearly 10 percent of the 1.5 million arabs in the occupied territories, to their homes
in the west bank city of ramallah, police detained american teachers alison glick, 25, of cincinnati, and john benvenuto, in his 40s, of albany, n.y., because they allegedly possessed inciting material, said joost hiltermann, a friend of the two and researcher for the ramallah-based civil rights group law in the service of man
ramallah police refused to discuss the case
hiltermann said ms. glick and benvenuto were detained while walking in ramallah and carrying posters with names of palestinians killed by israelis in the past 11 weeks
benvenuto and ms. glick, teachers at a quaker school in ramallah, were not allowed to see a lawyer, said hiltermann
david good, a spokesman for the u.s. consulate in east jerusalem, said he was informed of the detentions but could not elaborate
in jerusalem, about 3,000 israelis attended a rally organized by the ``peace now'' movement near the home of prime minister yitzhak shamir. demonstrators carried banners reading `say yes to the peace initiative.''
speakers urged the government to trade land for peace, a formula advocated by shultz, but opposed by shamir
also in jerusalem, palestinian protesters blocked roads near the shufat refugee camp, throwing stones and burning tires. police dispersed the crowd with rubber bullets and arrested six protesters
about 3,000 police officers, double the usual number, were deployed in jerusalem after palestinian organizers last week called for stepped-up protests during the five-day shultz visit
shultz, on a mission to seek agreement on guidelines for starting arab-israeli talks, met with syrian and jordanian leaders in damascus and amman saturday and returned to jerusalem later in the day
in northern israel, meanwhile, hundreds of left-wing israeli arabs took to the streets to protest the shultz visit and the israeli crackdown on the protests. there were no reports of violence, and police did not interfere
four hundred protesters demonstrated in umm el fahm, a town of 30,000, the site of frequent anti-israeli violence. in the arab town of shefaram, also in northern israel, about 300 israeli arabs demonstrated
since the protests began in the occupied territories, many of israel's 700,000 arab citizens have expressed support for their brethren in the west bank and gaza strip
irish banker john guinness, whose wife was kidnapped two years ago and held captive for eight days, was fatally injured saturday in a 500-foot fall on snowdon mountain in north wales, police reported
they said guinness, a cousin of members of the guinness brewing family, was accompanied on the climb by his 49-year-old wife, jennifer, their son ian and three friends. guinness, 52, plunged from the snow-covered path as the party descended from the summit of the 3,560-foot mountain, according to police
guinness suffered multiple injuries and was airlifted off the mountain by a royal air force helicopter but was dead on arrival at a hospital in bangor, 10 miles away
a police spokesman said, ``they were ill-equipped for such a walk bearing in mind the conditions
the weather was not particularly bad but the conditions underfoot were very hazardous where the accident occurred.''
the couple had three children
jennifer guinness was kidnapped from the family home near dublin april 8, 1986, and held captive for a ransom of two million irish pounds _ then $2.6 million
eight days later, police besieged the hideout where she was held and freed her without payment of the ransom
her three abductors surrendered and three other people were arrested later
mrs. guinness was praised by police for keeping calm and playing a key role in the negotiations during the siege
guinness was chairman of the dublin merchant bank guinness and mahon
on the day of his wife's abduction, he returned home from work to find her and their 23-year-old daughter, gillian, tied up. the abductors pistol-whipped him and tied him. two and a half hours after they fled he managed to free himself and telephoned police
the guinnesses were married in 1959. their third child, tania, is in her 20s
guinness was regarded as one of ireland's finest long-distance sailors and once sailed the atlantic with his wife
he was sixth cousin of the titular head of the centuries-old family, the third earl of iveagh. the earl is chairman of the world famous brewery that bears the family name
hard-line leftists won control of britain's largest union saturday at a time when the union-financed labor party is seeking to moderate its stance after three successive electoral defeats
the transport and general workers union, with 1.4 million members nationwide, elected 23 hard-left candidates to its 39-member national executive council. the moderate faction supporting labor party leader neil kinnock previously had a 21-18 majority
the transport workers union has a 1,250,000 block vote for the equivalent of 20 percent of the total voting power at the labor party conference and could create obstacles for reforms kinnock is seeking
welsh-born kinnock, 45, who took over the leadership in 1983, waged a polished campaign in the june 1987 general election but still lost resoundingly to prime minister margaret thatcher's conservatives
at the labor party conference in september, kinnock told the delegates the 87-year-old party must ``face the realities of changing society. ... what do you say to a docker who earns 400 pounds ($700) a week, owns his house, a new car, microwave and video? you do not say `let me take you out of your misery brother.'''
the party then voted overwhelmingly for a policy review
ron todd, union general secretary, said saturday, ``the policy of our union will be maintained. our support for the (labor) party and its leader will be maintained.''
we are involved in the labor party on an exercise on policy review,'' he added. ``our union will take its decision on the review policy but it has always given consistent support to the party. it's not a blank check and mr. kinnock knows that.''
dennis skinner, left-wing labor member of parliament and a member of the party's ruling national executive, said: ``this result, together with the ford strike and the (national health service) campaign, indicates a new-found belief in strong trade unionism, and every socialist should welcome these results
the left has had a few lean years. now, the omens look rather better.'' auto workers struck all the british plants of ford motor co. feb. 8-11th in britain's first major industrial strike in three years
the workers had rejected their leaders' recommendation that they accept offered pay increases and a three-year contract. instead they won an increased pay settlement and a two-year pact. labor leaders called it the first significant union victory in seven years
nurses staged a one-day strike feb. 3 to protest their hours and wages and express concern for the condition of the publicly financed national health service. they said it must have more resources. warfare,'' similar threat a week ago against pan am apparently not carried out; brief work stoppage at detroit, background on talks at pan am, other detail, deleting some pvs material to tighten. no pickup.</note>
northwest airlines planes continued flying saturday and a union spokesman said strike preparations by 6,700 flight attendants were ``put on hold'' even though all-night contract talks hit a snag
consensus was reached on all issues except wages during a 22-hour bargaining session, said william wren, northwest's vice president for public relations. but union officials said there were other issues still unsettled
wren said he did not know when talks might resume
the union's rank-and-file negotiating committee met late saturday afternoon to receive direction from about 20 teamsters unit representatives from around the country, said william genoese, international director of the teamsters airline division
genoese said a strike was still possible, though he said talks with northwest might be resumed
genoese also threatened what he termed ``guerrilla warfare'' _ which he defined as a decline in attentiveness by flight attendants _ should there be no settlement or support for a strike
when you beat up on the workers who service the passengers, they beat up on the passengers,'' he said. ``you can't beat up on people in a service business.'' he had made the same threat a week ago against another airline, pan am, after those talks broke off, but no significant disruption in service has been reported, pan am said
a request by the federal mediator involved in the northwest talks to delay a strike helped avert a walkout saturday morning, he said
the government wants to take another crack at this,'' he said. ``it was 8 in the morning and everybody had been working all night. maybe some of the numbers fell through the cracks.''
the airline proposes to stretch from five to nine years the time in which an employee advances from a ``b'' or lower pay scale to the ``a'' schedule, a change the union is resisting, union officials said
in another area of disagreement, the union wants a three-year contract rather than the 4{-year pact offered by the airline. also, the sides are divided over the issue of retroactive pay, negotiators said
earlier, in the morning, genoese said workers were being told to walk out
teamsters local 2747 spokesman jeff musto said, however, that no strike had been called, and spot checks by the associated press at airports around the nation served by the nation's fifth largest airline found no pickets or other strike activity. airline operations were reported normal from honolulu to boston
on any given day you're subject to some delayed flights, but we're operating as scheduled normally,'' wren said saturday afternoon
there was a 20-minute work stoppage early saturday at detroit's metropolitan airport, union spokesman richard leebove said, adding that about 200 northwest machinists joined 70 flight attendants saturday afternoon in a rally at the airport
many of the 75 flight attendants who assembled at strike headquarters in eagan for picketing duty left by noon
representatives for the airlines and the union had continued negotiations after a midnight est deadline friday, but the negotiations recessed saturday morning
we did everything we possibly could to avoid a strike,'' genoese said during the morning. ``apparently the company feels it wants to take a strike on. if we want to close down the airline, we can close it down.''
a spokesman for northwest said the airline was prepared to carry out its strike-management program, but hoped that talks would resume
about 2,000 managers trained as flight attendants were posted throughout the northwest system with 200 newly hired replacement flight attendants also ready to move, said terry erskine, the airline's vice president for law and labor relations
there was no immediate word on whether flight attendant picket lines would be honored by pilots or machinists
tyler said the machinists are under a contract that forbids them to strike in sympathy with another union; the pilots' union said no decision had been made on its role
since northwest acquired republic airlines in 1986, former republic flight attendants have been working under their old contract, and many former republic employees are paid less than their northwest counterparts
northwest is trying to bring the workers under one contract and offered to bring former republic employees up to the salary levels of northwest employees. but the union claimed the airline is compensating by reducing vacation pay and retirement benefits
meanwhile, pan am corp. is continuing negotiations with the teamsters, which represent 4,500 pan am reservations agents, customer service employees and other ground workers. the union had threatened to strike because management is seeking $35 million in concessions
formal talks broke off last weekend and a strike deadline passed, but the employees kept working and informal talks have continued by telephone, pan am spokesman james a. arey said saturday
there was no evidence the teamsters carried out a threat of ``guerrilla warfare'' at pan am, he said
about 5,000 members of a right-wing paramilitary group rallied saturday to demand a whites-only state in south africa and urge the government to strengthen apartheid legislation
members of the afrikaner resistance movement held a four-hour ceremony in pretoria, saying the government was attempting to ``sell out'' its whites. the group also burned the flag of the african national congress, an outlawed black guerrilla group that supports majority black rule
the protesters, many wearing uniforms and carrying pistols, said prayers, sang and waved flags
they commemorated an 1881 victory by the afrikaners over the british in the town of majuba, which leader eugene terreblanche said was symbolic of the afrikaners' present-day struggle to establish a homeland
the day is coming when this government will capitulate (to blacks),'' terreblanche said. ``the awb must prepare ... because that is when we will take over the country.''
if you scrap the apartheid laws, you can expect south africa to follow the same route as the other (african) colonies, which have decayed and rotted,'' he said. ``without apartheid laws we cannot have order. and without order this country will disintegrate.''
apartheid, by law and custom, establishes a racially segregated society in which south africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
the demonstration followed wednesday's government crackdown which banned 18 of the country's leading black opposition groups from engaging in politics
terreblance did not comment on the crackdown
after the meeting, group members traveled to the union buildings, the government's executive headquarters, to present a petition calling for a whites-only state in south africa
riot police blocked the entrance to the building, but accepted the petition from terreblanche. there were no reports of violence or arrests
the right-wing group is made up almost exclusively of afrikaners, the dutch-descended settlers of south africa. the group rejects all concessions from south africa's 5 million whites to the nation's 26 million black majority
in other developments saturday, security forces began erecting a five-foot barbed-wire fence around most of the ktc squatter camp outside cape town
the ktc camp has been the site of ongoing faction fighting among rival black groups in recent weeks. police said two people were killed and 20 shacks were flattened in fighting last week
witnesses said the fence, which stretched for more than a mile, had three openings for residents to enter and exit. several thousand people live in the ktc camp
in june 1986, 70,000 people lost their homes and scores of people were killed in ktc and three other sections of the crossroads squatter complex during an onslaught by black vigilantes
the pilot who abandoned a twin-engine cessna along a closed highway in september 1985 left behind nearly a ton of cocaine and the clue eventually led to the indictment of panamanian gen. manuel antonio noriega, a newspaper reported saturday
the cessna's pilot, anthony azpruia, told prosecutors about the noriega link after his arrest, the miami herald reported. his cooperation and implication of miami-based aircraft parts business diasca sparked an investigation
the investigation of alleged panamanian drug trafficking was completed by miami-based federal officials whose information was ignored by drug enforcement administration officials in the u.s. embassy in panama city and in washington, according to a senate foreign relations subcommittee counsel and the chief assistant u.s. attorney in miami
there's absolutely no question that, through all the administrations since 1969, we had more than adequate information that this guy (noriega) was a dope dealer and chose to ignore it,'' said richard gregorie, chief assistant u.s. attorney in miami
even when we wanted to indict him, there were two factions within the dea,'' he said. ``people were satisfied with what they were getting out of panama, that he was doing enough. the other faction wanted to work the case. we really didn't send a lot up to washington. we stayed clear of it.''
diasca had already been penetrated by dea agent dan moritz when pilot azpruia made his emergency landing on a closed section of interstate 75 in south florida on sept. 25, 1985
running out of fuel and pursued by a dea helicopter, azpruia landed and abandoned the $1 million plane and its cargo, about 900 kilograms or roughly 1,980 pounds of cocaine
moritz said diasca president alfredo caballero provided aircraft for ``cocaine-smuggling ventures'' by 38-year-old pilot floyd carlton, who is now the government's key witness against noriega
moritz said the diasca office was used for ``planning smuggling ventures, for assembling and distributing large cash proceeds of narcotics transactions and for placing telephone calls.''
caballero denies any involvement in drug trafficking
four months after the cessna's highway landing, caballero, his son, azpruia, carlton and three others were indicted. all were jailed but carlton, who was in panama
azpruia told prosecutors that there was a noriega connection, but investigators needed carlton to make a case
carlton was pursued not only by authorities in florida but by drug lords in colombia who believed he had stolen a cocaine shipment of more than 1,100 pounds from them, the herald reported
carlton was so worried that he went to the u.s. embassy in panama city and told dea agents there about noriega's alleged role in the drug smuggling
when i mentioned the name of general noriega, they immediately became upset, and i noticed that. of course, i became nervous at that point,'' carlton has said
the embassy confession was a bungled opportunity, said jack blum, counsel to a senate foreign relations subcommittee
the minute the boys hear what he's got, they turn cold, like he's a lunatic,'' blum said. ``when he tells them about noriega, there's an understanding that this isn't a healthy place to talk about it.''
he was seeking help. but he wasn't seeking help as far as being willing to come to the united states and testify,'' gregorie said
carlton eventually went to colombia, confronted the drug lords and, with a kind word from the boss of colombia's medellin cartel, the pressure was reduced, the newspaper said
miami investigators used caballero to set up a trap in costa rica to capture carlton. since then, carlton has given detailed depositions about drug flights he says he flew to the united states under arrangement with noriega and has testified before the senate. all letters quoted were published in sunday editions of the newspaper, which becomes available saturday, sted published saturday and sunday. picks up 8th graf, `k_he said...'.</note>
serial killer john wayne gacy believes he will be paroled, cried while watching the olympics and says ``it doesn't always pay to be good to people,'' according to letters published sunday
the letters were written by gacy and sent to sue terry, 43, of centralia. she says gacy has proposed and she would marry him, the chicago sun-times said in sunday's early editions
gacy, 45, now on death row, was convicted of killing 33 young men and boys, 29 of whom were found buried under or near his home outside chicago
i don't believe hardly any of it,'' ms. terry told the sun-times. ``i really don't. ... he doesn't think he's guilty. to me he don't seem like he could hurt anyone
we're real close,'' she said. ``i like john, and he trusts me. i guess i love him. yes.''
gacy wrote 41 letters to ms. terry, who is divorced, from oct. 5, 1986, to feb. 16, 1988. she shared some of them with the newspaper and the sun-times said it would publish the letters for a week
the portions published in sunday's editions, which became available saturday, ranged from gacy's thoughts on freedom to his disdain for queen elizabeth ii:
_he said he was moved by the performance of olympic speed skater dan jansen, whose sister died while he was competing in calgary
she wanted him to go on and skate for her. and in the first turn he lost his balance and fell. the tears just rolled down my face. and i don't even know him,'' gacy wrote
_ms. terry asked gacy about an eventual release from prison
you asked me what i'll do when i get my freedom. i don't deal in fantasy that much. it will be hard. don't forget it may be as long as 10 years before i get this monkey off my back. and that's a lot to make up for as i have eight years or more done already.''
i have land in five states. most of it is where i don't want to live _ florida, arizona, illinois, wisconsin and minnesota. hey, you want to live on an island? i think that would be great
if you got mad at someone, they couldn't get away from you.''
in another letter quoted in sunday's editions, gacy had more to say about what he would do if free
i am being sued for $697 million right now. start paying that off,'' he wrote. ``the numbers don't mean a thing, as they can have it all. just give me my freedom. i'll make what i need so fast anyway as i have a knack for making money
i already told you what kind of house i am going to build. ... i am going to make it a halfway house for horny girls and party my butt off in orgies. can you dig it?'' many of the boys and young men gacy is convicted of killing had been sexually molested before they died, prosecutors said
_gacy says he has no affection for britain's queen elizabeth
i can't stand royalty. when people are starving, we have these sissy types wasting money. ... since when do you bow to another human being? they are no better than you.''
in another letter, gacy writes, ``it doesn't always pay to be good to people, even family.''
ms. terry could not be reached for comment by telephone saturday; there is no telephone listing for her in centralia
marvin ziporyn, a chicago forensic psychiatrist who analyzed the letters for the newspaper, said they give a clear understanding of gacy's personality
he doesn't discuss the (murder) case in the letters, but they show the mechanics of his personality like what makes a watch tick,'' ziporyn said
i think what's important is that he's `john wayne' gacy. john wayne like the movie star, and his trying to live up to that image is an important part of his personality,'' ziporyn said. address</head>
some michigan state university trustees are questioning plans for the rev. jesse jackson to deliver the university's winter commencement address two weeks before the state's democratic caucuses
opponents have said that allowing jackson to speak would break a 71-year-old tradition. since 1917, no candidate for public office has addressed michigan state graduates
joel ferguson, a trustee who also is jackson's michigan campaign director, said jackson was scheduled to deliver the march 12 address before declaring he would seek the democratic presidential nomination
michigan democrats will hold their caucuses march 26
ferguson said the speech would be non-political, something other trustees doubted
there's absolutely no way he can write a speech that doesn't look and sound presidential,'' trustee thomas reed said. ``even when he comes here and talks about his grandmother, it will have some political overtones.''
trustee kathy wilbur called on the michigan state to adopt a rule to prevent presidential candidates from making commencement addresses at the university
michigan state president john dibiaggio has supported jackson's selection as the winter commencement speaker
we wanted to have the rev. jackson because he is a distinguished leader, a humanitarian ... a positive role model for minorities and others,'' dibiaggio said. ``there's a great deal of enthusiasm among the student body.''
but dibiaggio added that banning candidates from speaking ``has some legitimacy.''
several notable politicians have given commencement addresses at michigan state, including then-vice president richard nixon in 1957 and former president harry s. truman in 1960, but none was running for office at the time. authorities annoucing two arrests, one suspect freed on recognizance, picking up 22nd graf, `the gunman...'.</note>
a ku klux klan group's protest of the dallas police department's new affirmative action hiring plan turned into a melee saturday when an anti-kkk group charged the hooded klansmen and other white supremacists
police clubbed members of the crowd of about 200 and some protesters sustained minor injuries, authorities said. eight people were arrested on minor charges, police said
members of the anti-kkk group held a rally and burned confederate and nazi flags in front of city hall, where about a dozen klansmen had gathered to stage a news conference against the affirmative action plan
members of the placard-carrying anti-kkk crowd surrounded the klansmen and shouted ``go away. ... dallas doesn't want you. we don't want you.''
as the klan marched around city hall plaza, an elderly black woman was punched in the face by a white man, who was arrested for aggravated assault
that was the worst thing. we put him right in jail. i don't know why he did it but it certainly instigated a few tempers to pop,'' said deputy chief r.l. schifelbein
the anti-klan protesters threw bottles and horse manure at the klansmen as tactical squad police armed with clubs and mounted officers tried to ring the hooded men and keep the crowd back. police dogs converged on the scene as officers tried to break up the feuding factions
skirmishes erupted several times during the one-hour confrontation, with opponents in the crowd spitting on each other
klansmen seeking to escape the hostile crowd squeezed into cars and tried to leave the scene. as they were attempting to flee, an officer hit one anti-klan demonstrator in the stomach with a club
some of the demonstrators apparently resented police protection of the klan and shouted ``cops kill the people!'' one man yelled ``shoot a cop!''
the demonstration also drew a group of ``skinheads,'' or white supremacists with shaven heads.the skinheads usually remained outside the ring of police protection, and it was between this group and the crowd that most of the fights and pushing occurred
the rev. leonard charles stovall led the anti-klan crowd in prayer after the melee. speaking of police, he said, ``lord help them be responsible to everybody.''
schifelbein said the klansmen came from connecticut
we did not invite them. we don't want that kind of support. we want the support of the people of dallas and not some idiot from connecticut,'' he said
the news conference was scheduled by a man who identified himself as david white, of the invisible empire, knights of the ku klux klan based in shelton, conn
the city council implemented the affirmative action hiring plan earlier this year in response to critics' charges that the police department did not reflect the city's racial makeup
racial tension in dallas increased in recent weeks after the fatal shootings of three police officers and four other men who were shot by police
the most controversial shooting was the death of white officer john glenn chase, who was killed by a mentally ill, black transient who grabbed his gun and then shot him while a street-corner crowd watched and some witnesses allegedly shouted ``shoot, shoot!'' the transient was later killed by police
after that shooting, police chief billy prince said criticism of the department by minority elected officials had fostered an environment of ill-will between the minority community and police
critics of the police have blasted the department, saying officers are too trigger happy when confronting minorities. criticism of the department also led to a congressional hearing last spring
the latest shooting occurred friday, when off-duty officer gary d. mccarthy, 33, was gunned down during an attempted robbery at a grocery store where he was moonlighting as a security guard
saturday evening, police announced two arrests, and said one of the two men had late been released on personal recognizance bond. they gave few details, declining to name the suspects or give charges against them
the gunman was black and the victim white, but prince said he didn't think the shooting was racially motivated
the problem is we have too many people on the streets who should be in the penitentiary,'' the chief said. ``there are too many people on the streets who are mean.'' update with robertson peace offering to bush. picks up 9th graf pvs, `meanwhile, there ...'</note>
presidential candidate pat robertson said he made a stop at a baton rouge airport saturday to support fellow evangelist jimmy swaggart because ``in christianity we don't shoot our wounded.''
swaggart, who stepped down from his television pulpit feb. 21 after tearfully admitting to an unspecified sin, reportedly paid a prostitute to pose naked and tried to make a deal with a preacher who confronted him about it
robertson said swaggart was in seclusion at his walled family compound _ routinely guarded by security officers _ and the two felt a personal visit to the home ``would expose him to further unneeded scrutiny by the press.''
robertson's brief airport appearance came while he was en route to huntsville, ala., from houston
the republican candidate said he had talked twice by phone to swaggart on saturday. ``i told him i want to see him soon restored to his pulpit and continue again his magnificent work.''
i am not one who is going to get involved between the assemblies of god, which i admire and appreciate, or jimmy swaggart. that is an inner-church matter,'' robertson, a southern baptist, said when asked if he was urging the assemblies of god to go light on any punishment
louisiana officials of the assemblies of god recommended barring swaggart from preaching for three months, but officials at the group's national headquarters sent the recommendation back, asking for reconsideration
a person is forgiven when he asks for it,'' said robertson. ``in my estimation, god has forgiven him. i just wanted to symbolically put my arm around him and say, `brother, i love you and i am here to tell the world.'''
robertson also made a peace offering to vice president george bush, a fellow gop presidential contender
while we're in an attitude of reconciliation, i think it might be appropriate to ask for reconciliation between me and george bush,'' robertson said when asked if he felt bush had anything to do with disclosures about swaggart. ``i don't wish to have any confusion or animosity between us.''
robertson charged earlier in the week that the disclosures about swaggart and the prostitute were timed to hurt his campaign. he offered no proof, and declined to say who he thought was behind the disclosures. however, in the same interview he accused bush's campaign of ``dirty politics'' and ``trickery'' directed at him
meanwhile, there was no indication when assemblies of god officials in louisiana might submit new punishment proposals for swaggart
i would not have any comment on that. i'm sorry, you know. i just don't have any comment,'' the rev. cecil janway, district superintendent of the church's louisiana district council, said saturday
neither the church nor marvin gorman, the defrocked assemblies of god minister who reportedly confronted swaggart with photographs documenting his indiscretions, has said exactly what they were
but admitted prostitute debra murphree claims swaggart paid her to pose naked and talk dirty to him, but did not have intercourse
she tried to sell her story to the national enquirer for $100,000, but the tabloid rejected her offer after she failed a lie detector test, senior editor paul levy said friday. murphree told wvue-tv on friday that nervousness, drug use and inability to remember some of the questions caused that failure
before the pictures were given to church officials, swaggart offered to help gorman return to the assemblies of god and to have gorman appear on his television show, according to unidentified sources quoted in saturday's editions of the times-picayune in new orleans
gorman, who claimed in a $90 million lawsuit against swaggart and 13 others that swaggart destroyed his ministry by spreading false rumors of numerous adulterous affairs, refused to comment on the report. so did officials at jimmy swaggart ministries in baton rouge
the sources, which the newspaper described as close to gorman, said gorman told swaggart he wasn't especially interested in either offer and gave swaggart four months to deal with his personal problems
there were no strings,'' one source told the newspaper. ``swaggart knew that gorman had photographic proof of his indiscretion but gorman was leaving it up to swaggart to figure out how to deal with it. gorman did not dictate how swaggart should deal with it.''
the newspaper quoted its sources as saying that swaggart appeared truly repentant, and gorman left the meeting satisfied that swaggart was ready to seek the counsel of church elders and accept their advice
gorman wrote swaggart early this month to remind him of the deadline, the newspaper said, but when there was no response people close to gorman gave the photographs to national assemblies of god leaders in springfield, mo
those leaders forbade officials and ministers to talk about the proposed punishment, when a decision might be reached, or anything else about the matter
f.c. chamberlain, a louisiana presbyter who said friday that it was swaggart's complete confession _ not favoritism _ that prompted a recommendation for an unusually short three-month suspension, had no comment saturday
calls to other members of the district council either were not answered or were not returned
the council recommended monday that swaggart undergo two years of rehabilitation and counseling, starting with a three-month suspension from preaching in this country
cbs news, without citing any sources, reported that the church's executive presbytery in springfield told leaders of the louisiana district to order swaggart to step down for a year. the church's general superintendent, g. raymond carlson, refused to say what penalty was recommended
