lula e. ``tiny'' oslund, a former silent screen star known as blanche sweet when she played confident and determined heroines for filmmaker d.w. griffith, has died. she was 92
mrs. oslund's ashes were scattered in the pacific ocean off honolulu following private services friday, the day after she died at home
born in geneseo, ill., in 1895, mrs. oslund began making films while still in her teens. ``the lonedale operator'' (1911) and ``judith of bethulia'' (1913) were two of the films she made with griffith
mrs. oslund went on to work with several other directors, starring in such movies as ``anna christie'' (1923) and ``tess of the d'urbervilles'' (1924)
she made only four movies after the silent era ended, including a bit part in the 1959 danny kaye film ``the five pennies.''
mrs. oslund and her son, wilman f. oslund, moved to hawaii in 1983 from abilene, texas
she also is survived by a sister, vila o. miller, and two grandchildren
a judge ordered the winner of a $1.8 million lottery jackpot to pay half the prize to his former live-in girlfriend
ingham county circuit judge peter houk upheld a claim friday by carolyn eeles of westland that she and her ex-boyfriend, james w. renfro, had an oral agreement to share any winnings from the michigan lotto tickets they bought dec. 18, 1985
one of those tickets turned out to be the jackpot winner. but eeles' lawyer, karl nickolai, said renfro returned to his estranged wife less than two days after claiming all the prize money and then moved to tennessee
houk said renfro testified during the trial that he bought the lotto tickets himself. but the judge said 17 other witnesses contradicted renfro's testimony, including some who vouched for eeles' claim that she and renfro each paid $5 for 10 tickets and that eeles herself picked the winning numbers
renfro was ordered to pay eeles half of the first two after-tax installments, worth about $74,000 each, that he has collected. houk also ordered that eeles receive half of the remaining 18 payments and interest on the first two installments, and that renfro pay her lawyer's fees
i'm thrilled _ there is justice in this land,'' eeles, 43, said afterward. renfro, 48, said the witnesses ``weren't telling the truth.'' with details of luncheon, media reception. picks up 23rd graf pvs, `the royal ...'; should stand for ams.</note>
britain's prince andrew and his wife, sarah, began their official 10-day southern california visit saturday in a typical freeway traffic jam that delayed their arrival at a city hall welcoming ceremony by 25 minutes
the car carrying the duke and duchess of york had to take a detour around the jam on the trip from the royal yacht britannia, moored in long beach, 25 miles south of downtown los angeles. the traffic snarl was caused by an accident on the santa monica freeway
when the royal couple arrived at city hall, they were cheered by about 1,000 people, some of them waving british flags, and mayor tom bradley welcomed them in the city council chambers. the day's events saturday also included visits to chinatown and a school for the performing arts
andrew and sarah were in town to launch uk-la '88, a three-month celebration of british culture and commercial achievement
the united kingdom has sent the diversity of its cultural life to share with us,'' bradley told them. ``we count it a very special honor that you have joined us on this occasion.''
andrew stressed the couple's participation in launching uk-la '88, which he described as an ``ambitious, cultural collaborative venture'' between los angeles and british art groups
during their stay, andrew and sarah are expected to attend a number of the festival's 60 cultural events featuring british and american artists
noting that he and his wife will visit the aircraft carrier uss nimitz at sea during their visit, the prince cited common military obligations shared by the two nations around the world
for us, our visit to one of your ships will remind us of those many parts of the world in central europe, in the persian gulf and elsewhere in which your armed forces and ours stand side by side in common defense or our shared democratic values,'' said the prince, a royal navy helicopter pilot
the city hall reception featured songs by los lobos, an east los angeles group that gave its musical bounce to last year's hit film about ritchie valens, who died in a 1959 plane crash with rock legend buddy holly
los lobos performed two songs, including the rollicking spanish song that valens immortalized, ``la bamba,'' from which last year's movie title was taken. sarah, 28, who is expected the couple's first child in august, kept time with her left heel
after the city hall welcome, the royal pair toured nearby chinatown under light rain
sandy wong, a chinatown resident originally from hong kong, said people who hail from that british colony have a special affection for the royal couple, and she confessed to being particularly impressed by andrew
he's really better looking than the pictures,'' said mrs. wong, 49
the royal couple applauded politely during a performance by elementary school students in a small square. the boys performed a lion dance and the girls a parasol dance
the next stop was a quick visit to the 32nd street school, a ``magnet'' school for performing arts, where the couple was treated to dance performances, jazz music and skits
well done,'' sarah told the young dancers and musicians before the couple sat in on a medieval history lesson to discuss life in a castle
one student asked if there were still dungeons in windsor castle, the official residence of the british ruling family
there used to be dungeons in one part of the castle, andrew responded, but ``there is no use for dungeons nowadays, so they've been brought up to date _ they're now a disco.''
another student asked about the most important responsibility of being a duchess
hope you've got a pad and pencil,'' sarah quipped, then added, ``oh, my husband. he comes first and then my life.''
as a parting gift, students gave the couple three school t-shirts _ one baby-size. the couple's first child is due in august
for lunch, the duke and duchess dined on smoked quail and grilled pacific salmon in a restaurant atop a downtown high-rise. the luncheon crowd was dotted with show business personalities, including ed begley jr. of television's ``st. elsewhere'' and singer marilyn mccoo, host of the ``solid gold'' rock music tv show. later, there was an off-the-record reception for news media representatives on the royal yacht
the royal couple flew in from london on friday afternoon, arriving to spring-like weather five years to the day after the start of a similar tour by andrew's parents, queen elizabeth ii and prince philip, that was marred by rough weather
security personnel experienced some tense moments friday when they discovered a suspicious-looking briefcase about a block from where the yacht britannia was docked. a state department bomb unit blew it up
it was no bomb,'' said a british consulate spokeswoman who did not want her name used. weerst, picking up 6th graf, `they were...'.</note>
four children and their baby sitter were killed by carbon monoxide fumes from a faulty gas heater, officials said saturday
ola weerts and a friend had left the children with a baby sitter friday night and went to dinner
they came back and checked about 9:30 p.m., left again and arrived shortly before midnight and found the majority of them dead,'' said clay county sheriff's lt. tim martin
pronounced dead at mrs. weerts' home here were two of her three children, 10-year-old james and 6-year-old sherri. her friend's granddaughter, julie meador, 10, and baby sitter jennifer bias, 17, were also dead, martin said
the third weerts child, 12-year-old tanya, died saturday evening at shands hospital in nearby gainesville
they were all in their beds, apparently sleeping, except for one 10-year-old on the kitchen floor,'' martin said. ms. bias was found on a living room sofa
it's absolutely the worst multiple death case in one family that we've had in clay county,'' martin said
an autopsy on tanya was scheduled for sunday. autopsies on the others showed they died of acute carbon monoxide poisoning, authorities said
a normal carbon monoxide level was 1 to 2 percent, caused by pollutants like ozone,'' martin said. ``smokers have higher level, maybe 10 percent.''
the four kids had an average of 65 percent,'' he said
ultimately, what has happened was, we feel, a faulty exhaust on a gas furnace became clogged and the carbon monoxide fumes were allowed to back up and disperse through the house,'' martin said
composer, pianist and musical arranger gene vincent de paul, whose collaboration with lyricist don raye on ``pigfoot pete'' got them an oscar nomination, died saturday after a lengthy illness, his daughter said
de paul, who was 68 and had been suffering from a brain tumor, died at his suburban northridge home, daughter april leach said
he often collaborated with raye, and the two were nominated for an academy award in 1942 for the song ``pigfoot pete'' from the film ``hellzapoppin.''
de paul worked with johnny mercer on music for the 1954 film ``seven brides for seven brothers'' and the broadway play, ``l'il abner.'' de paul also worked on the music for the walt disney film, ``the legend of sleepy hollow,'' ms. leach said
de paul was inducted into the songwriters' hall of fame in 1985, ms. leach said. he was born in new york on june 17, 1919
he's had his music recorded from everybody from big bands to phoebe snow and stevie wonder,'' ms. leach said. ``the judds' latest album has one of his songs on it.''
among his biggest hits were ``cow cow boogie,'' ``star eyes,'' ``irresistible,'' ``when you're in love'' and ``mr. five by five.''
he is survived by his daughter, three sons and two grandchildren. a funeral was tentatively planned for thursday, ms. leach said.   
president reagan intends to nominate jill e. kent to be an assistant secretary of treasury for management, the white house said friday
ms. kent, a native of detroit, would succeed john f. w. rogers in the treasury department post
since 1985, ms. kent has been principal deputy assistant secretary for finance and management at the treasury department. before that she was chief of the treasury and general services branch at the office of management and budget
she was acting chief of legislative reference at the department of health and human services from 1978-80
ms. kent graduated from the university of michigan in 1970 and george washington university law school in 1975
senegal's violence-marred electioneering ended friday with president abdou diouf, the heavy favorite, making a final campaign speech before an overflow crowd at the 30,000-seat demba diop sports stadium
diouf was expected to be re-elected and retain his socialist party's majority in the national assembly in elections sunday
four presidential candidates and six of senegal's 17 registered political parties were to contest the multiparty presidential and national assembly elections
a crowd estimated at more than 10,000 went to senegal's independence monument in this capital city friday to attend a final rally for the main opposition candidate, abdoulaye wade, and his senegalese democratic party
security was increased following two days of violence in thies, 42 miles northeast of dakar. truckloads of members of the military intervention group were stationed along dakar's streets
the riot police were deployed against democratic party supporters in two days of running battles in thies, after the government barred a rally by wade's party in the town's main square. troops used tear gas, rubber bullets and truncheons to scatter groups of stone-throwing youths
some democrats claimed more than 100 people, including eight local party officials, were arrested. government official did not comment on the allegations
diouf denounced his opponents, primarily wade, at a rally friday morning in thies at the place de france, site of the earlier clashes
in light of the events of yesterday, i am ashamed of senegal,'' said diouf. ``i thought i was facing men who thought as i did .... unfortunately, these men are men of subversion.''
a socialist party spokesman refused to comment when asked why diouf was allowed to speak in thies while then opposition rally was barred
most of those who fought the riot forces were teen-agers
brawling began thursday
by friday, the youths had armed themselves with sticks and wore motorcycle helmets in preparation for street fighting. during diouf's 10-minute address in thies, the concussion of exploding tear gas canisters could be heard in the surrounding neighborhood. the level of violence friday appeared less intense than the day before, though minor injuries were reported
the socialists were expected to lose some of their 111 seats in the 120-member assembly sunday, although the 52-year-old diouf was expected to win easy re-election to a second five-year term
he has led senegal since 1981, when the nation's first president, leopold sedar senghor, retired. diouf won the 1983 elections with 83.5 percent of the vote to wade's 14.79 percent. three other candidates shared the rest. wade accused diouf's party of rigging the elections, a charge the president denied
wade, 61, a lawyer and three-time presidential candidate, accuses diouf of selling out the country to western creditors and foreign businessmen
wade threatened to turn his party into ``a liberation movement'' if he considered this election to have been rigged
two million of senegal's estimated 7 million people are registered to vote
hungary and the soviet union pledged friendship and support for each other friday as a five-day visit by soviet president andrei gromyko drew to a close
and according to an unexpected announcement by both countries, the hungarian writers' union, which a year ago ran into political trouble after it rejected conservatives in its leadership, signed a working agreement with the soviet writers' union
the friendship pledge came in a final communique signed by gromyko and president karoly nemeth of hungary
gromyko is to return to moscow on saturday, ending his first foreign state visit since assuming the presidency in 1985
the agreement between the writers' unions means they will cooperate in publishing books, exchange visits and sponsor exchanges of students and critics
we are ahead of you'' in terms of glasnost, or openness, viktor karpov, head of the soviet writer's union, chided his hungarian audience at a news conference
earlier, in an interview with a hungarian newspaper, karpov noted that the hungarian writer's union ``has successfully put behind it the difficulties that had arisen within it.''
last year, more than 25 communist party loyalists left the association of about 600 members. culture minister bela koepeczi said the union no longer represented hungary's literary sector after writers chose to elect an independent board, rejecting board members favored by the party
the state then authorized formation of a guild of writers, poets and translators
the head of the hungarian union, tibor cseres, said friday that in the end a ``compromise was reached and neither side had to yield its basic ground.''
he said the compromise made possible the agreement with the soviet writers' union. 24, are asked to use the following story.</note>
the associated press reported erroneously wednesday that southern cross ranch, where scenes for the television show ``dallas'' have been shot, was recently appraised at $61.5 million
the 455-acre ranch, which is to be auctioned march 12, was appraised at $6.15 million
the museum of modern art's director has resigned because of protests about an exhibition in which a printed face of marilyn monroe was imposed on an image of the virgin of guadalupe, patron saint of mexico
more than 100 artists and intellectuals issued a statement friday expressing ``profound indignation'' and demanded reinstatement of jorge alberto manrique
they blamed his resignation on ``the pressure exerted by reactionary groups'' and said ``the director of a museum cannot .. . be raised to be the censor of any work of art,'' the liberal newspaper la jornada reported
the government, which runs the museum, requested manrique's resignation thursday and he complied
on jan. 23, about 1,000 people chanting ``long live christ the king!'' stormed the museum in the chapultepec park and forced the management to close an exhibit called ``alternative spaces'' by rolando de la rosa, 36
he had superimposed the face of the late actress marilyn monroe on an image of the virgin of guadalupe, an object of reverence in mexico where 90 percent of the 80 million citizens are roman catholic
in another work, styled after leonardo da vinci's ``last supper,'' jesus christ had the face of the late mexican actor and singer pedro infante. in ``la sagrada familia'' the baby jesus was replaced by a soccer ball
pro-vida, the group that organized the museum assault, demanded the resignations of manrique and martin reyes vayssade, undersecretary of culture. it also demanded de la rosa be hospitalized for ``social re-education.''
manrique was the only official of the government's fine arts institute, which runs the museum, to condemn the closing of the exhibition, la jornada said
it quoted him as calling for legal action against the protesters, whom he described as ``neo-fascists with clear political objectives.''
inevitably this decision will be interpreted as a pat on the back for the attackers of museums,'' the newspaper quoted him as saying about the forced resignation
earlier, manrique told the weekly magazine proceso: ``to say the mexican people were offended (by the art) is a big lie and absurd.'' no pickup. adds byline.</note>
actress tracy scoggins was attacked in a hotel elevator while in town to serve as a co-host of the miss usa pageant, police said friday
miss scoggins, who played monica colby in the abc series ``the colbys,'' suffered bruises in the attack thursday night, said police lt. j.r. grijalva. she did not require medical attention
antonio garcia, 35, was charged with attempted sexual assault and released on $100 bail set by adolfo romero, an associate magistrate, grijalva said
miss scoggins expressed outrage at what she considered low bail
what that says to me is that a man like this can save himself a whole expensive night of dinner and dancing and just pay $100 to assault the woman of his choice,'' she said. ``that's a pretty good deal.''
romero was not in his office late friday
police said garcia had followed miss scoggins to the marriott hotel, where she was staying, and into the elevator
he pulled down the front of her evening gown and attempted to sexually assault her,'' grijalva said. ``she was able to fight him off, and when the door opened, she was able to get out and call for help.''
hotel guests pulled the man out of the elevator and subdued him until hotel security and police arrived, grijalva said
miss scoggins was attacked after returning from a taping of the evening gown and swimsuit competitions
the 51 contestants have been staying in another hotel. miss usa will be crowned tuesday night in a nationally broadcast pageant
a special court convicted and sentenced five people friday for three armed robberies in 1983 designed to help finance the left-wing terrorist group direct action
the sentences _ life imprisonment for one defendent and 13 years for each of the four others _ ended a two-week series of trials of suspected direct action members
a sixth defendant was given a suspended sentence
regis schleicher, 31, was given a life sentence and prosecutor daniel barreyre called him ``a commando chief who shoots like a professional, the most dangerous of the group.''
police considered schleicher a founding member of direct action. the terrorist group has asserted responsibility for numerous bombings, the 1986 fatal shooting of renault president georges besse and the 1985 killing of french gen. rene audran
barreyre had asked for 20-year prison terms for each of the other four: jean-marc rouillan, 35, on his 88th day of a hunger strike; vincenzo spano, 31; nicolas halfen, 24, and his brother, claude, 32
the sixth defendant, frederique germain, 31, cooperated with police and received a five-year suspended prison term
a seven-judge court deliberated just over two hours before handing down the convictions and sentences
the six were convicted of robbing two banks and a jewelry shop in 1983. the holdups netted about $100,000, police said
in one robbery, two policemen were wounded and a member of the gang was killed in a gun fight
rouillan began a hunger strike dec. 1, along with three other suspected direct action members, to protest being kept in isolation in prison
on thursday, france's human rights minister, claude malhuret, said the hunger strike campaign ``plays on the humanitarian sentiments of the french people and must be stopped.''
he said that despite their confinement, the defendants had the right to daily walks, to receive newspapers, listen to the radio and receive visits from family members, lawyers and doctors
the defendents were arrested by police feb. 21, 1987, at a loire valley farm. authorities said direct action terrorist activities ended with the arrests
the three other people on hunger strike are suspected of being direct action leaders. in previous trials, seven suspected direct action members were convicted on various lesser charges and given prison sentences
seven latin american countries asked the united states friday to halt all aid to the rebels fighting nicaragua's leftist government
the foreign ministers of argentina, brazil, colombia, mexico, peru, uruguay and venezuela also signed a declaration calling for a united nations agreement to fight drug trafficking
several foreign ministers indirectly criticized panama's military strongman, gen. manuel antonio noriega, after noriega's allies deposed civilian president eric arturo delvalle early friday
the nations are members of the group of eight, formed last year to assist central american peace efforts. the group ended its three-day meeting in cartagena friday
panama, the eighth member, was not represented after foreign minister jorge abadia left cartagena thursday night because of the political crisis
the group's formal declaration made no mention of the panamanian turmoil, which began thursday when delvalle ordered noriega to step down from his post as military chief and noriega refused
but foreign minister german nava carrillo of venezuela made an indirect reference to noriega, saying that in a democracy ``the military must be obedient to civilian power.''
foreign minister julio londono paredes of colombia, who did not mention panama specifically, said democracy has suffered a blow in latin america
the ministers' statement recognized ``the value of the contribution to the peace process'' that president oscar arias of costa rica made with a peace plan signed last aug. 7 by the five central american presidents
but the statement said fighting continues, countries are building up armaments and ``destabilizing actions and violations of international rights'' occur
sources close to the foreign ministers told the associated press that the reference to destabilizing actions and violations of international rights was a reference to u.s. aid to the nicaraguan rebels known as contras
the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the ministers expressed concern in their talks about alleged cuban support of salvadoran rebels. but the final declaration made no mention of cuban involvement in central america
according to u.s. officials, there are some 8,000 soviet bloc and cuban personnel in nicaragua, including about 3,500 military and secret police. more than 40,000 people have been killed in the 6-year-old civil war
el salvador claims that cuba is supporting salvadoran rebels with aid coming through nicaragua
referring to negotiations between the nicaraguan government and nicaraguan rebels, the formal statement said that for the talks to succeed there must be no interference from outside central america
the statement urged developed nations to contribute emergency aid to central american countries
president raul alfonsin said friday that agricultural subsidies by the united states and the european economic community have cost argentina $12 billion since 1980
you have forgotten the developing world,'' alfonsin told the cairns group of 14 food-exporting nations on the last day of a three-day meeting
the agricultural subsidies create economic and social unrest that endangers the political stability of some countries, alfonsin said
alfonsin criticized trade proposals by the united states and european common market countries to begin reducing farm subsidies as too little and too late
he said he didn't believe a u.s. proposal to eliminate farm subsidies over 10 years ``can be considered definite,'' and the eec proposal to limit grain production to 160 million tons is about the same grain production figure as last year
the cairns group ``has the central object of eliminating that arsenal of protectionist measures that distorts foreign trade in the field of agriculture,'' the president said
the group takes its name from the australian coastal city where the first ministerial-level meeting of the organization was held in august 1986
it issued a closing declaration outlining its hopes for a strategy to reduce trade protectionism. the declaration will be introduced at the meeting of the general agreement on tariffs and trade group next month
the cairns group also agreed to meet again in december in toronto
also calling for the reduction or elimination of agricultural trade protectionism was grains minister charlie mayer of canada. trade ministers mike moore of new zealand and michael duffy of australia made similar declarations earlier at the meetings
the nations in the cairns group are argentina, australia, brazil, canada, chile, colombia, fiji, hungary, indonesia, malaysia, new zealand, the philippines, thailand and uruguay
only fiji among the 14 did not send a representative to bariloche, a mountain resort 1,000 miles southwest of buenos aires. dayton</head>
minority students occupying a hampshire college office vowed friday to continue the four-day sit-in through the weekend, while university of dayton students held the president's office in a protest against cia recruiting
the hampshire college students were attempting to pressure the private school in amherst, mass., to do more to promote racial harmony
anita fearman, a spokeswoman for the 40 students who took over an office in a dormitory tuesday, said discussions with college president adele simmons have been cordial, but she saw no quick end to the standoff
the students' demands include funding and a full-time coordinator for their activities on behalf of minority students, hiring of an administrator for multicultural affairs, a policy statement condemning racism and amnesty for the protest
the administration has offered us $25,000 to reorganize and make fundamental structural changes in the social fabric of the college,'' ms. fearman said. ``it's going to take a lot more money than that and we know they have the resources.''
simmons has said some of the demands, such as a policy on racial harassment, have been in the works for several months. about 100 of the college's 1,100 students are minorities
in dayton, about 50 members of plowshares for peace and the democratic socialists of america took over the outer office thursday of brother raymond l. fitz, the roman catholic school's president, and demanded a one-year moratorium on cia recruitment
the number had dwindled to 27 by friday, university spokeswoman teri rizvi said
the students who remained were charged with disruption under the student conduct code, ms. rizvi said. penalties could range from a fine to expulsion, and will be determined by a student-faculty panel, she said
fitz met with the protesters for 1{ hours friday and said he would discuss their demands with administrators and faculty
schuerman told the protesters later: ``whatever the resolution is, it's not going to hinge on whether you stay here or leave.''
last week, students at the university of massachusetts occupied a building for six days to protest racial violence at the campus. the siege ended with an agreement on such demands as increased resources for third world programs
a 79-year-old man was charged with attempted murder friday after he stormed into a retirement home that had evicted him for being a troublemaker and opened fire, wounding four people, police said
william h. ``shorty'' cox was ordered held on $250,000 bond in the shootings. police said cox burst in during a board meeting thursday
he picked out the people he felt had done him wrong and began firing,'' police spokesman dee anderson said
four people suffered minor gunshot wounds and a fifth, willie joe wright, 67, suffered a heart attack and was listed in critical condition friday at arlington memorial hospital
cox had lived in the home for 22 months but was evicted in september for `violent acts,'' including shoving others and using profane language, said sam hilburn, president of the home's board of directors
i heard the rounds going off _ ping, ping, ping _ and saw people ducking,'' said pat wilkinson, an electrician who phoned authorities. ``i was still on the phone when he wandered through the office. he said, `go ahead and call the police ... i don't want to get everything blown out of proportion.'''
the home, which houses 140 people, has no security guards. cox entered the board room, where about 15 people were gathered, with a semiautomatic rifle in his hands and another rifle strung around his neck, police said
he said, `i've got a statement to make,' but rambled incoherently,'' said board member charles smith
cox shot once into the ceiling then ``apparently he selected people and shot at them,'' anderson said. ``it was not random shooting.''
cox surrendered to police in a kitchen at the home, anderson said
cox had sued the home, alleging that he had been wrongfully evicted, but the suit was dismissed, hilburn said. news digest: panama city-panama, a0456; moscow-soviet-missiles, a0438; washington-leap day, a0410; cheltenham-eddie the eagle, a0415.</note>
