judy heckman, chief of pesticide disposal for the u.s. environmental protection agency, hasn't. heckman plans to fly to texas to preside at the burning of the last 330,000 gallons of the pesticide early next week
the edb, or ethylene dibromide, to be incinerated was taken from a warehouse and put on a train in liberty, mo., that left last week for an industrial park in deer park outside houston. more trains will leave with the remaining gallons every monday until june, officials said. news digest: panama city, panama _ panama; tegucigalpa, honduras _ honduras; damascus, syria _ shultz; jerusalem _ israel-violence; nicosia, cyprus _ iran-iraq; eagan, minn. _ northwest strike; undated _ political rdp; atlanta _ democrats debate.</note>
