the value of newly started construction fell 8 percent in january from the previous month, led by a steep drop in non-residential buildings, a construction research concern said sunday
the f.w. dodge division of mcgraw-hill information systems co. said the latest decline continued a downward drift from highs reached last august
the report said the annualized value of new construction contracts fell to $228 billion in january from $247.3 billion in december 1987
on a seasonally adjusted basis, contracts for non-residential building tumbled 16 percent to $75.6 billion, residential construction fell 3 percent to $110.4 billion and public works construction fell 4 percent to $42.0 billion
january's contracting data reinforced the downward trend of new construction activity which has been developing since the fall,'' said george a. christie, vice president and chief economist for f.w. dodge
he said construction contracting has fallen on a month-to-month basis in three of the past five months since reaching an august peak of $273.1 billion
contracting for new construction is viewed as a leading indicator of spending and employment throughout the construction industry
christie said a decline in january's contracting for non-residential buildings reflected a bigger than expected decline in the commercial construction market
it's been a tough winter especially throughout the south where starts were weak, so part of january's steep fall may have been weather related,'' he said. he said he expected non-residential contracting ``will be ratcheting its way down over the rest of 1988.''
non-residential construction also includes buildings for industrial, manufacturing, educational, religious and recreational puposes
the decline in residential contracting reflected stability in one-family home building and continued declines for apartments and hotels, the report said. dodge expects total housing starts will fall 5 percent in all of 1988 to 1.525 million units
the drop in contracting for public works projects and other ``non-building'' construction reflected a stabilization in highway and bridge construction
that figure also includes contruction of dams, sewage and water supply systems, airports and utility and communication systems
the poker-faced federal reserve let the public peek at some of its cards this past week by providing specific clues as to how monetary policy was being played out lately
manuel h. johnson, vice chairman of the fed, confirmed that the central bank was paying closer attention to fluctuations in the dollar, commodity prices and the interest-rate yield curve, or the difference in long- and short-term rates
fed policy in recent years had involved watching a greater variety of economic measures, such as the money supply, which includes cash in circulation, checking and savings accounts and money market accounts
while most fed watchers had been aware of this change in direction for some time _ seeing hints, for example, in minutes of policy committee meetings or from central bank governors _ they were heartened by the fact the fed made this information available to the public
god bless johnson ... because we can all start thinking the same way,'' said william v. sullivan, director of money market research for dean witter reynolds inc. ``the fed has operated in a cloak of secrecy.''
he said ``the new regime seems to be more open'' under chairman alan greenspan than it was under paul a. volcker, who left office last summer
the fed enjoys a certain amount of secrecy,'' said f. ward mccarthy, chief financial economist for merrill lynch capital markets. ``the less the public knows ... the easier it is for it to do its job
but i don't think it's always intentional. i think for a period of time they couldn't decide exactly what was driving monetary policy.''
at a conference sponsored by the cato institute in washington, johnson noted that the relationship between the money supply and the economy has become less predictable in recent years. he admitted that as a result there was always a mystery about what numbers the fed was watching, and that was unhealthy for the credit markets
the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the yield-curve might not be perfect indicators, johnson said, but together they provide a clearer picture of whether the economy is heating up
economists say the fed is likely to keep lowering interest rates to stimulate the economy until the indicators point toward inflation
the credit markets have been closely tracking those same indicators for some time, pushing interest rates higher at the sign of rising inflation and lower with sluggish economic growth
this reaffirms the perception that the markets are the ultimate critic of monetary policy,'' said mccarthy
johnson's remarks this past week means the fed and the credit markets are on the same wavelength, said maria f. ramirez, a top economist at drexel burnham lambert inc., and they also provide a clearer indication as to where rates might be heading
this could reduce volatility'' in bond prices, said sullivan
but carol a. stone, senior economist for nomura securities inc., said, ``it could mean somewhat more volatility because the markets know the fed is looking at particular things,'' and they might overreact
united autoworkers union local 72 filed a lawsuit friday against chrysler corp., alleging the company is breaking federal laws by pulling auto production from kenosha and putting 5,500 people out of work
in reponse, chrysler said a preliminary review of the suit indicated it was ``without merit.''
the suit, which also names as defendants the city of detroit and the u.s. department of housing and urban development, said chrysler obtained about $50 million in federal grants to modernize its jefferson avenue plant in detroit, said james eggleston, an attorney for the union
he said that when chrysler applied for the federal money, the carmaker said it would make mid-sized trucks at the old jefferson avenue plant to keep jobs there during the modernization of the facility
but now the company plans to shift production of the l-body omni-horizon cars to detroit from kenosha, he said. chrysler announced last month it planned to close the kenosha plant by fall
the lawsuit is trying to prevent the use of federal funds to destroy a community,'' eggleston said
the suit was filed in u.s. district court in milwaukee, and it seeks an injunction to force chrysler to keep its plant in kenosha open while continuing its upgrading of the jefferson avenue plant
in its response, chrysler said, ``our lawyers have not had time to thoroughly examine the complaint but based on a preliminary review the lawsuit is without merit.''
the government money is for the new jefferson facility. no government money will be spent at the old jefferson plant where the l-body (omni-horizon) will be produced,'' chrysler said in the statement
bob berg, spokesman for detroit mayor coleman young, said the city has not received formal notification of the lawsuit and would not comment until it was able to examine the filing
chrysler announced late last month the kenosha plant would close
eggleston said $15 million of the federal money came under the urban development action grant program, which he said cannot be used to transplant jobs from one community to another
the remaining $35 million came under a community development block grant, which eggleston said requires an impact study be done by the federal government and detroit. the suit said that the grant was approved without assessing ``the significant adverse effects on the human environment in kenosha.''
chrysler chairman lee iacocca has offered to divert profits from this year's car sales in wisconsin to create a trust fund for the laid off autoworkers. iacocca also said while the automaker may have raised expectations in wisconsin, it made no promises to keep the kenosha plant open
here are some price trends during the past week:
grains and soybean prices were mostly lower at the chicago board of trade
the contract for delivery of wheat in march settled at $3.15\ a bushel friday, down from $3.22 a week earlier; march corn settled at 2.00} a bushel, up a notch over $2.00{ last friday; march oats settled friday at $1.90\ a bushel, down from $1.91} a week earlier, and march soybeans settled at $6.25{ a bushel, down from $6.31
cattle and hog futures prices were mixed at the chicago mercantile exchange
live cattle for delivery in april settled at 72.55 cents a pound, up from 72.37 cents a week earlier; march feeder cattle were 80.72 cents a pound, down from 83.55 cents last friday; april hogs settled friday at 44.30 cents a pound, compared to 45.50 a week earlier; and march frozen pork bellies dipped to 52.10 cents a pound from 53.67 cents
gold and silver prices retreated at the commodity exchange in new york
april gold settled friday at $431.10 a troy ounce, down from $448 a week earlier; and march silver settled at $6.16 a troy ounce, compared to $6.40 last friday
energy futures prices fell in trading at the new york mercantile exchange
april crude oil settled friday at $15.78 a barrel friday, down from $16.48 a week earlier; april heating oil was 43.37 cents a gallon compared to 45.80 cents last friday; and unleaded gasoline dropped to 45.70 cents a gallon from 46.43 cents
final figures likely will show that texas crude oil production fell about 8 percent during 1987, the texas railroad commission reported friday
commission chairman jim nugent said the state's oil production still is suffering from the effects of the 1986 plunge in world oil prices
texas' oil production decline steepened in 1987. final production numbers should show a drop of 60 million barrels, or about 8 percent, from 1986,'' nugent said
a barrel is equivalent to 42 gallons
nugent said the state's daily production rate fell 80,000 barrels a day between january and december 1987
that's not surprising when you look at the number of wells that have been dropped off production over the last two years,'' he said
between the end of 1985 and the fall of last year, we lost production from some 30,000 stripper wells and more than 9,000 of the better-producing wells,'' nugent said
consumer prices, consumer spending and personal income all rose by 0.3 percent in january, while home sales fell for a third consecutive month
the reports friday left the picture of a u.s. economy experiencing continued moderate inflation and weaker growth in spending by consumers
in the financial markets, the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.64 points to 2,023.21, finishing the week with a net gain of 8.62 points. bond prices edged higher and the dollar slipped slightly
the increase in consumer prices in january was about the same rate of inflation as through 1987, but a large decline in energy costs cloaked hefty increases in many other areas
the advance was equivalent to an annual inflation rate of 4.2 percent, according to labor department analysts. that compares to the 4.4 percent actual rate of inflation posted for 1987 and is also in line with the reagan administration's projection of 4.3 percent inflation for 1988
analysts said that many of the price increases may reflect one-time-only increases timed to coincide with the beginning of the year
there were a lot of price increases that come at the first of the year, but i'm not overly alarmed,'' said lawrence chimerine, chairman of the wefa group, a philadelphia-area forecasting service
but donald ratajczak, a georgia state university economist, called the report ``a bit worrisome.''
in another economic reports friday:
_the commerce department said americans' personal incomes and consumer spending both rose at moderate rates of 0.3 percent in january, less than half the 0.7 gains both posted in december. economists expect weakening consumer spending this year as the economy slows down
the gains were taken as positive signs that consumer spending, while not growing as briskly as it did during the early years of the economic recovery, will at least expand enough this year to keep the economy out of a recession
_a real estate trade group said sales of existing homes fell 3.6 percent in january, the third consecutive monthly decline. the national association of realtors said that sales of existing single-family homes were at their slowest pace since june 1985
the association said that consumer fears raised by the collapse of the stock market in october were partly to blame for the slowdown
oil prices continue to be weighed down by an overwhelming mood of bearishness in the market, analysts say
at the new york mercantile exchange friday, contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude oil, closed at $15.78 per 42-gallon barrel, down 14 cents from thursday
it was the second day in a row that the near-month crude contract closed below $16 since dec. 21, when it settled at $15.16
among march contracts for refined products, wholesale heating oil closed at 45.70 cents a gallon, up 0.48 cent from thursday, while wholesale unleaded gasoline settled at 45.26 cents a gallon, 0.11 cent lower
heating oil was the only bright spot during the day, drawing strong demand because of a perception that inventories are ``relatively low,'' said andrew lebow, an analyst at the shearson lehman hutton inc. securities firm
but he said the prevailing sentiment ``is still bearish,'' adding that he joined other traders in expecting further declines for crude prices next week
john o'dea, manager of international energy futures at dean witter reynolds inc., said his firm shared that view, citing overproduction by opec as ``the overriding issue.''
o'dea said the 13 members of the organization of petroleum exporting countries have been operating on an ``every-man-for-himself'' basis, producing as much oil as necessary for their respective shares of the market, despite slack demand and burgeoning inventories
as a result, he said, this has only increased downward pressure on prices
